\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|34.64% ''1,534''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''64.59%''' ''2,860''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|0.77% ''34''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[1984 United States presidential election|1984]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|29.26% ''1,225''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''70.55%''' ''2,953''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|0.19% ''8''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[1980 United States presidential election|1980]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|25.15% ''985''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''60.73%''' ''2,378''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|14.12% ''553''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[1976 United States presidential election|1976]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|35.52% ''1,220''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''63.78%''' ''2,191''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|0.70% ''24''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[1972 United States presidential election|1972]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|32.87% ''1,009''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''65.21%''' ''2,002''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|1.92% ''59''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[1968 United States presidential election|1968]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|33.66% ''820''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''60.22%''' ''1,467''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|6.12% ''149''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[1964 United States presidential election|1964]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''50.88%''' ''1,011''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|49.12% ''976''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|0.00% ''0''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[1960 United States presidential election|1960]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|30.92% ''569''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''69.08%''' ''1,271''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|0.00% ''0''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[1956 United States presidential election|1956]]\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|24.61% ''392''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''75.39%''' ''1,201''\n|align=\"center\" {{Party shading/Independent}}|0.00% ''0''\n|}\n\nRedding has an [[open town meeting]] form of government. A three-person, popularly elected [[board of selectmen]] performs day-to-day administration of the town, with executive authority vested in the [[first selectman]]. Legislative authority is vested in the Town Meeting. All town residents aged 18 and over who own property worth at least $1,000 can participate in the Town Meeting, which is held on an as{{space}}needed basis.\n\nMunicipal elections are held every odd-numbered year. In addition to the board of selectmen, other elected town positions include the town clerk, treasurer, tax collector, constables, and members of various boards. In 2013, Democrat Julia Pemberton was elected first selectman, replacing Republican Natalie Ketcham who did not run for reelection after holding the position since 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstimes.com/local/article/Pemberton-wins-in-Redding-4958768.php|title=Pemberton wins in Redding|last=Pirro|first=John|date=2013-11-06|website=Danbury NewsTimes|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\nRedding is part of [[Connecticut's 4th congressional district]] and is currently represented by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[U.S. Representative]] [[Jim Himes]].\n\nThe town is included in Connecticut's 26th Senatorial District, held by State Senator [[Will Haskell]], a Democrat. Portions of Redding are in Connecticut's 135th Assembly District, held by State Representative [[Anne Hughes]], a Democrat; and Connecticut's 2nd Assembly District, held by State Representative [[Raghib Allie-Brennan]], a Democrat.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main list|List of people from Redding, Connecticut}}\nIn part due to its relative proximity to New York City,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/redding-twains-last-home-is-proud-of-privacy-1397264537|title=Redding, Twain's Last Home, Is Proud of Privacy|last=Lefkowitz|first=Melanie|date=2014-04-14|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-08-14|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> many famous people have lived in Redding.\n\nActors and directors who have resided in Redding include [[Hope Lange]],<ref name=\"history\" /> [[Barry Levinson]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001469/bio|title=Barry Levinson|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref> [[Jessica Tandy]] and her spouse [[Hume Cronyn]],<ref name=\"history\" /> and [[Christopher Walken]].\n\nArtists who have lived in Redding include [[Dan Beard]], whose illustrations appeared in books authored by Mark Twain;<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web | title=An Impressive List of Individuals Who Have Called Redding Home | website=History of Redding, Connecticut (CT) Past & Present | url=http://www.historyofredding.net/HRfamouspeople.htm | access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref> [[Anna Hyatt Huntington]], who lived on the property that today is [[Collis P. Huntington State Park]];<ref>{{cite book|last=Cullen-DuPont|first=Kathryn|title=Encyclopedia of Women's History in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oIro7MtiFuYC&pg=PA120|date=2014-05-14|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-1033-2|page=120}}</ref> and photographer [[Edward Steichen]], who purchased a farm that he called Umpawaug.<ref name=\"Niven 1997 530\">Niven, Penelope (1997). ''Steichen: A Biography''. New York: Clarkson Potter. {{ISBN|0-517-59373-4}}, p. 530</ref> living there until his death in 1973.<ref name=\"Niven 1997 698\">Niven (1997), p. 698</ref> Steichen's property became Topstone Park,<ref name=\"NYT 1999\">Prevost, Lisa, the ''New York Times'', \"An Upscale Town With Upcountry Style,\" 3 January 1999</ref> open seasonally to this day.<ref name=\"Redding parks\">{{cite web | title=Topstone Park | website=townofreddingct.org | date=2011-06-28 | url=http://www.townofreddingct.org:80/Public_Documents/ReddingCT_ParksRec/facilities/top | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628063755/http://www.townofreddingct.org:80/Public_Documents/ReddingCT_ParksRec/facilities/top | archive-date=2011-06-28 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\nAthletes who have lived in Redding include [[Charlie Morton (pitcher)|Charlie Morton]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Barlow Hall of Fame inducts 19. | website=The Redding Pilot | date=2015-11-30 | url=http://www.thereddingpilot.com/2015/11/30/barlow-hall-of-fame-inducts-19/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324094132/http://www.thereddingpilot.com/2015/11/30/barlow-hall-of-fame-inducts-19/ | archive-date=2017-03-24 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref> a pitcher for the [[Tampa Bay Rays]]; and [[Brooklee Han]], a figure skater who represented Australia in the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in [[Sochi, Russia]].\n\n[[File:Mark Twain's house, front view. - NARA - 516527.tif|left|thumb|Clemens' house, \"Stormfield\", in Redding, Connecticut]]\nAuthors who have lived in Redding include [[Joel Barlow]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Barlow, Joel (1754-1812), businessman, diplomat, and poet | website=American National Biography | date=2017-06-16 | url=https://www.anb.org/view/10.1093/anb/9780198606697.001.0001/anb-9780198606697-e-1600077;jsessionid=4B2728F81E7D6B106D3ACCF0C7C75E1D | access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref> a poet and diplomat, born in town; [[Samuel Clemens]], who in 1908 moved into a mansion dubbed [[Stormfield]] that was built on land located on present-day Mark Twain Lane and lived there until his death in 1910;  [[Howard Fast]];<ref name=\"history\" /> [[Lawrence Kudlow]], author and host of the \"Kudlow and Company\" television program;<ref>{{cite web | title=Larry Kudlow to speak at annual breakfast - The Redding Pilot | website=thereddingpilot.com | date=2014-10-25 | url=http://www.thereddingpilot.com/15825/larry-kudlow-speak-annual-breakfast/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025160355/http://www.thereddingpilot.com/15825/larry-kudlow-speak-annual-breakfast/ | archive-date=2014-10-25 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref> [[Dick Morris]], political consultant and author; [[Flannery O'Connor]] (who wrote her novel ''[[Wise Blood]]'' while a boarder at the home of fellow writer [[Robert Fitzgerald]]);<ref>{{cite web | title=When Flannery O'Connor didn't live here | website=The Ridgefield Press | date=2014-04-30 | url=http://www.theridgefieldpress.com/16949/when-flannery-oconnor-didnt-live-here/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140430024622/http://www.theridgefieldpress.com/16949/when-flannery-oconnor-didnt-live-here/ | archive-date=2014-04-30 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref>, futurist [[Alvin Toffler]]<ref>{{cite news| url= http://westport.dailyvoice.com/neighbors/happy-birthday-to-reddings-alvin-toffler/405405/ | title= Happy Birthday To Redding's Alvin Toffler!| work= Westport Daily Voice| location= Weston, Connecticut| date= October 4, 2013| accessdate= May 4, 2016}}</ref> and economist [[Stuart Chase]], who lived in Redding from 1930 and served on the town's planning commission from 1956 until his death in 1985.<ref>http://stevenlewis.info/gs/Stuart_Chase_bio.htm | Stuart Chase -- A Biography | accessed March 15, 2020</ref>\n\nBusinesspeople who have lived in Redding include [[Alfred Winslow Jones]], credited by some as \"the father\" of the [[hedge fund]] industry.<ref name=\"history\" />\n\nComposers, musicians and singers who have lived in Redding include [[Leonard Bernstein]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Gottlieb|first=Jack|title=Working with Bernstein: A Memoir|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TWXHOCMpM74C&pg=PA33|year=2010|publisher=Amadeus Press|isbn=978-1-57467-186-5|page=33}}</ref> [[Daryl Hall]],<ref name=\"history\" /> [[Jascha Heifetz]],<ref name=\"history\" /> [[Charles Ives]],<ref name=\"history\" />[[Meat Loaf]], [[Derek Piotr]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ctinsider.com/living/ctpost/article/Creamy-chamber-music-from-Redding-composer-13972356.php|title='Creamy chamber music' from Redding composer}}</ref> and [[Mary Travers (Peter, Paul and Mary)|Mary Travers]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/17/arts/music/17travers.html|title=Mary Travers, Singer of Protest Anthems, Dies at 72|last=Grimes|first=William|date=2009-09-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\nRedding was selected as the second best small town by Connecticut Magazine in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.connecticutmag.com/rating-the-towns/rating-the-towns/article_ffbe78c2-09c9-5443-97cf-32877b52989f.html|title=Rating the Towns 2012: 6,500-10,000|date=2012-03-01|website=Connecticut Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref>  It was selected as the fourth best town to live in nationwide by CNNMoney in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/galleries/2009/moneymag/0907/gallery.bplive_6_figure_towns.moneymag/4.html|title=6-figure towns - Redding, CT (4) - Money Magazine|date=2009-07-21|website=money.cnn.com|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n[[Metro-North Railroad]]'s [[Danbury Branch]] has a station at [[Redding (Metro-North station)|West Redding]].<ref>http://as0.mta.info/mnr/stations/station_detail.cfm?key=276 \"Metro North Railroad Home > Stations Redding,\" MTA.com. Retrieved 2014-05-04.</ref> [[Housatonic Area Regional Transit]] provides local bus service.\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/revolutionarysol00grum|title=The revolutionary soldiers of Redding, Connecticut, and the record of their services;|last=Grumman|first=William Edgar|date=1904|publisher=Hartford press: The Case, Lockwood & Brainard company|isbn=|location=|pages=}}\n* {{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/historyofredding1906todd|title=The history of Redding, Connecticut : from its first settlement to the present time|last=Todd|first=Charles Burr|date=1906|publisher=Grafton Press|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Connecticut}}\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Redding (Connecticut)|Redding, Connecticut}}\n*[http://www.townofreddingct.org/ Town of Redding official website]\n*[http://www.townofreddingct.org/Public_Documents/ReddingCT_About/elected List of town elected officials]\n*[http://www.historyofredding.com/ History of Redding]\n*[http://www.er9.org/ Easton Redding Region 9 school district]\n*[http://www.er9.org/jrms/ John Read Middle School]\n*[http://www.marktwainlibrary.org/ Mark Twain Library], the town public library\n*[http://www.hamlethub.com/redding hyperlocal publication about Redding]\n{{Fairfield County, Connecticut}}\n{{Connecticut}}\n{{New York metropolitan area}}\n{{New England}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Redding, Connecticut| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Fairfield County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Towns in the New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:Towns in Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "Casoulman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDisasters:Tightens language.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Redding,_Connecticut"}
{"title_page": "Charles Ingram", "text_new": "{{Other people}}\n{{short description|British fraudster}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Charles Ingram\n| image              = Charles Ingram 1.jpg\n| caption            = Ingram with his wife Diana in 2006\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1963|8|6|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shardlow|Shardlow, Derbyshire]], England\n| occupation         = Novelist, computer repairman, army major\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Diana Ingram<br />|November 1989}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles William Ingram''' (born 6 August 1963) is an English novelist, computer repairman, and former [[British Army]] [[Major (United Kingdom)|major]] who became known for being accused of, and convicted of, cheating on the television [[game show]] ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' in 2001, after winning the maximum prize of one million pounds. Following [[R v Ingram, C., Ingram, D. and Whittock, T.|a lengthy trial]] at Southwark Crown Court, he was convicted on a single count of [[Deception (criminal law)|procuring the execution of a valuable security by deception]].  He was convicted of an unrelated [[insurance fraud]] in 2003, and ordered to resign his commission as a major by the Army Board.\n\n==Early life==\nCharles Ingram was born on 6 August 1963 in [[Shardlow|Shardlow, Derbyshire]], the son of retired [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] wing commander John Ingram<ref>(RAF/39187)</ref> and his wife, theatre set designer Susan. His father's [[Wellington bomber]], operating with 103 Squadron from [[RAF Elsham Wolds]], had been shot down around 20 or 21 September 1941; he was taken as a [[Prisoner of War|POW]], while two of his crew were killed.<ref name=\"thetimesapr03\">{{cite news|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?p=GPS&sw=w&u=wikipedia&v=2.1&id=GALE%7CA99786172&it=r&asid=9b7c7d8914dc6e0c4999a52da0a6d156|title=The major: strategist who flunked simple questions; Profile|date=8 April 2003|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=2 October 2017|page=11|url-access=subscription |via=Academic OneFile}}</ref> Ingram's parents divorced when he was young and he spent most of his education years boarding privately at [[Oswestry School]] in [[Oswestry|Oswestry, Shropshire]].<ref name=\"guardianaug06\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2006/sep/16/moneysupplement4|title=Fame and fortune|last=Walne|first=Toby|date=16 September 2006|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> There he was a member of the [[Combined Cadet Force]] and completed the [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award|Duke of Edinburgh Silver Award]].<ref name=\"thetimesapr03\" /> He went on to obtain a [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] in civil engineering from [[Kingston University]].<ref name=\"guardianaug06\" /> \n\n==Career==\nIn 1986, Ingram trained for the British Army at [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|Sandhurst]] and was commissioned as an officer in the [[Royal Engineers]].<ref name=\":1\">{{London Gazette\n| issue = 52131\n| date = 8 May 1990\n| page = 8819\n| supp = y\n}}</ref> He was promoted to the rank of [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in 1990,<ref name=\":1\" /> and major in 1995.<ref>{{London Gazette\n| issue = 54173\n| date = 2 October 1995\n| pages = 13315\u201313316\n| supp = y\n}}</ref> In 1998, Ingram was sent to [[Banja Luka]] in Bosnia<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/mar/20/broadcasting.uknews|title=Pager claims are rot, major tells court|last=Vasagar|first=Jeevan|date=20 March 2003|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> for six months on United Nations peacekeeping duties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wiltshire/3218325.stm|title=The man behind the scams|date=28 October 2003|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> He graduated from [[Cranfield University]] with a master's degree in corporate management in August 2000.<ref name=\"thetimesapr03\" /> He was ordered by the [[Army Board]] via letter to resign his commission on 20 August 2003 and give up his rank of major.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2003/07/200849163838278691.html|title=Marching orders for Army gameshow cheat|date=24 July 2003|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nSince leaving the Army, Ingram has written two novels: ''The Network'', published on 27 April 2006, and ''Deep Siege'', published on 8 October 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/i/charles-ingram/deep-siege.htm |title=Deep Siege by Charles Ingram |accessdate=17 December 2012 |date=8 October 2007 |work=Fantastic Fiction |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061214/http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/i/charles-ingram/deep-siege.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''==\n===Beginning===\n{{WWTBAM question\n| float    = right\n| value    = \u00a31 million (15 of 15) - No time limit  \n| question = A number one followed by one hundred zeros is known by what name?\n| a        = Googol\n| astyle   = correct\n| b        = Megatron\n| c        = Gigabit\n| d        = Nanomole\n| caption  = Ingram's \u00a31 million question\n}}\nOn 9 and 10 September 2001, Ingram was a contestant on the television game show ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' His wife Diana and her brother Adrian Pollock had previously been contestants on the show, both winning \u00a332,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2823407.stm |title=Major Charles Ingram has been found guilty of cheating his way to the top prize on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=7 April 2003 |work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media |people=[[Martin Bashir]] |year=2003 |title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire: Major Fraud |medium=Television |publisher=ITV |location=London, England}}</ref> The show, presented by [[Chris Tarrant]], was one of the highest-rated in the UK at its peak in 1999; one edition was watched by 19 million viewers, a third of the British population at the time.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/vdqdw9/15-years-of-the-coughing-major-who-wants-to-be-a-millionare|title=That Time a Guy Won 'Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?' by Cheating Terribly |author=Harrison, Angus |date=9 September 2016 |work=[[Vice (magazine)|VICE]]|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIngram practised for about twenty minutes per day on a \"[[Fastest Finger First (Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?)|Fastest Finger First]]\" machine that he constructed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1425308/Millionaire-quiz-major-had-ploy-to-foil-Tarrant.html|title=Millionaire quiz major had ploy to foil Tarrant|last=Woolcock|first=Nicola|date=22 March 2003|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref> By the time recording ended on the first day, Ingram had reached \u00a34,000 and used two of his three \"lifelines\". The production team doubted he would proceed much further when recording resumed, but he went on to win the top prize of \u00a31 million.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ingram flipped between answers erratically, appearing to settle on one answer before suddenly moving to another. For example, when asked who recorded the 2000 [[Craig David]] album ''[[Born to Do It]]'', Ingram said he had \"never heard of\" David and appeared to go for a different option before moving to the correct answer.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe show's production company, [[Celador]], suspended the \u00a31 million payout after they suspected Ingram had cheated. Production staff accused Ingram and his wife of defrauding the show by having an accomplice amongst the waiting contestants, lecturer Tecwen Whittock, who would cough when Ingram read out a correct answer.<ref name=\"Millionaire winner 'unhappy'\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2836937.stm|title=Millionaire winner 'unhappy'|date=10 March 2003|accessdate=13 May 2008|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nTarrant, who drank champagne with the Ingrams in their dressing room, said he was convinced that Ingram was genuine when he signed the \u00a31 million cheque: \"If I thought there was anything wrong, I certainly would not have signed it.\" When asked whether the atmosphere in the dressing room was tense after the show, Tarrant replied: \"No, not at all. They seemed as normal as people who have just won a million pounds would be in the situation.\" However, he said that on his way to the dressing room, \"I had been told there had been quite an unpleasant exchange.\"<ref name=\"scotsman\" /> A member of the crew, Eve Winstanley, testified in court that Ingram seemed \"very unhappy\" for someone who had just won a million pounds.<ref name=\"Millionaire winner 'unhappy'\"/>\n\nIn court, Paul Smith of Celador confirmed that his company had previously produced a television programme involving witnesses in the case, for broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] after the trial. The programme, ''Tonight With Trevor McDonald \u2013 Major Fraud'', was broadcast on ITV on 21 April 2003 (a month after the trial began), and credited with over 17 million viewers. On 9 May 2003 (the day after ''Major Fraud'' aired in the US as a special episode of ''[[Primetime (U.S. TV program)|Primetime]]''), the same channel broadcast another programme on the same topic, entitled ''The Final Answer'', which was credited with over 5 million viewers.\n\n=== Trial ===\nFollowing [[R v Ingram, C., Ingram, D. and Whittock, T.|a trial]] at [[Southwark]] [[Crown Court]] lasting four weeks (including jury deliberation for three-and-a-half days), Ingram, his wife and Whittock were convicted by a majority verdict of \"[[Deception (criminal law)|procuring the execution of a valuable security by deception]]\" on 7 April 2003. Both the Ingrams and Whittock were each given prison sentences [[suspended sentence|suspended]] for two years (the Ingrams were sentenced to eighteen months and Whittock was sentenced to twelve months), each fined \u00a315,000, and each ordered to pay \u00a310,000 towards prosecution costs. Within two months of the verdict and sentence, the trial judge ordered the Ingrams to pay additional defence costs: Charles Ingram \u00a340,000 and Diana Ingram \u00a325,000. Altogether with legal fees, the Ingrams had to pay \u00a3115,000.<ref>{{cite news |title=Charles Ingram transcript |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/charles-ingram-transcript-6967487.html |accessdate=13 January 2019 |work=Evening Standard |date=21 January 2004}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 August 2003, the [[Army Board]] ordered Ingram to resign his commission as a major after 17 years of service, but stated that this would not affect his [[pension]] entitlements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3092357.stm|title=BBC NEWS - UK - Millionaire cheat sacked by Army|website=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May 2004, the [[Court of Appeal]] denied Ingram leave to appeal against his conviction and upheld his sentence, but agreed to quash his wife's fine and prosecution costs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/wiltshire/3728929.stm |title=TV quiz cheat loses his appeal |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=19 May 2004 |work=BBC News}}</ref> On 5 October, the [[House of Lords]] denied Ingram leave to appeal against his fine and prosecution costs, and he appealed to the [[European Court of Human Rights]]. On 20 October, the original trial judge reduced Ingram's defence costs order to \u00a325,000 and Diana's defence costs order to \u00a35,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/wiltshire/3762688.stm |title=Quiz cheat has defence costs cut |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=21 October 2004 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Ingram's defence costs were later further reduced to \u00a35,000 on appeal.\n\nIn 2006, journalist [[Jon Ronson]], who covered the case at the time for ''[[The Guardian (newspaper)|The Guardian]]'', wrote that he believed the Ingrams might be innocent. Ronson, who attended every day of the trial, had observed that when the word \"cough\" was mentioned, pensioners in the public gallery had coughed. [[James Plaskett]], who had appeared on ''Millionaire'' several times before winning \u00a3250,000 in January 2006, argued this was an example of coughs caused by unconscious triggers; Whittock had simply coughed involuntarily when he heard the correct answer. Whittock was also accused of having coughed after Ingram mentioned an incorrect option to his penultimate question and swiftly following that up with a smothered \"No\". However, Plaskett, who had sat in that very same seat, argued that he might have audibly said it in response to an incorrect option in the same way that other waiting contestants have been known to whisper \"No\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/jul/17/couldthewhowantstobeami|title=Are the Millionaire three innocent?|last=Ronson|first=Jon|date=17 July 2006|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 August 2014|location=London}}</ref>\n\n====Recorded evidence====\nIn court, Ingram claimed the videotape of his appearance on ''Millionaire'' was \"unrepresentative of what I heard\", and he continues to assert that it was \"unfairly manipulated\". A video recording, with coughing amplified relative to other sounds including Ingram's and Tarrant's voices, was prepared by Celador's editors (Editworks) for the prosecution and \"for the benefit of the jury\" during the trial (and later for viewers in television broadcasts). Ingram claims that he neither \"listened for, encouraged, nor noticed any coughing\". The prosecution alleged that, of the 192 coughs recorded during his second-night performance, 32 were recorded from the ten Fastest Finger First contestants, and that 19 of the 32 coughs heard on the video tape were \"significant\". The prosecution asserted that these \"significant\" coughs were by Whittock, each falling any time the correct answer had been spoken. During the trial, Tarrant also denied hearing any coughing throughout the episode, claiming he was too busy to notice.<ref name=\"scotsman\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/quizmaster-amazed-to-hear-163-1m-winner-could-have-cheated-1-598995 |title=Quizmaster 'amazed' to hear \u00a31m winner could have cheated |date=13 March 2003 |accessdate=13 May 2008 |location=Edinburgh |work=The Scotsman |first=Karen |last=Mcveigh}}</ref>\n\n====Testimony of Larry Whitehurst====\nLarry Whitehurst, another contestant who had appeared on the show as a Fastest Finger First contestant on four occasions, was adamant that he had known the answers to Ingram's questions. He told the court that he had been able to detect a pattern of coughing, and that he was entirely convinced that coughing had helped Ingram.<ref name=\"BBC News\u2013Coughs\">{{cite news|title=Contestant 'spotted Millionaire coughs'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2839587.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=8 July 2011|date=11 March 2003}}</ref>\n\n====Testimony of Tecwen Whittock====\nWhittock claims to have suffered a persistent cough for his entire life<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/weekend/story/0,3605,938649,00.html |title=So I phoned a friend \u2013 part two |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=19 April 2003 |location=London |work=The Guardian}}</ref> and insisted that he had a genuine cough caused by a combination of [[hay fever]] and a dust [[allergy]], and that it was only coincidence that his throat problem coincided with the right answers.<ref name=\"scotsman_pager\" /> During the trial, however, the jury heard evidence that once Whittock himself earned the right to sit in the hot seat, his throat problems disappeared.<ref name=\"scotsman_pager\" /> Whittock later testified that he drank several glasses of water before he went in front of the cameras.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2888791.stm |title=Cheating 'silly' says Millionaire accused |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=26 March 2003 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Whittock also insisted that he had not known the answers to three of the questions he allegedly helped with. However, the police found the answer to the twelfth question, regarding the artist who painted ''[[The Ambassadors (Holbein)|The Ambassadors]]'', in a hand-written general knowledge book at Whittock's home.<ref name=\"scotsman_pager\">{{cite news |url=http://news.scotsman.com/uk/Pager-plot-too-risky-for.2408136.jp |title=Pager plot too risky for TV quiz |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=7 March 2003 |location=Edinburgh |work=The Scotsman |first=John |last=Innes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022105328/http://www.scotsman.com/news/uk/pager-plot-too-risky-for-tv-quiz-1-548871|archivedate=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nDavies, the floor manager, said that, as soon as the coughing came to his notice during the recording, he decided to find out who was responsible. \"The loudest coughing was coming from Tecwen in seat number three\", he said. \"He was talking to the person to his left when I was observing him, and then he turned towards the set and the hot seat to cough.\" Whittock remarked during the trial that \"you do not cough into someone's face\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portia.org/chapter14/major.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=26 September 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041020172443/http://www.portia.org/chapter14/major.html |archivedate=20 October 2004 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the trial, Whittock portrayed himself as a \"serial quiz show loser\" because he had been eliminated in round one of ''[[Fifteen to One]]'', had also failed on ''The People Versus'' and had been able to win only an atlas on his appearance on ''[[Sale of the Century (UK game show)|Sale of the Century]]''.<ref name=\"scotsman_whittock\">{{cite news |url=http://news.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=788&id=360802003 |title=Lecturer a serial quiz show failure, court is told |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=26 March 2003 |location=Edinburgh |work=The Scotsman|last=Innes|first=John|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030418205015/http://www.news.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?id=360802003&tid=788|archivedate=18 April 2003}}</ref>\n\n==After ''Millionaire''==\n===TV appearances===\nFollowing his appearance on ''Millionaire'', Ingram has appeared on other various TV shows, including ''[[The Games (British TV series)|The Games]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukgameshows.com/ukgs/The_Games|title=The Games|publisher=UK Game Shows|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Weakest Link (British game show)|The Weakest Link]]'', and ''[[Wife Swap (British TV series)|Wife Swap]]'', featuring alongside his wife in the latter two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/3238445.stm|title=Goody and Ingram's celebrity swap|publisher=The BBC|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Insurance fraud case===\nIn late 2003, the Ingram and his wife were charged with further [[fraud]] offences. On 28 October, Ingram was found guilty at [[Bournemouth Crown Court]] of obtaining a pecuniary advantage by deception, and of a second charge of deception, having attempted to claim on an insurance policy after an alleged [[burglary]] at his home. Ingram had failed to tell [[Direct Line]] Insurance about claims he had made in the three years before he took out the policy in July 2001. The court was told that Ingram had been a \"habitual claimant\" with [[Norwich Union]] after suffering \"unfortunate\" losses of private possessions.<ref name=woolcock>{{cite news |last1=Woolcock |first1=Nicola |title='Millionaire' quiz cheat guilty of insurance fraud |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1445354/Millionaire-quiz-cheat-guilty-of-insurance-fraud.html |accessdate=12 September 2018 |work=Daily Telegraph (UK) |date=29 October 2003}}</ref>\n\n[[Christopher Parker]], prosecuting, said Ingram switched insurers to [[Zurich Insurance Group]] in 1997, after Norwich Union reduced a burglary claim from \u00a319,000 to \u00a39,000, and in 2000 switched again to Direct Line. \"He has been ineluctably dishonest\", Parker said. \"He went to Direct Line and didn't make a disclosure about his claims history because he knew he wouldn't have been insured. It might not have started off as the most monstrous piece of villainy but these things tend to snowball and it all came to a sticky end when he claimed for \u00a330,000.\" Staff at Direct Line were already \"suspicious\" about Ingram's \u00a330,000 burglary claim but decided to investigate only after reading newspaper coverage about his questionable win on ''Millionaire''.<ref name=woolcock/>\n\nIngram was given a [[conditional discharge]] on the charge of fraudulently claiming \u00a330,000 on insurance. The judge told Ingram he took into account \"the punishment [Ingram had] brought upon [himself] and [his] dire financial state\" and rejected an alternative option of [[community service]] after Ingram told a [[probation officer]] he feared other criminals would bully him.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Savill |first1=Richard |title=Cheating major walks free over insurance fraud |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1447382/Cheating-major-walks-free-over-insurance-fraud.html |accessdate=12 September 2018 |work=Daily Telegraph (UK) |date=22 November 2003}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nA book covering the case, ''Bad Show: The Quiz, The Cough, The Millionaire Major'', by [[Bob Woffinden]] and James Plaskett was published in January 2015. ''[[Quiz (play)|Quiz]]'', a play written by [[James Graham (playwright)|James Graham]] that re-examines the events and subsequent conviction of the Ingrams and Whittock, opened at the [[Minerva Theatre, Chichester|Minerva Theatre]], [[Chichester]], on 3 November 2017, running until 9 December 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cft.org.uk/whats-on/event/quiz |title=Quiz |accessdate=18 November 2017 |publisher=[[Chichester Festival Theatre]]}}</ref> The play transferred to the [[West End theatre|West End]]\u2014playing at the [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]] from 31 March 2018 to 16 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://quiztheplay.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412123518/http://quiztheplay.com/|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 April 2018|title=Quiz the Play by James Graham {{!}} Official West End Website|date=12 April 2018|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref>. \n\nIn 2019, [[James Graham (playwright)|James Graham]] adapted his play into a [[Quiz (TV series)|serial drama]] for [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]], which was broadcast in April 2020 in three parts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itvmedia.co.uk/making-an-impact/itv-has-commissioned-quiz-a-three-part-drama-directed-by-stephen-frears-starring-hollywood-star-michael-sheen|title=ITV has commissioned 'Quiz' a three-part drama directed by Stephen Frears starring Hollywood star, Michael Sheen|website=ITV Media|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIngram met his wife, Diana, while she was training to be a teacher at [[Barry College]] in Wales. The two became engaged during his first posting with the Royal Engineers in Germany. They were married in November 1989 and have three children.<ref name=\"thetimesapr03\" />\n\nIn 2010, Ingram lost three toes in an accident involving a lawn mower.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/millionaire-cheat-loses-toes-in-accident-2081292.html|title=Millionaire cheat loses toes in accident|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|England|Biography|War}}\n*[[Martin Flood]]\n*[[Michael Larson]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1358467|name=Charles Ingram}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ingram, Charles}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century English criminals]]\n[[Category:Royal Engineers officers]]\n[[Category:Contestants on British game shows]]\n[[Category:Entertainment scandals]]\n[[Category:Television controversies in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Cranfield University]]\n[[Category:English fraudsters]]\n[[Category:People from Shardlow]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oswestry School]]\n[[Category:British people convicted of fraud]]\n[[Category:Mensans]]\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:British male criminals]]\n[[Category:Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people}}\n{{short description|British fraudster}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Charles Ingram\n| image              = Charles Ingram 1.jpg\n| caption            = Ingram with his wife Diana in 2006\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1963|8|6|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shardlow|Shardlow, Derbyshire]], England\n| occupation         = Novelist, computer repairman, army major\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Diana Ingram<br />|November 1989}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles William Ingram''' (born 6 August 1963) is an English novelist, computer repairman, and former [[British Army]] [[Major (United Kingdom)|major]] who became known for being accused of, and convicted of, cheating on the television [[game show]] ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' in 2001, after winning the maximum prize of one million pounds. Following [[R v Ingram, C., Ingram, D. and Whittock, T.|a lengthy trial]] at Southwark Crown Court, he was convicted on a single count of [[Deception (criminal law)|procuring the execution of a valuable security by deception]].  He was convicted of an unrelated [[insurance fraud]] in 2003, and ordered to resign his commission as a major by the Army Board.\n\n==Early life==\nCharles Ingram was born on 6 August 1963 in [[Shardlow|Shardlow, Derbyshire]], the son of retired [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] wing commander John Ingram<ref>(RAF/39187)</ref> and his wife, theatre set designer Susan. His father's [[Wellington bomber]], operating with 103 Squadron from [[RAF Elsham Wolds]], had been shot down around 20 or 21 September 1941; he was taken as a [[Prisoner of War|POW]], while two of his crew were killed.<ref name=\"thetimesapr03\">{{cite news|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?p=GPS&sw=w&u=wikipedia&v=2.1&id=GALE%7CA99786172&it=r&asid=9b7c7d8914dc6e0c4999a52da0a6d156|title=The major: strategist who flunked simple questions; Profile|date=8 April 2003|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=2 October 2017|page=11|url-access=subscription |via=Academic OneFile}}</ref> Ingram's parents divorced when he was young and he spent most of his education years boarding privately at [[Oswestry School]] in [[Oswestry|Oswestry, Shropshire]].<ref name=\"guardianaug06\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2006/sep/16/moneysupplement4|title=Fame and fortune|last=Walne|first=Toby|date=16 September 2006|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> There he was a member of the [[Combined Cadet Force]] and completed the [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award|Duke of Edinburgh Silver Award]].<ref name=\"thetimesapr03\" /> He went on to obtain a [[Bachelor of Science|BSc]] in civil engineering from [[Kingston University]].<ref name=\"guardianaug06\" /> \n\n==Career==\nIn 1986, Ingram trained for the British Army at [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|Sandhurst]] and was commissioned as an officer in the [[Royal Engineers]].<ref name=\":1\">{{London Gazette\n| issue = 52131\n| date = 8 May 1990\n| page = 8819\n| supp = y\n}}</ref> He was promoted to the rank of [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in 1990,<ref name=\":1\" /> and major in 1995.<ref>{{London Gazette\n| issue = 54173\n| date = 2 October 1995\n| pages = 13315\u201313316\n| supp = y\n}}</ref> In 1998, Ingram was sent to [[Banja Luka]] in Bosnia<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2003/mar/20/broadcasting.uknews|title=Pager claims are rot, major tells court|last=Vasagar|first=Jeevan|date=20 March 2003|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> for six months on United Nations peacekeeping duties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/wiltshire/3218325.stm|title=The man behind the scams|date=28 October 2003|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> He graduated from [[Cranfield University]] with a master's degree in corporate management in August 2000.<ref name=\"thetimesapr03\" /> He was ordered by the [[Army Board]] via letter to resign his commission on 20 August 2003 and give up his rank of major.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2003/07/200849163838278691.html|title=Marching orders for Army gameshow cheat|date=24 July 2003|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nSince leaving the Army, Ingram has written two novels: ''The Network'', published on 27 April 2006, and ''Deep Siege'', published on 8 October 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/i/charles-ingram/deep-siege.htm |title=Deep Siege by Charles Ingram |accessdate=17 December 2012 |date=8 October 2007 |work=Fantastic Fiction |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061214/http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/i/charles-ingram/deep-siege.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''==\n===Beginning===\n{{WWTBAM question\n| float    = right\n| value    = \u00a31 million (15 of 15) - No time limit  \n| question = A number one followed by one hundred zeros is known by what name?\n| a        = Googol\n| astyle   = correct\n| b        = Megatron\n| c        = Gigabit\n| d        = Nanomole\n| caption  = Ingram's \u00a31 million question\n}}\nOn 9 and 10 September 2001, Ingram was a contestant on the television game show ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' His wife Diana and her brother Adrian Pollock had previously been contestants on the show, both winning \u00a332,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2823407.stm |title=Major Charles Ingram has been found guilty of cheating his way to the top prize on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=7 April 2003 |work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media |people=[[Martin Bashir]] |year=2003 |title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire: Major Fraud |medium=Television |publisher=ITV |location=London, England}}</ref> The show, presented by [[Chris Tarrant]], was one of the highest-rated in the UK at its peak in 1999; one edition was watched by 19 million viewers, a third of the British population at the time.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/vdqdw9/15-years-of-the-coughing-major-who-wants-to-be-a-millionare|title=That Time a Guy Won 'Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?' by Cheating Terribly |author=Harrison, Angus |date=9 September 2016 |work=[[Vice (magazine)|VICE]]|access-date=5 July 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIngram practised for about twenty minutes per day on a \"[[Fastest Finger First (Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?)|Fastest Finger First]]\" machine that he constructed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1425308/Millionaire-quiz-major-had-ploy-to-foil-Tarrant.html|title=Millionaire quiz major had ploy to foil Tarrant|last=Woolcock|first=Nicola|date=22 March 2003|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref> By the time recording ended on the first day, Ingram had reached \u00a34,000 and used two of his three \"lifelines\". The production team doubted he would proceed much further when recording resumed, but he went on to win the top prize of \u00a31 million.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ingram flipped between answers erratically, appearing to settle on one answer before suddenly moving to another. For example, when asked who recorded the 2000 [[Craig David]] album ''[[Born to Do It]]'', Ingram said he had \"never heard of\" David and appeared to go for a different option before moving to the correct answer.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe show's production company, [[Celador]], suspended the \u00a31 million payout after they suspected Ingram had cheated. Production staff accused Ingram and his wife of defrauding the show by having an accomplice amongst the waiting contestants, lecturer Tecwen Whittock, who would cough when Ingram read out a correct answer.<ref name=\"Millionaire winner 'unhappy'\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2836937.stm|title=Millionaire winner 'unhappy'|date=10 March 2003|accessdate=13 May 2008|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nTarrant, who drank champagne with the Ingrams in their dressing room, said he was convinced that Ingram was genuine when he signed the \u00a31 million cheque: \"If I thought there was anything wrong, I certainly would not have signed it.\" When asked whether the atmosphere in the dressing room was tense after the show, Tarrant replied: \"No, not at all. They seemed as normal as people who have just won a million pounds would be in the situation.\" However, he said that on his way to the dressing room, \"I had been told there had been quite an unpleasant exchange.\"<ref name=\"scotsman\" /> A member of the crew, Eve Winstanley, testified in court that Ingram seemed \"very unhappy\" for someone who had just won a million pounds.<ref name=\"Millionaire winner 'unhappy'\"/>\n\nIn court, Paul Smith of Celador confirmed that his company had previously produced a television programme involving witnesses in the case, for broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] after the trial. The programme, ''Tonight With Trevor McDonald \u2013 Major Fraud'', was broadcast on ITV on 21 April 2003 (a month after the trial began), and credited with over 17 million viewers. On 9 May 2003 (the day after ''Major Fraud'' aired in the US as a special episode of ''[[Primetime (U.S. TV program)|Primetime]]''), the same channel broadcast another programme on the same topic, entitled ''The Final Answer'', which was credited with over 5 million viewers.\n\n=== Trial ===\nFollowing [[R v Ingram, C., Ingram, D. and Whittock, T.|a trial]] at [[Southwark]] [[Crown Court]] lasting four weeks (including jury deliberation for three-and-a-half days), Ingram, his wife and Whittock were convicted by a majority verdict of \"[[Deception (criminal law)|procuring the execution of a valuable security by deception]]\" on 7 April 2003. Both the Ingrams and Whittock were each given prison sentences [[suspended sentence|suspended]] for two years (the Ingrams were sentenced to eighteen months and Whittock was sentenced to twelve months), each fined \u00a315,000, and each ordered to pay \u00a310,000 towards prosecution costs. Within two months of the verdict and sentence, the trial judge ordered the Ingrams to pay additional defence costs: Charles Ingram \u00a340,000 and Diana Ingram \u00a325,000. Altogether with legal fees, the Ingrams had to pay \u00a3115,000.<ref>{{cite news |title=Charles Ingram transcript |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/charles-ingram-transcript-6967487.html |accessdate=13 January 2019 |work=Evening Standard |date=21 January 2004}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 August 2003, the [[Army Board]] ordered Ingram to resign his commission as a major after 17 years of service, but stated that this would not affect his [[pension]] entitlements.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3092357.stm|title=BBC NEWS - UK - Millionaire cheat sacked by Army|website=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May 2004, the [[Court of Appeal]] denied Ingram leave to appeal against his conviction and upheld his sentence, but agreed to quash his wife's fine and prosecution costs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/wiltshire/3728929.stm |title=TV quiz cheat loses his appeal |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=19 May 2004 |work=BBC News}}</ref> On 5 October, the [[House of Lords]] denied Ingram leave to appeal against his fine and prosecution costs, and he appealed to the [[European Court of Human Rights]]. On 20 October, the original trial judge reduced Ingram's defence costs order to \u00a325,000 and Diana's defence costs order to \u00a35,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/wiltshire/3762688.stm |title=Quiz cheat has defence costs cut |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=21 October 2004 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Ingram's defence costs were later further reduced to \u00a35,000 on appeal.\n\nIn 2006, journalist [[Jon Ronson]], who covered the case at the time for ''[[The Guardian (newspaper)|The Guardian]]'', wrote that he believed the Ingrams might be innocent. Ronson, who attended every day of the trial, had observed that when the word \"cough\" was mentioned, pensioners in the public gallery had coughed. [[James Plaskett]], who had appeared on ''Millionaire'' several times before winning \u00a3250,000 in January 2006, argued this was an example of coughs caused by unconscious triggers; Whittock had simply coughed involuntarily when he heard the correct answer. Whittock was also accused of having coughed after Ingram mentioned an incorrect option to his penultimate question and swiftly following that up with a smothered \"No\". However, Plaskett, who had sat in that very same seat, argued that he might have audibly said it in response to an incorrect option in the same way that other waiting contestants have been known to whisper \"No\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/jul/17/couldthewhowantstobeami|title=Are the Millionaire three innocent?|last=Ronson|first=Jon|date=17 July 2006|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 August 2014|location=London}}</ref>\n\n====Recorded evidence====\nIn court, Ingram claimed the videotape of his appearance on ''Millionaire'' was \"unrepresentative of what I heard\", and he continues to assert that it was \"unfairly manipulated\". A video recording, with coughing amplified relative to other sounds including Ingram's and Tarrant's voices, was prepared by Celador's editors (Editworks) for the prosecution and \"for the benefit of the jury\" during the trial (and later for viewers in television broadcasts). Ingram claims that he neither \"listened for, encouraged, nor noticed any coughing\". The prosecution alleged that, of the 192 coughs recorded during his second-night performance, 32 were recorded from the ten Fastest Finger First contestants, and that 19 of the 32 coughs heard on the video tape were \"significant\". The prosecution asserted that these \"significant\" coughs were by Whittock, each falling any time the correct answer had been spoken. During the trial, Tarrant also denied hearing any coughing throughout the episode, claiming he was too busy to notice.<ref name=\"scotsman\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/uk-news/quizmaster-amazed-to-hear-163-1m-winner-could-have-cheated-1-598995 |title=Quizmaster 'amazed' to hear \u00a31m winner could have cheated |date=13 March 2003 |accessdate=13 May 2008 |location=Edinburgh |work=The Scotsman |first=Karen |last=Mcveigh}}</ref>\n\n====Testimony of Larry Whitehurst====\nLarry Whitehurst, another contestant who had appeared on the show as a Fastest Finger First contestant on four occasions, was adamant that he had known the answers to Ingram's questions. He told the court that he had been able to detect a pattern of coughing, and that he was entirely convinced that coughing had helped Ingram.<ref name=\"BBC News\u2013Coughs\">{{cite news|title=Contestant 'spotted Millionaire coughs'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2839587.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=8 July 2011|date=11 March 2003}}</ref>\n\n====Testimony of Tecwen Whittock====\nWhittock claims to have suffered a persistent cough for his entire life<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/weekend/story/0,3605,938649,00.html |title=So I phoned a friend \u2013 part two |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=19 April 2003 |location=London |work=The Guardian}}</ref> and insisted that he had a genuine cough caused by a combination of [[hay fever]] and a dust [[allergy]], and that it was only coincidence that his throat problem coincided with the right answers.<ref name=\"scotsman_pager\" /> During the trial, however, the jury heard evidence that once Whittock himself earned the right to sit in the hot seat, his throat problems disappeared.<ref name=\"scotsman_pager\" /> Whittock later testified that he drank several glasses of water before he went in front of the cameras.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/2888791.stm |title=Cheating 'silly' says Millionaire accused |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=26 March 2003 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Whittock also insisted that he had not known the answers to three of the questions he allegedly helped with. However, the police found the answer to the twelfth question, regarding the artist who painted ''[[The Ambassadors (Holbein)|The Ambassadors]]'', in a hand-written general knowledge book at Whittock's home.<ref name=\"scotsman_pager\">{{cite news |url=http://news.scotsman.com/uk/Pager-plot-too-risky-for.2408136.jp |title=Pager plot too risky for TV quiz |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=7 March 2003 |location=Edinburgh |work=The Scotsman |first=John |last=Innes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022105328/http://www.scotsman.com/news/uk/pager-plot-too-risky-for-tv-quiz-1-548871|archivedate=22 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nDavies, the floor manager, said that, as soon as the coughing came to his notice during the recording, he decided to find out who was responsible. \"The loudest coughing was coming from Tecwen in seat number three\", he said. \"He was talking to the person to his left when I was observing him, and then he turned towards the set and the hot seat to cough.\" Whittock remarked during the trial that \"you do not cough into someone's face\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.portia.org/chapter14/major.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=26 September 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041020172443/http://www.portia.org/chapter14/major.html |archivedate=20 October 2004 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the trial, Whittock portrayed himself as a \"serial quiz show loser\" because he had been eliminated in round one of ''[[Fifteen to One]]'', had also failed on ''The People Versus'' and had been able to win only an atlas on his appearance on ''[[Sale of the Century (UK game show)|Sale of the Century]]''.<ref name=\"scotsman_whittock\">{{cite news |url=http://news.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?tid=788&id=360802003 |title=Lecturer a serial quiz show failure, court is told |accessdate=13 May 2008 |date=26 March 2003 |location=Edinburgh |work=The Scotsman|last=Innes|first=John|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030418205015/http://www.news.scotsman.com/topics.cfm?id=360802003&tid=788|archivedate=18 April 2003}}</ref>\n\n==After ''Millionaire''==\n===TV appearances===\nFollowing his appearance on ''Millionaire'', Ingram has appeared on other various TV shows, including ''[[The Games (British TV series)|The Games]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukgameshows.com/ukgs/The_Games|title=The Games|publisher=UK Game Shows|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Weakest Link (British game show)|The Weakest Link]]'', and ''[[Wife Swap (British TV series)|Wife Swap]]'', featuring alongside his wife in the latter two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/3238445.stm|title=Goody and Ingram's celebrity swap|publisher=The BBC|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Insurance fraud case===\nIn late 2003, the Ingram and his wife were charged with further [[fraud]] offences. On 28 October, Ingram was found guilty at [[Bournemouth Crown Court]] of obtaining a pecuniary advantage by deception, and of a second charge of deception, having attempted to claim on an insurance policy after an alleged [[burglary]] at his home. Ingram had failed to tell [[Direct Line]] Insurance about claims he had made in the three years before he took out the policy in July 2001. The court was told that Ingram had been a \"habitual claimant\" with [[Norwich Union]] after suffering \"unfortunate\" losses of private possessions.<ref name=woolcock>{{cite news |last1=Woolcock |first1=Nicola |title='Millionaire' quiz cheat guilty of insurance fraud |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1445354/Millionaire-quiz-cheat-guilty-of-insurance-fraud.html |accessdate=12 September 2018 |work=Daily Telegraph (UK) |date=29 October 2003}}</ref>\n\n[[Christopher Parker]], prosecuting, said Ingram switched insurers to [[Zurich Insurance Group]] in 1997, after Norwich Union reduced a burglary claim from \u00a319,000 to \u00a39,000, and in 2000 switched again to Direct Line. \"He has been ineluctably dishonest\", Parker said. \"He went to Direct Line and didn't make a disclosure about his claims history because he knew he wouldn't have been insured. It might not have started off as the most monstrous piece of villainy but these things tend to snowball and it all came to a sticky end when he claimed for \u00a330,000.\" Staff at Direct Line were already \"suspicious\" about Ingram's \u00a330,000 burglary claim but decided to investigate only after reading newspaper coverage about his questionable win on ''Millionaire''.<ref name=woolcock/>\n\nIngram was given a [[conditional discharge]] on the charge of fraudulently claiming \u00a330,000 on insurance. The judge told Ingram he took into account \"the punishment [Ingram had] brought upon [himself] and [his] dire financial state\" and rejected an alternative option of [[community service]] after Ingram told a [[probation officer]] he feared other criminals would bully him.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Savill |first1=Richard |title=Cheating major walks free over insurance fraud |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1447382/Cheating-major-walks-free-over-insurance-fraud.html |accessdate=12 September 2018 |work=Daily Telegraph (UK) |date=22 November 2003}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nA book covering the case, ''Bad Show: The Quiz, The Cough, The Millionaire Major'', by [[Bob Woffinden]] and James Plaskett was published in January 2015. ''[[Quiz (play)|Quiz]]'', a play written by [[James Graham (playwright)|James Graham]] that re-examines the events and subsequent conviction of the Ingrams and Whittock, opened at the [[Minerva Theatre, Chichester|Minerva Theatre]], [[Chichester]], on 3 November 2017, running until 9 December 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cft.org.uk/whats-on/event/quiz |title=Quiz |accessdate=18 November 2017 |publisher=[[Chichester Festival Theatre]]}}</ref> The play transferred to the [[West End theatre|West End]]\u2014playing at the [[No\u00ebl Coward Theatre]] from 31 March 2018 to 16 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://quiztheplay.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412123518/http://quiztheplay.com/|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 April 2018|title=Quiz the Play by James Graham {{!}} Official West End Website|date=12 April 2018|access-date=12 April 2018}}</ref>. \n\nIn 2019, [[James Graham (playwright)|James Graham]] adapted his play into a [[Quiz (TV series)|serial drama]] for [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV.]], which was broadcast in April 2020 in three parts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itvmedia.co.uk/making-an-impact/itv-has-commissioned-quiz-a-three-part-drama-directed-by-stephen-frears-starring-hollywood-star-michael-sheen|title=ITV has commissioned 'Quiz' a three-part drama directed by Stephen Frears starring Hollywood star, Michael Sheen|website=ITV Media|language=en|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIngram met his wife, Diana, while she was training to be a teacher at [[Barry College]] in Wales. The two became engaged during his first posting with the Royal Engineers in Germany. They were married in November 1989 and have three children.<ref name=\"thetimesapr03\" />\n\nIn 2010, Ingram lost three toes in an accident involving a lawn mower.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/millionaire-cheat-loses-toes-in-accident-2081292.html|title=Millionaire cheat loses toes in accident|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|England|Biography|War}}\n*[[Martin Flood]]\n*[[Michael Larson]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1358467|name=Charles Ingram}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ingram, Charles}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century English criminals]]\n[[Category:Royal Engineers officers]]\n[[Category:Contestants on British game shows]]\n[[Category:Entertainment scandals]]\n[[Category:Television controversies in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Cranfield University]]\n[[Category:English fraudsters]]\n[[Category:People from Shardlow]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oswestry School]]\n[[Category:British people convicted of fraud]]\n[[Category:Mensans]]\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:British male criminals]]\n[[Category:Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]\n", "name_user": "Tvcameraop", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn popular culture:remove .", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Ingram"}
{"title_page": "Ceilings of the Natural History Museum, London", "text_new": "{{short description|Decorated ceilings}}\n[[File:Ceiling of the Central at the Natural History Museum, London 2.JPG|right|thumb|upright=1.5|alt=Central Hall ceiling|Central Hall (now Hintze Hall) ceiling in 2013]]\nThe '''ceilings of the Natural History Museum''' are a pair of decorated ceilings in the main Central Hall (officially Hintze Hall since 2014) and smaller North Hall of the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in [[South Kensington]], London, unveiled at the building's opening in 1881. They were designed by the museum's architect [[Alfred Waterhouse]] and painted by the artist Charles James Lea. The ceiling of the Central Hall consists of 162 panels, 108 of which depict plants considered significant to the history of the museum, to the [[British Empire]] or the museum's visitors and the remainder are highly stylised decorative botanical paintings. The ceiling of the smaller North Hall consists of 36 panels, 18 of which depict plants growing in the [[British Isles]]. Painted directly onto the plaster of the ceilings, they also make use of [[gilding]] for visual effect.\n\nThe natural history collections had originally shared a building with their parent institution the [[British Museum]], but with the expansion of the British Empire there was a significant increase in both public and commercial interest in natural history, and in the number of specimens added to the museum's natural history collections. In 1860 it was agreed that a separate museum of natural history would be created in a large building, capable of displaying the largest specimens, such as whales. The superintendent of the natural history departments, [[Richard Owen]], envisaged that visitors would enter a large central hall containing what he termed an \"index collection\" of representative exhibits, from which other galleries would radiate, and a smaller hall to the north would display the natural history of the British Isles. Waterhouse's [[Romanesque Revival architecture in the United Kingdom|Romanesque]] design for the museum included decorative painted ceilings. [[Acton Smee Ayrton]], the [[First Commissioner of Works]], refused to permit the decoration of the ceilings on grounds of cost, but Waterhouse convinced him that provided the painting took place while the scaffolding from the museum's construction was still in place it would incur no extra cost; he further managed to convince Ayrton that the ceiling would be more appealing if elements of the paintings were gilded.\n\nThe ceiling of the Central Hall consists of six rows of painted panels, three on each side of the roof's apex. Above the landing at the southern end of the building, the ceiling is divided into nine-panel blocks. The uppermost three panels in each block consist of what Waterhouse termed \"archaic\" panels, depicting stylised plants on a green background. Each of the lower six panels in each block depicts a plant considered of particular significance to the British Empire, against a pale background. Above the remainder of the Central Hall the archaic panels remain in the same style, but each set of six lower panels depicts a single plant, spreading across the six panels and against the same pale background; these represent plants considered of particular significance either to visitors, or to the history of the museum. The ceiling of the smaller North Hall comprises just four rows of panels. The two uppermost rows are of a simple design of heraldic symbols of the then constituent countries of the United Kingdom; each panel in the lower two rows depicts a different plant found in Britain or Ireland, in keeping with the room's intended purpose as a display of British natural history.\n\nAs the ceilings were built cheaply, they are extremely fragile and require regular repair. They underwent significant conservation work in 1924, 1975 and 2016. The restoration in 2016 coincided with the removal of \"[[Dippy (London)|Dippy]]\", a cast of a ''[[Diplodocus]]'' skeleton which had previously stood in the Central Hall, and the installation of the skeleton of a [[blue whale]] suspended from the ceiling.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Hans Sloane by Stephen Slaughter, 1736, National Portrait Gallery, London.JPG|right|upright|thumb|alt=Hans Sloane|Hans Sloane]]\nIrish physician [[Hans Sloane]] was born in 1660, and since childhood had a fascination with natural history.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=11}} In 1687 Sloane was appointed personal doctor to [[Christopher Monck, 2nd Duke of Albemarle|Christopher Monck]], the newly appointed [[Lieutenant Governor of Jamaica]],{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=11}} and lived on that island until Monck died in October 1688.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=13}} During his free time in Jamaica Sloane indulged his passion for biology and botany, and on his return to London brought with him a collection of plants, animal and mineral specimens and numerous drawings and notes regarding the local wildlife, which eventually became the basis for his major ''A Voyage to the Islands {{not a typo|Madera}}, Barbados, Nieves, S. Christophers and Jamaica'' (1707\u20131725).{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=13}} He became one of England's leading doctors, credited with the invention of [[chocolate milk]] and with the popularisation of [[quinine]] as a medicine,{{efn-ua|Sloane's chocolate milk was intended for medicinal use, in particular as a believed cure for [[tuberculosis]] and [[Syncope (medicine)|fainting fits]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=43}}{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=14}}}} and in 1727 [[George II of Great Britain|King George&nbsp;II]] appointed him [[in ordinary|Physician in Ordinary]] (doctor to the Royal Household).{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=14}}\n\nBuilding on the collection he had brought from Jamaica, Sloane continued to collect throughout his life, using his new-found wealth to buy items from other collectors and to buy out the collections of existing museums.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=15}}{{efn-ua|Sloane's motivation for collecting is unknown. Towards his death he claimed that by studying as much of the world as possible he hoped to have a closer understanding of the will of God, but there is little evidence that he was particularly pious during most of the period in which he assembled his collections.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=17}}}} During Sloane's life there were few public museums in England, and by 1710 Sloane's collection filled 11 large rooms, which he allowed the public to visit.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=18}} Following his death on 11 January 1753, Sloane stipulated that his collection\u2014by this time filling two large houses{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=11}}\u2014was to be kept together for the public benefit if at all possible.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=18}} The collection was initially offered to King George II, who was reluctant to meet the \u00a320,000 (about \u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|20000|1753|r=-5}}|0}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} terms{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}) purchase cost stipulated in Sloane's will.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=20}}{{efn-ua|Hans Sloane's will was specific as to how the collection was to be disposed of. He named a committee of 63 trustees, a mixture of scientists, politicians, religious figures, other collectors, business leaders and Sloane family members. The trustees were instructed to offer the collection for \u00a320,000 to the King; if the King declined to purchase it they were to offer it to the [[Royal Society]], [[Oxford University]] and the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]], and if they declined it was to be offered to an assortment of foreign academic bodies. Only if none of the named institutions were willing to purchase the collection were the trustees to allow it to be broken up.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=18}}}} Parliament ultimately agreed to establish a national lottery to fund the purchase of Sloane's collection and the [[Harleian Library]] which was also currently for sale, and to unite them with the [[Cotton library]], which had been bequeathed to the nation in 1702, to create a national collection.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|pp=20\u201321}} On 7 June 1753 the [[British Museum Act 1753]] was passed, authorising the unification of the three collections as the [[British Museum]] and establishing the national lottery to fund the purchase of the collections and to provide funds for their maintenance.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=21}}\n\n[[File:Montagu House, drawing by Sutton Nichols (published 1754).JPG|right|thumb|alt=Montagu House|Montagu House at the time of its transfer to the newly-created British Museum]]\nThe trustees settled on [[Montagu House, Bloomsbury|Montagu House]] in [[Bloomsbury]] as a home for the new British Museum, opening it to the public for the first time on 15 January 1759.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|pp=25\u201326}}{{efn-ua|Although the collections were open to the public, the early British Museum was not easy to visit. Prospective visitors had to apply in writing to the porter and return the next day to find out whether they had been judged 'fit and proper persons', only after which would they be issued a ticket to attend at a specified time in future.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=27}} Visitors were not permitted to spend more than an hour in each of the three departments of Natural and Artificial Productions, Printed Books, and Manuscripts.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=25}}}} With the British Museum now established numerous other collectors began to donate and bequeath items to the museum's collections,{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=28}} which were further swelled by large quantities of exhibits brought to England in 1771 by the [[first voyage of James Cook]],{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=29}} by a large collection of Egyptian antiquities (including the [[Rosetta Stone]]) ceded by the French in the [[Capitulation of Alexandria (1801)|Capitulation of Alexandria]],{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=31}} by the 1816 purchase of the [[Elgin Marbles]] by the British government who in turn passed them to the museum,{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=31}} and by the 1820 bequest of the vast botanical collections of [[Joseph Banks]].{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=29}}{{efn-ua|Joseph Banks had accompanied Captain James Cook on his voyage to Australia. Banks persuaded Cook to call his landing site [[Botany Bay]], on account of the wide variety of specimens he collected there; Cook had intended to call the site Stingray Bay.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=45}} Banks went on to become one of the founders of [[Kew Gardens]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=47}}}} Other collectors continued to sell, donate or bequeath their collections to the museum, and by 1807 it was clear that Montagu House was unable to accommodate the museum's holdings. In 1808\u201309, in an effort to save space, the newly appointed keeper of the natural history department [[George Shaw]] felt obliged to destroy large numbers of the museum's specimens in a series of bonfires in the museum's gardens.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=31}} The 1821 bequest of the library of 60,000 books assembled by [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]] forced the trustees to address the issue, as the bequest was on condition that the collection be displayed in a single room, and Montagu House had no such room available.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=41}} In 1823 [[Robert Smirke (architect)|Robert Smirke]] was hired to design a replacement building, the first parts of which opened in 1827 and which was completed in the 1840s.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=42}}\n\n===Plans for a Natural History building===\n[[image:Richard-owen2.jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=Richard Owen|Richard Owen, 1878]]\nWith more space for displays and able to accommodate large numbers of visitors, the new British Museum proved a success with the public, and the natural history department proved particularly popular.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=52}} Although the museum's management had traditionally been dominated by classicists and antiquarians,{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=49}} in 1856 the natural history department was split into separate departments of botany, zoology, mineralogy and geology, each with their own keeper and with botanist and palaeontologist [[Richard Owen]] as superintendent of the four departments.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=54}} By this time the expansion of the [[British Empire]] had led to an increased appreciation of the importance of natural history on the part of the authorities, as territorial expansion had given British companies access to unfamiliar species, the commercial possibilities of which needed to be investigated.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=65}}{{efn-ua|A similar approach to natural history had already been undertaken by Spain during its colonial expansion in the Americas; from 1712 onwards Spanish government and religious officials were obliged to record and report on any plants, animals or minerals they encountered with potential commercial uses.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=65}}}}\n\nBy the time of Owen's appointment, the collections of the natural history departments had increased tenfold in size in the preceding 20 years, and the museum was again suffering from a chronic lack of space.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=59}} There had also long been criticism that because of the varied nature of its displays the museum was confusing and lacked coherence; as early as 1824 [[Robert Peel|Sir Robert Peel]], the [[Home Secretary]], had commented that \"what with marbles, statues, butterflies, manuscripts, books and pictures, I think the museum is a farrago that distracts attention\".{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=8}} Owen proposed that the museum be split into separate buildings, with one building to house the works of Man<!-- \"works of Man is Owen's phrasing --> (art, antiquities, books and manuscripts) and one to house the works of God (the natural history departments);{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=60}} he argued that the expansion of the British Empire had led to an increased ability to procure specimens, and that increased space to store and display these specimens would both aid scholarship, and enhance Britain's prestige.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=63}}\n{{quote|text=The great instrument of zoological science, as Lord Bacon points out, is a Museum of Natural History. Every civilized state in Europe possesses such a Museum. That of England has been progressively developed to the extent which the restrictive circumstances under which it originated have allowed. The public is now fully aware, by the reports that have been published by Parliament, by representations to Government, and by articles in Reviews and other Periodicals, of the present condition of the National Museum of Natural History and of its most pressing requirements. Of them the most pressing, and the one essential to rendering the collections worthy of this great empire, is 'space'. Our colonies include parts of the earth where the forms of plants and animals are the most strange. No empire in the world had ever so wide a range for the collection of the various forms of animal life as Great Britain. Never was there so much energy and intelligence displayed in the capture and transmission of exotic animals by the enterprising traveller in unknown lands and by the hardy settler in remote colonies, as by those who start from their native shores of Britain. Foreign Naturalists consequently visit England anticipating to find in her capital and in her National Museum the richest and most varied materials for their comparisons and deductions. And they ought to be in a state pre-eminently \nconducive to the advancement of a philosophical zoology, and on a scale commensurate with the greatness of the nation and the peculiar national facilities for such perfection. But, in order to receive and to display zoological specimens, space must be had, and not merely space for display, but for orderly display: the galleries should bear relation in size and form with the nature of the classes respectively occupying them. They should be such as to enable the student or intelligent visitor to discern the extent of the class, and to trace the kind and order of the variations which have been superinduced upon its common or fundamental characters.|author=Richard Owen, President's Address to the [[British Association for the Advancement of Science]], 1858<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/cbarchive_108573_presdentsaddresstothebaas18581859/presdentsaddresstothebaas18581859_djvu.txt|title=President's Address to the BAAS, 1858|last=Owen|first=Richard|year=1858|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1858 a group of 120 leading scientists wrote to [[Benjamin Disraeli]], at the time the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], complaining about the inadequacy of the existing building for displaying and storing the natural history collections.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=8}}{{efn-ua|Owen was not a signatory to the letter, probably because he was an employee of the museum and was reluctant to criticise his employer in public. It is likely that he orchestrated its writing.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=8}}}} In January 1860, the trustees of the museum approved Owen's proposal.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=41}} (Only nine of the British Museum's fifty trustees supported Owen's scheme, but 33 trustees failed to turn up to the meeting. As a consequence, Owen's plan passed by nine votes to eight.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=60}}) Owen envisaged a huge new building of {{convert|500000|sqft|sqm}} for the natural history collections, capable of exhibiting the largest specimens.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=61}} Owen felt that exhibiting large animals would attract visitors to the new museum; in particular, he hoped to collect and display whole specimens of large whales while he still had the opportunity, as he felt that the larger species of whale were on the verge of extinction.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=61}} (It was reported that when the [[Royal Commission on Scientific Instruction]] asked Owen how much space would be needed, he replied \"I shall want space for seventy whales, to begin with\".<ref name=\"TimesOpening\">{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=This is a great day with the young people of the metropolis |author= |section=Opinion and Editorial |date=18 April 1881 |page_number=9 |issue=30171 |column=D}}</ref>) In October 1861 Owen gave [[William Ewart Gladstone]], the newly-appointed Chancellor of the Exchequer, a tour of the cramped natural history departments of the British Museum, to demonstrate how overcrowded and poorly lit the museum's galleries and storerooms were, and to impress on him the need for a much larger building.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=7}}\n\n[[image:Alfred Waterhouse, The Graphic, 4 May 1878.jpg|alt=Alfred Waterhouse|right|thumb|Alfred Waterhouse, 1878]]\nAfter much debate over a potential site, in 1864 the site formerly occupied by the [[1862 International Exhibition]] in [[South Kensington]] was chosen. [[Francis Fowke]], who had designed the buildings for the International Exhibition, was commissioned to build Owen's museum.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=66}} In December 1865 Fowke died, and the [[Office of Works]] commissioned little-known architect [[Alfred Waterhouse]], who had never previously worked on a building of this scale,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=15}} to complete Fowke's design. Dissatisfied with Fowke's scheme, in 1868 Waterhouse submitted his own revised design, which was endorsed by the trustees.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=66}}{{efn-ua|The delay between the selection of the site in 1864 and the acceptance of Waterhouse's design in 1868 was the result of repeated changes of government; the United Kingdom had five different prime ministers during this period, each of whom had a different opinion on the controversial scheme to build a major museum in what was then a distant and relatively inaccessible suburb.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|pp=20\u201321}}}}\n\nOwen, who considered animals more important than plants, was unhappy with the museum containing botanical specimens at all, and during the negotiations that led to the new building supported transferring the botanical collections to the new [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Royal Botanic Gardens]] at [[Kew]] to amalgamate the national collections of living and preserved plants.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=124}} However, he decided that it would diminish the significance of his new museum were it not to cover the whole of nature,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=125}} and when the Royal Commission on Scientific Instruction was convened in 1870 to review the national policy on scientific education Owen successfully lobbied for the museum to retain its botanical collections.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=126}} In 1873 construction finally began on the new museum building.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=7}}\n\n==Waterhouse's building==\n[[File:Waterhouse NHM painting.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.2|alt=Natural History Museum exterior|Painting by Waterhouse of the final design for the building, 1876. The arch between the central towers is the entrance to the Central Hall. The side facade at the extreme right of the painting, fronting onto what is now [[Exhibition Road]], was never built.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=40}}]]\nWaterhouse's design was a [[Romanesque Revival architecture in the United Kingdom|Romanesque]] scheme,{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=31}} loosely based on German religious architecture;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=16}} Owen was a leading [[creationism|creationist]], and felt that the museum served a religious purpose in displaying the works of God.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=27}} The design was centred around a very large rectangular central hall and a smaller hall to the north.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=17}} Visitors would enter from the street into the Central Hall,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=18}} which would hold what Owen termed an \"index collection\" of typical specimens, intended to serve as an introduction to the museum's collections for those unfamiliar with natural history.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=15}}{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=12}}{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=62}} Extended galleries were to radiate to the east and west from this central hall to form the south face of the museum, with further galleries to the east, west and north to be added when funds allowed to complete a rectangular shape.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=68}}{{efn-ua|A lack of funds meant that Waterhouse's planned east, west and north galleries were never built, and the central halls and south front were the only parts of his design to be completed.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=22}} Between 1911 and 1913 plans were drawn up to build extensions to the east and west in a similar style to Waterhouse's, but the First World War meant the plans were abandoned.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=64}} By the time funds became available for further expansion in the late 20th century, Waterhouse's style was out of fashion, and later additions to the museum are in a radically different architectural style.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=68}}}}\n\nUniquely for the time, Waterhouse's building was faced inside and out with [[terracotta]], the first building in England to be so designed;{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=53}} although expensive to build, this was resistant to the [[acid rain]] of heavily-polluted London, allowed the building to be washed clean,{{efn-ua|Waterhouse chose terracotta because it was washable, but for much of the museum's history the exterior was never cleaned, giving the building a reputation for ugliness. It was only in 1975 that the exterior was fully washed, restoring it to Waterhouse and Owen's intended appearance.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=57}}{{sfn|Stearn|1980|p=53}}}} and also allowed it to be decorated with intricate mouldings and sculptures.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=70}} A smaller North Hall, immediately north of the Central Hall, would be used for exhibits specifically relating to British natural history.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=99}}{{efn-ua|The use of the smaller North Hall for the exhibition of British natural history was controversial. [[Henry Woodward (geologist)|Henry Woodward]], the Keeper of the geological department, felt that this would be the topic of the most interest to visitors, and that as a consequence it should be in the more prominent Central Hall.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=100}}}} On 18 April 1881 the new British Museum (Natural History) opened to the public.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=23}}{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=76}} As relocating exhibits from Bloomsbury was a difficult and time-consuming process, much of the building remained empty at the time the museum opened.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=99}}\n\n==Central Hall==\n[[File:Central Hall, Natural History Museum, London 20181216 102906 (31397699157).jpg|right|thumb|alt=Central Hall|Being above the skylights meant that the ceiling was dimly lit. As it could be viewed from both the distant floor and the much higher balconies, the design needed to be aesthetically pleasing at both long and short distances.]]\nAs well as being large, the Central Hall was to be very high, rising the full {{convert|72|ft|m|adj=on}} height of the building to a plaster-lined [[mansard roof]],{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}}{{sfn|Stearn|1980|p=47}} with [[skylight]]s running the length of the hall at the junction between the roof and the wall.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}} A grand staircase at the northern end of the hall, flanked by archways leading to the smaller North Hall,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=99}} led to balconies running almost the full length of the hall to a staircase which in turn led to a large landing above the main entrance, such that a visitor entering the hall would walk the full length of the floor of the hall to reach the first staircase, and then the full length of the balcony to reach the second.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=66}} As a consequence, it posed a difficulty to Waterhouse's plans to decorate the building. As the skylights were lower than the ceiling the roof was in relative darkness compared to the rest of the room,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=18}} and owing to the routes to be taken by visitors, the design needed to be attractive when viewed both from the floor below, and from the raised balconies to the each side.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=66}} To address this, Waterhouse decided to decorate the {{convert|170|ft|m|adj=on}}{{sfn|Stearn|1980|p=47}} ceiling with painted botanical panels.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}}\n{{quote|text=The lower panels will have representations of foliage treated conventionally. The upper panels will be treated with more variety of colour and the designs will be of an archaic character. The chief idea to be represented is that of growth. The colours will be arranged so that the most brilliant will be near the apex of the roof.|author=Alfred Waterhouse, June 1876{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}}}}\n\n[[File:Central Hall, Natural History Museum, London 20181216 101359 (46336914261).jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=Balcony|One of the identical twin balconies running the length of Central Hall, connecting the first and second staircases]]\n[[Acton Smee Ayrton]], the [[First Commissioner of Works]], was hostile to the museum project, and sought to cut costs wherever possible;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=20}} he disliked art, and felt that it was his responsibility to restrain the excesses of artists and architects.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=22}} Having already insisted that Waterhouse's original design for wooden ceilings and a lead roof be replaced with cheaper plaster and slate,{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=22}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}} Ayrton vetoed Waterhouse's plan to decorate the ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}} Waterhouse eventually persuaded Ayrton that provided the ceiling were decorated while the scaffolding from its construction remained in place, a decorated ceiling would be no more expensive than a plain white one. He prepared two sample paintings of the [[pomegranate]] and [[magnolia]] for Ayrton, who approved \u00a31435 (about \u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|1435|1868|r=-4}}|0}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} terms{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}) to decorate the ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}} Having obtained approval for the paintings, Waterhouse managed to convince Ayrton that the paintings' appeal would be enhanced if certain elements were [[gilding|gilded]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}}\n\nRecords do not survive of how the plants to be represented were chosen and who created the initial designs.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}} Knapp & Press (2005) believe that it was almost certainly Waterhouse himself, likely working from specimens in the museum's botanical collections,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}} while [[William T. Stearn]], writing in 1980, believes that the illustrations were chosen by botanist [[William Carruthers (botanist)|William Carruthers]], who at the time was the museum's Keeper of Botany.{{sfn|Stearn|1980|p=52}} To create the painted panels from the initial [[modello|cartoons]], Waterhouse commissioned Manchester artist [[Charles James Lea]] of Best & Lea, with whom he had already worked on [[Rockliffe Park (Hurworth)|Pilmore Hall]]<!-- This isn't an incorrect link, Pilmore Hall changed its name --> in [[Hurworth-on-Tees]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=20}} Waterhouse provided Lea with a selection of botanical drawings, and requested that Lea \"select and prepare drawings of fruits and flowers most suitable and gild same in the upper panels of the roof\";{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=20}} it is not recorded who drew the cartoons for the paintings, or how the species were chosen.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=123}} Best & Lea agreed a fee of \u00a31975 (about \u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|1975|1868|r=-4}}|0}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} terms{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}) for the work.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=23}} How the panels were painted is not recorded, but it is likely Lea painted directly onto the ceiling from the scaffolding.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=123}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=23}}\n\n===Main ceiling===\n[[File:Hintze Hall ceiling (part).jpg|right|thumb|alt=Central hall ceiling and girders|Three long rows of panels on each side rise from the skylights to meet at the roof's apex. The supporting girders are themselves decorated with gilded leaves.]]\nWaterhouse and Lea's design for the ceiling is based on a theme of growth and power. From the skylights on each side, three rows of panels run the length of the main hall, with the third, uppermost rows on each side meeting at the apex of the roof.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=25}} The two lower rows are divided into blocks of six panels apiece, each block depicting a different plant species.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=38}} Plants spread their branches upwards towards the apex, representing the theme of growth.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=25}} The supporting girders of the ceiling are spaced at every third column of panels, dividing the panels into square blocks of nine;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=28}} the girders are an integral part of the design, designed to be barely visible from the ground but highly visible from the upper galleries, representing industry working with nature.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=29}}\n\n[[File:Banksia speciosa painting on the ceiling of the Natural History Museum, London.jpg|right|thumb|alt=Painting of Banksia speciosa|The six panels depicting ''Banksia speciosa'']]\nThe girders themselves are based on 12th-century German architecture. Each comprises a round arch, braced with repeating triangles to create a zig-zag pattern. Within each upward-facing triangle is a highly stylised gilded leaf; the six different leaf designs repeat across the length of the hall.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=29}} Running perpendicular to the girders\u2014i.e., along the length of the hall\u2014are seven iron support beams. The topmost of these forms the apex of the roof, and the next beam down on each side, separating the topmost from the middle row of panels, is painted with a geometric design of cream and green rectangles.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=30}} The next beam down on each side, separating the middle from the lowest row of panels, is decorated in the same shades of cream and green, but this time with a design of green triangles pointing upwards.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=30}} The lowest of the beams, separating the panels from the skylights, is painted deep burgundy and is labelled with the scientific name of the plant depicted in the panels above; the names are flanked with a motif of gilt dots and highly stylised roses.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=30}} At Owen's request, the plants were labelled with their [[binomial name]]s rather than their English names, as he felt this would serve an educational purpose to visitors.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}}\n\nOther than on the outermost edges of the panels at the two ends of the hall,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=129}} each set of nine panels is flanked alongside the girders by an almost abstract design of leaves; these decorations continue along the space between the skylights and the girders to reach the terracotta walls below, providing a visible connection between the walls and the ceiling designs.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}}\n\nBetween the main entrance and the landing of the main staircase,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=48}} the lower two rows of panels all have a pale cream background, intended to draw the viewer's attention to the plant being illustrated; each plant chosen was considered significant either to visitors, or to the museum itself.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}} Each block of three columns depicts a different species, but all have a broadly similar design.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}} The central column in the lowest row depicts the trunk or stalk of the plant in question, while the panels on either side and the three panels of the row above depict the branches of the plant spreading from the lower central panel.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}} The design was intended to draw the viewer's eye upwards, and to give the impression that the plants are growing.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=32}}\n[[File:Ceiling of the Central at the Natural History Museum, London.JPG|center|620px|thumb|alt=Central Hall ceiling|Layout of the skylights and panels]]\n\n====Archaic panels====\n{{multiple image|align= right|direction= horizontal|total_width= 400|caption_align= left|image1= Ottelia cordata painting on the ceiling of the Natural History Museum, London.jpg|alt1=Ottelia|caption1= Archaic panel depicting ''[[Ottelia]]'' and a stylised bird|image2= Nathaniel Wallich05.jpg|alt2=Curcuma|caption2= ''[[Curcuma]]'', Nathaniel Wallich (1832)}}\nAbove the six-panel sets and adjacent to the apex of the roof lie the top rows of panels. These panels, called the \"archaic\" panels by Waterhouse, are of a radically different design to those below. Each panel is surrounded by gilded strips and set against a dark green background, rather than the pale cream of the six-panel sets; the archaic panels also continue beyond the six panel sets and over the landing of the main staircase, to run the full length of the Central Hall.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=48}}\n\nThe archaic panels depict flattened, stylised plants in pale colours with gilt highlighting, sometimes accompanied by birds, butterflies and insects.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=58}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=51}} Unlike the six-panel sets the archaic panels are not labelled, and while some plants on the archaic panels are recognisable others are stylised beyond recognition.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=51}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=122}}\n\nNo records survive of how Waterhouse and Lea selected the designs for the archaic panels,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=52}} or on from which images they were derived.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=129}} Owing to the flattened nature of the designs, it is possible that they were based on [[pressed flowers]] in the museum's [[herbarium]], or on illustrations in the British Museum's collection of books on botany.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=52}} Some of the archaic panels appear to be simplified versions of the illustrations in [[Nathaniel Wallich]]'s book ''[[Plantae Asiaticae Rariores]]''.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=54}}\n\n===Balconies===\n{{multiple image|align= right|direction= horizontal|total_width= 400|caption_align= left|image1= Central Hall, Natural History Museum, London 20181216 101316 (45613574294).jpg|alt1=Balcony ceiling panels|caption1= Panels from the balcony ceiling, with a lizard, snail, bird and crab|image2= Central Hall, Natural History Museum, London 20181216 100923 (45613575774).jpg|alt2=Lobby ceiling panel|caption2= A northern lobby ceiling depicting birds, insects, butterflies and paterae}}\nThe ceiling of the balconies flanking the Central Hall are also decorated, albeit to a far more simple design. The ceilings are painted with a stencilled motif of square panels, each containing a small illustration of a different plant or animal. All the birds and insects from the archaic panels are included; the panels also feature cacti, cockatoos, crabs, daisies, fish, hawks, lizards, octopuses, pinecones, pomegranates, snails and snakes.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=61}} The ceilings of the lobbies at the northern end of each balcony\u2014originally the entrances to the museum's refreshment room\u2014are each decorated with a single large panel of stencilled birds, insects, butterflies and [[patera]]e.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=61}}\n\n===South landing===\n{{multiple image|align= right|direction= horizontal|total_width= 400|caption_align= left|image1= Natural History Museum Main Hall, London, UK - Diliff.jpg|alt1=Central Hall from the landing|caption1= Unlike the intentionally exposed girders of the main hall, the supporting arches above the landing are enclosed within terracotta facing.|image2= Central Hall, Natural History Museum, London 20181216 101528 (46286407432).jpg|alt2=Nine botanical panels|caption2= A nine-panel set from above the landing. The archaic panels' style remains the same, but each lower panel depicts a separate species.}}\nUnlike the cavernous, intentionally cathedral-like feel of the main space of the Central Hall,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=25}}<!-- this is the cite for \"intentionally cathedral-like --> the ceiling of the landing above the main entrance, connecting the balconies to the upper level, has a different design.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=66}} Instead of the exposed and decorated iron girders of the main space, the structural girders of this end of the building are faced in the same terracotta style as the building's walls.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=66}} As the structure of the landing and staircases meant that the ceiling at this end of the room was not clearly visible from the ground floor, there was less of a need to make the designs appear attractive from far below; instead, the design of this stretch of the ceiling was intended to be viewed from a relatively close distance.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=67}}\n\nAs with the rest of the Hall, the ceiling is still divided into blocks of nine panels.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=67}} The archaic panels still run the full length, providing a thematic and visual connection with the rest of the ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=51}} The six lower panels of each set do not depict a single plant spreading across each set of panels; instead, each of the 36 panels in the lower two rows depicts a different plant.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=67}} These each represent a plant considered of particular significance to the British Empire.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=123}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=67}}\n\n==North Hall==\nArchways flanking the northern staircase to the balcony level lead to the North Hall, intended by Owen for a display of the natural history of the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=100}} Waterhouse designed a ceiling for the North Hall representing this theme.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}} As with the Central Hall, this ceiling comprises rows of panels above a long skylight along each side of the room; there are two rows per side rather than three, and nine panels on each row.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}} Unlike the archaic panels in the top row of the Central Hall, the upper rows on each side consist of plain green panels, each containing a heraldic rose, thistle or shamrock in representation of England, Scotland and Ireland, the three nations then constituting the constituent parts of the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}} (Wales was not represented, as in this period it was considered a part of England.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}})\n\n[[File:Ceiling of the North Hall (now the canteen), Natural History Museum, London.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.5|alt=North Hall ceiling|The ceiling of the smaller North Hall depicts native British plants against a green background.]]\nIn keeping with Owen's intent that the room be used for a display on the topic of the British Isles,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=103}} the nine lower panels on each side each illustrate a different plant found in Britain or Ireland.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}}{{efn-ua|It is now known that five of the 18 plants depicted in the North Hall are not native to the British Isles but were introduced by humans.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=103}}}} The plants depicted were chosen to illustrate the variety of plant habitats in the British Isles.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=103}}{{efn-ua|The only significant habitat type found in the British Isles not represented on the North Hall ceiling is [[moorland]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=103}}}} Uniquely in the building, the ceiling panels of the North Hall make use of [[Silver leaf (art)|silver leaf]] as well as gilt.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}} (During conservation work in 2016 it was found that initially some panels in the Central Hall had also made use of silver leaf, but the silver sections had subsequently been overpainted with [[ochre]].<ref name=\"HiddenTreasures\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/discover/hidden-treasures-above-heads.html|title=Hidden treasures above our heads|last=Pavid|first=Katie|date=24 April 2016|publisher=[[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]]|accessdate=8 April 2019|location=London}}</ref>) The style of illustration is similar to that of those over the south landing,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}} but instead of the pale backgrounds of the main ceiling and the panels above the landing, the illustrations in the North Hall are set against a dark green background; Waterhouse's intent was that the darker colour scheme would create an intimate feel by making the ceiling appear lower.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=103}}\n\nOne of the last parts of the initial museum to be completed, the display of British natural history in the North Hall was somewhat arbitrary, and did not reflect Owen's original intentions.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}} Stuffed native animals such as birds and rats were exhibited, alongside prize-winning racehorses, common domesticated animals such as cows and ducks, and an exhibit on commonly grown crops and garden vegetables and on the control of insects.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}} The display was unsuccessful, and was later removed,{{efn-ua|The museum eventually opened a more coherent display on the natural history of Britain in a second floor gallery.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}}}} with the North Hall used as a space for temporary exhibitions before eventually becoming the museum's cafeteria.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}}{{efn-ua|The original refreshment room had been on the balcony level between the Central and North Halls.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=61}} It was illuminated by large stained glass windows overlooking both Halls.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=100}}}}\n\n==After completion==\n{{quote|text=The walls and the ceilings are decorated, as befits a Palace of Nature, with all the varieties of animal and vegetable life, and the more striking fossil remains&nbsp;... Not the least admirable part of the plan is the great central hall, to be furnished and ornamented as an index to the contents of the museum. Though its proportions are magnificent, it will only be an epitome of the whole collection. The idea seems to have been suggested by the Reference Library of 60,000 volumes in the Reading Room of the British Museum, which this hall will almost equal in size, though of a very different form. We are sure that Londoners will be very glad to hear that they have now the opportunity of pursuing the most delightful of all studies in a true Temple of Nature, showing, as it should, the Beauty of Holiness.|author=''The Times'' on the opening of the Natural History Museum, 18 April 1881<ref name=\"TimesOpening\" />}}\n\n[[File:Terracotta monkey in the Natural History Museum Central Hall.jpg|right|upright|thumb|alt=Terracotta monkey|A terracotta monkey on a supporting column in the Central Hall]]\nAlthough the terracotta decorations of the museum do contain some botanical motifs, most of the decor of the building with the exception of the ceiling depicts animals,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=123}} with extinct species depicted on the east wing and extant species on the west.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=71}}{{efn-ua|The sculptures on the interior and exterior of the building reflect the original layout of its displays. Those parts of the building east of the Central Hall were intended by Owen and Waterhouse to be used for geological specimens, and are decorated with sculptures of extinct species known only from fossils; those parts to the west were to be used for the display of extant species, and are decorated with sculptures of living plants and animals.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=71}} The division is not absolute; bats are depicted on the east wing among extinct species, while [[ammonite]]s are depicted among the living species on the west wing.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=71}}}} A statue of [[Adam]] originally stood between the two wings over the main entrance, celebrating humanity as the peak of creation, but was dislodged during the Second World War and not replaced.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=58}}{{efn-ua|In Waterhouse's initial design the main entrance was topped with statues of both Adam and Eve, but after his original plan for a level [[parapet]] was replaced by a [[gable]], mounting two statues became impractical and only Adam was included.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=57}}}} Much was written at the time of the museum's opening about the terracotta decorations of the museum, but very little was written about how the ceiling was received.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=27}} Knapp & Press (2005) speculate that the apparent lack of public interest in the design of the ceiling could be owing to the prevalence of [[William Morris]]'s ornate floral wallpaper and fabric designs rendering the decorations of the ceiling less unusual to Victorian audiences than might be expected.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=28}}\n\n===Deterioration, restoration and conservation===\nDuring the construction of the building Waterhouse had been under intense pressure from the trustees to cut costs, and consequently was forced to abandon his proposed wooden ceiling.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=69}} Instead, beneath a [[slate roof]], the ceilings were constructed of [[lath]] and plaster. The ribs that frame the panels were reinforced with animal hair, but the panels themselves were not reinforced.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=117}} As a consequence, the ceiling panels are unusually susceptible to vibration and to expansion and contraction caused by temperature variations.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=117}}\n\nThe elaborate nature of the building's design means that its roof slopes at multiple angles, with numerous gutters and gullies, all of which are easily blocked by leaves and wind-blown detritus.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=118}} As such, during periods of heavy rainfall water often penetrates the slate roof and reaches the fragile plaster ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=118}} In 1924 and 1975, the museum has been obliged to repair and restore the ceilings owing to water damage.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=118}} The height of the Central Hall ceiling made this a complicated and expensive process, requiring floor-to-ceiling scaffolding across the length and width of the Central Hall.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=118}} The need to avoid damage to the fragile mosaic flooring and the terracotta tiling on the walls caused further difficulty in erecting the scaffolding.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=120}} The exact nature and the cost of the repairs conducted in 1924 and 1975 is unknown, as is the identity of the restorers, as the relevant records have been lost, although it is known that cracks in the ceiling were filled with plaster and the paintwork and gilding retouched;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|pp=120\u2013121}} it is possible that some of the panels were replaced entirely.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=121}}\n\nDuring the Second World War, South Kensington was heavily bombed. The north, east, south and west of the building sustained direct bomb hits; the east wing in particular suffered severe damage and its upper floor was left a burned-out shell. The bombs missed the centre of the museum, leaving the fragile ceilings of the Central and North Halls undamaged.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=117}}\n\n[[File:Whale skeleton (39940686951).jpg|right|thumb|alt=Whale skeleton hanging from ceiling|In 2017 a blue whale skeleton was suspended from the ceiling of the recently renamed Hintze Hall, replacing the \"Dippy\" ''Diplodocus'' cast which had stood there for many years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/discover/news/2018/september/secret-history-of-hope-the-blue-whale-finally-revealed.html|title=The secret history of Hope the blue whale has finally been revealed|last=Davis|first=Josh|date=21 September 2018|publisher=[[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]]|accessdate=8 April 2019|location=London}}</ref>]]\nSince the 1975 restoration the ceiling once more began to deteriorate, individual sections of plaster becoming unkeyed (detached from their underlying laths),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=122}} paintwork peeling from some panels,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=121}} and the delicate plasterwork cracking.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|pp=121\u2013122}} The ends of the Central Hall suffered the worst deterioration, with some cracks above the landing and the northern end of the hall becoming large enough to be visible to the naked eye, while the gilding in the North Hall became gradually tarnished.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=122}}\n\nIn 2001 a systematic programme for the conservation of the ceilings was instituted.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=121}} A specialised [[hoist (device)|hoist]] is regularly used to allow a surveyor to take high [[image resolution|resolution]] photographs of each panel from a close distance, and the images of each panel used to create a [[time series]] for each panel.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=121}} This permits staff to monitor the condition of each panel for deterioration.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=121}}\n\nIn 2014, following a \u00a35,000,000 donation from businessman [[Michael Hintze]], Central Hall was formally renamed Hintze Hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-27319973|title=Natural History Museum receives \u00a35m donation|date=8 May 2014|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=8 April 2019|location=London}}</ref> In 2016, in conjunction with works to replace the \"[[Dippy (London)|Dippy]]\" cast of a ''[[Diplodocus]]'' skeleton which had previously been the Central Hall's centrepiece with the skeleton of a [[blue whale]] suspended from the ceiling, further conservation work took place. The cracks in the plasterwork were filled, and flaked or peeling paintwork was repaired with [[Japanese tissue]].<ref name=\"HiddenTreasures\" />\n\n==Layout of the ceiling panels==\n===Central Hall panels===\n[[image:Hintze Hall ceiling\u2014Nicotiana tabacum.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Tobacco plant|''[[Nicotiana tabacum]]'' as pictured on the ceiling]]\nThe panels are arranged in blocks of nine. The two central, uppermost rows (55\u2013108) constitute the archaic panels. Of the outer two rows, in the six blocks at the southern end of the hall above the landing and the main entrance (1\u201318 and 109\u2013126) each panel depicts a different plant considered of particular significance to the British Empire,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=67}} while the twelve six-panel blocks above the main hall (19\u201354 and 127\u2013162) each depict a single plant considered of particular importance to visitors or to the history of the museum, spreading across six panels.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}} \n[[File:Natural History Museum, London, Central Hall ceiling layout.png|left|alt=|800px]]\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|1\n|''[[Garcinia hanburyi]]'', a variety of gamboge tree (misspelled on the ceiling as ''Garcinia hanburyii'').{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}} Gamboge trees were the traditional source of [[gamboge]], the dark yellow pigment of the clothing worn by [[Bhikkhu|Buddhist monks]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=10IMFSavIMsC&pg=PA1352&lpg=PA1352&dq|title=Mansfeld's Encyclopedia of Agricultural and Horticultural Crops: (Except Ornamentals)|last=Hanelt|first=Peter|date=11 May 2001|publisher=Springer|accessdate=8 August 2011|isbn=9783540410171}}</ref>\n|-\n|2\n|''[[Docynia|Pyrus indica]]'' (now ''Docynia indica''), the Indian pear.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}} Native to South and Southeast Asia, the fruit is used to produce juice, wine and related products.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Ha Van Tiep, Pham Huu Thuong, La Nguyen, Hoang Thi Lua, Vu Van Thuan, Lo Thi Kieu, Sammy Carsan, Ann Degrande, Delia Catacutan, Chris Harwood|year=2018|title=Domestication of ''Docynia indica'' in Vietnam|journal=Forests, Trees and Livelihoods|publisher=Taylor & Francis|location=Abingdon|volume=27|issue=4|pages=230\u2013242|doi=10.1080/14728028.2018.1511480}}</ref>\n|-\n|3\n|''[[Cornus capitata]]'', the evergreen dogwood, was a popular ornamental plant.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}}\n|-\n|4\n|''[[Coffea arabica]]'', the Arabian coffee plant,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}} was the main cultivar of [[coffee]]. Coffee had been one of Britain's most popular drinks since being introduced to Britain from the Middle East by [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]] traders in the early 17th century.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|pp=82\u201383}}{{efn-ua|As early as 1675, London contained over 3000 coffee-houses.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=81}}}} At the time the museum was built the coffee trade was dominated by the [[Dutch East Indies]], but British colonists were planting huge coffee plantations in [[British East Africa]] (now Kenya).{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}}\n|-\n|5\n|''[[Nicotiana tabacum]]'', the tobacco plant.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}} Tobacco from ''[[Nicotiana rustica]]'' (Aztec tobacco) had been introduced to England from the failed [[Roanoke Colony]], the first British attempt at permanent settlement in North America, but the taste proved unpopular in European markets.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=68}} In an effort to make the [[Colony of Virginia]] economically self-sufficient, settler [[John Rolfe]] began to plant seeds of the milder and better-tasting ''Nicotiana tabacum'' imported from Spanish colonies to the south.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=69}} The climate and soil of Virginia proved ideal for the cultivation of tobacco, which soon became the principal export of the colony.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=69}} The economic benefits of tobacco farming led to the colony prospering and to British expansion along the coast of North America, while the labour-intensive processes involved in tobacco production led to Britain entering the [[Atlantic slave trade]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=71}}\n|-\n|6\n|''[[Gossypium barbadense]]'', extra-long staple cotton (also known as sea cotton).{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}} Cotton imported from the Mediterranean had been in limited use in Britain since the 16th century, but expansion in India led to [[muslin]] and [[calico]]\u2014both made from ''[[Gossypium arboreum]]'' (tree cotton)\u2014being imported to Britain in large quantities.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=73}} Cotton-based fabrics were highly prized in Africa; as a consequence, Indian-made fabrics were traded by the British to African rulers in exchange for slaves, who in turn were shipped to North America to work in the tobacco industry.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=73}} In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, as the [[Industrial Revolution]] began, raw cotton began to be shipped to Britain to be woven into fabrics in the newly built [[cotton mill]]s.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=74}} To supply these mills, ''Gossypium barbadense'' was planted across the southern states of the newly independent United States, largely staffed with cheap slave labour; as it had longer fibres than the tree cotton of India, it was more suitable for weaving in the new industrial mills.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=74}} The plant was fundamental to both the British and the American economies; at the time the museum opened cotton accounted for more than half the value of exports from the US to Britain,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=74}} and approximately one in 10 jobs in Britain were connected to the cotton industry.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=77}}{{efn-ua|Alfred Waterhouse was a [[Quaker]] and an active [[abolitionist]], and would have been well aware of the significance of ''Gossypium barbadense''.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=77}}}}\n|-\n|7\n|''[[Prunus amygdalus]]'', the almond,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} was religiously significant in Christianity, being described in the Bible as among \"the best fruits in the land\".<ref>{{Bibleverse|Genesis|43:11|KJV}}</ref>\n|-\n|8\n|''[[Myroxylon balsamum|Myroxylon pereira]]'' (now ''Myroxylon balsamum''), was the source of [[Balsam of Peru]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} Balsam of Peru was a significant ingredient in perfumes and was also a commonly used food flavouring and traditional medication.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/balsam-of-peru|title=Balsam of Peru|work=ScienceDirect|publisher=Elsevier|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|9\n|''[[Butea frondosa]]'', flame-of-the-forest or dhaak,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} an Indian plant whose sap was an important source of [[tannin]].{{sfn|Cowen|1984|p=3}}\n|-\n|10\n|''[[Quercus tinctoria]]'', the black oak (now called ''Quercus velutina''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} is a North American species that was endemic to most of the former British American colonies.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=79}} It was valuable as a source of timber,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=79}} and also as the source of [[quercitron]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=77}} Before the invention of synthetic pigments in the 19th century quercitron was one of the most commonly used dyes in Europe, and was primarily imported through [[Glasgow]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=80}}\n|-\n|11\n|''[[Magnolia fraseri|Magnolia auriculata]]'', the big-leaf magnolia (now called ''Magnolia fraseri''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} was native to the [[Blue Ridge Mountains]] in the Appalachians. Imported to Europe in large quantities, it became a hugely popular ornamental plant.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|pp=80\u201381}} This design was one of the two sample images that persuaded Acton Smee Ayrton to authorise the decoration of the ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}}\n|-\n|12\n|''[[Citrus bergamia]]'', the bergamot orange.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} Bergamot is commonly used in perfume,{{sfn|Draelos|2015|p=57}} and also gives [[Earl Grey tea]] its distinctive flavour and scent.<ref name=GRIN>{{GRIN|''Citrus bergamia''}}</ref>\n|-\n|13\n|''[[Aesculus hippocastanum]]'', the horse chestnut,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} was native to the Balkans but had been cultivated throughout Europe. A popular ornamental plant, its hard seeds (known as [[conkers]]) were thought to be of medicinal benefit to horses.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Lack, H. Walter | title = The Discovery and Rediscovery of the Horse Chestnut | journal = Arnoldia | volume = 61 | issue = 4 | url = http://arnoldia.arboretum.harvard.edu/pdf/articles/628.pdf|page=15}}</ref>\n|-\n|14\n|''[[Strychnos nux-vomica]]'', the strychnine tree, is native to India.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} In 19th-century Britain [[strychnine]], produced from the tree's fruit, was one of the most commonly used poisons, and of high commercial significance as a [[rodenticide]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|15\n|''[[Gluta usitata|Melanorrh\u0153a usitata]]'', Burmese lacquer (now known as ''Gluta usitata''), was traditionally used as a source of varnish in [[Burma]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} As an Asian plant that would grow in the British climate, it was a popular ornamental plant in the 19th century.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=94}}\n|-\n|16\n|''[[Rhododendron maddenii|Rhododendron formosum]]'', a subspecies of ''Rhododendron maddenii'',{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} represents the many species of [[rhododendron]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=95}} Rhododendrons were widely found in [[Nepal]] and the Himalayan foothills, a region with a similar climate to the British Isles, and as a consequence these plants flourished in the cool damp British climate.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=94}} Rhododendrons and the closely related [[azalea]]s became hugely popular as ornamental plants in the 19th century, and a mainstay of 19th-century gardening.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=80}} Several rhododendron and azalea cultivars have subsequently spread throughout Britain and other territories previously controlled or influenced by Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=95}}\n|-\n|17\n|''[[Saccharum officinarum]]'', the most common species of [[sugarcane]], at the time the primary source of [[sugar]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} Although historically sugar was rarely used in Britain, it became hugely popular in the 18th century; in 1750 sugar constituted around one fifth of all European imports, and the overwhelming majority of these imports came from British and French [[slave plantation]]s in the Caribbean.{{sfn|Ponting|2000|p=510}} In the 19th century the popularity of sugar continued to rise; over the fifty years from 1800 to 1850 the ''per capita'' British consumption of sugar doubled.{{sfn|Ponting|2000|p=698}}\n|-\n|18\n|''[[Prunus domestica]]'', the most common species of [[plum]] tree.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} Believed to be one of the first fruit trees to be domesticated,<ref>{{cite book|title=Horticultural Reviews (Volume 23)|editor=Jules Janick|year=1998|isbn=978-0471254454|publisher=Wiley}}</ref> plums\u2014particularly the [[Damson]]\u2014were an important component of English cuisine.\n|-\n|19\u201324\n|''[[Banksia speciosa]]'', the showy banksia,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=130}} was an Australian plant that was rarely grown in Britain, and was unlikely to be familiar to British audiences. It is probable that it was included as a tribute to Joseph Banks, naturalist on [[HMS Endeavour|HMS ''Endeavour'']], {{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=41}} after whom the [[genus]] was named,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=44}} and whose 1820 bequest of his collections formed much of the core of the British Museum's botanical displays.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=41}} Although named for Banks, ''Banksia speciosa'' was not one of the species collected by him on the ''Endeavour'' voyage, but was first described by [[Robert Brown (botanist, born 1773)|Robert Brown]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=47}}\n|-\n|25\u201330\n|''[[Amygdalus persica]]'', the peach tree.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=131}} Although peaches do not grow well in Britain, they were nonetheless a popular fruit at the time.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=33}} At the time the museum was built, peach trees were grown extensively in Britain in [[greenhouse|hothouses]] and against south-facing walls which were warmed by the sun, and peaches were considered a luxury item.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=36}}\n|-\n|31\u201336\n|''[[Theobroma cacao]]'', the cacao tree,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=132}} did not grow in Britain, but chocolate was highly popular in Britain at the time. It is possible that it was included as a tribute to Hans Sloane.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=44}}\n|-\n|37\u201342\n|''[[Quercus robur]]'', the English oak,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=133}} was considered a national symbol of England.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=32}} Oaks were long-lived, hardy and strong, all qualities the English associated with themselves; they were also a key element in English culture, having been used as a building material in much of England's most celebrated architecture, and as the traditional English building material for warships.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=32}}\n|-\n|43\u201348\n|''[[Vitis vinefera]]'', the grape vine.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=134}} Although not native to Britain, visitors would have been familiar with grapes from the manufacture of wine, at the time considered a luxury.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=39}}\n|-\n|49\u201354\n|''[[Citrus aurantium]]'', the Seville orange,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=135}} did not generally grow in Britain, but was a staple of British culture as a key ingredient in [[marmalade]] and perfume.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=38}}\n|-\n|55\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Butea frondosa]]'' (dhaak or flame-of-the-forest){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|56\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Arisaema]]'' (cobra lily){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|57\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Dillenia]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|58\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Piper (plant)|Piper]]'' (pepper), possibly ''[[Piper ribesioides]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|59\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Curcuma]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|60\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[orchid]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|61\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Aloe]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|62\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[orchid]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|63\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[Citrus \u00d7 sinensis|orange tree]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|64\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[orchid]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|65\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Ottelia]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|66\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Blighia sapida]]'' (ackee){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|67\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[dahlia]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|68\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Quassia amara]]'' (Surinam quassia-wood){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|69\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[rose]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|70\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Phytelephas]]'' (ivory palm){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|71\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Arbutus unedo]]'' (strawberry<!-- Don't link this to [[strawberry]], despite the name the plants are unrelated --> tree){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|72\n|Archaic panel depicting an unidentifiable stylised plant{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|73\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Aesculus hippocastanum]]'' (horse chestnut){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|74\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Markhamia stipulata]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|75\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Bletilla]]'' (urn orchid){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|76\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Papaver somniferum]]'' (opium poppy){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|77\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Matonia]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|78\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Momordica charantia]]'' (bitter melon or bitter apple){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|79\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Psidium guajava]]'' (common guava){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|80\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Helianthus annuus]]'' (common sunflower){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|81\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Punica granatum]]'' (pomegranate){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|82\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[orchid]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|83\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Pothos (plant)|Pothos]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|84\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Gladiolus]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|85\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[hellebore]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|86\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Tradescantia]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|87\n|Archaic panel depicting an unidentifiable stylised plant{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|88\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Inula helenium]]'' (elecampane){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|89\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Marantaceae]]'' (arrowroot){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|90\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Vanilla planifolia]]'' (vanilla orchid){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|91\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Asclepiadoideae]]'' (milkweed){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|92\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Aristolochiaceae]]'' (birthwort){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|93\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Passiflora]]'' (passion flower){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|94\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Digitalis purpurea]]'' (common foxglove){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|95\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Viburnum]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|96\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[iris (plant)|iris]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|97\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Rhododendron arboreum]]'' (tree rhododendron){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|98\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Alcea rosea]]'' (common hollyhock){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|99\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Ananas comosus]]'' (pineapple){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|100\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[lily]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|101\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Hedychium]]'' (ginger lily){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|102\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Gossypium]]'' (cotton){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|103\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Bertholletia excelsa]]'' (Brazil nut){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|104\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Magnolia fraseri]]'' (big-leaf magnolia){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|105\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Zantedeschia aethiopica]]'' (arum lily){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|106\n|Archaic panel depicting an unidentifiable stylised ''[[Asteraceae]]'' (daisy), thought to be ''[[Arctotis]]'' or ''[[Chrysanthemum]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|107\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Lagerstroemia speciosa]]'' (crepe-myrtle){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|108\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Passiflora caerulea]]'' (common passion flower){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|109\n|''[[Camellia sinensis|Camellia thea]]'', the tea plant (now known as ''Camellia sinensis''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} is native to China, and [[tea]] made from its leaves has been drunk in China for millennia.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} Since the early 17th century limited quantities of tea were imported into Europe from China, but the drink remained expensive and was initially little known in Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} From the early 18th century onwards tea became popular and the British-owned [[East India Company]] began to import tea in large quantities from China.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} Chinese insistence on being paid in silver for tea, and for other exports such as porcelain, silk and spices, led to a trade deficits and to shortages of silver in Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} In 1773, in an effort to assist the East India Company and to reduce smuggling into its American colonies, Great Britain enacted the [[Tea Act]], allowing the Company to ship tea duty-free to [[British North America]], provoking the [[Boston Tea Party]] and subsequently the [[American War of Independence]]<!-- This is an article on a British topic in British English, don't change this to \"American Revolution\" or \"Revolutionary War\" as the terms aren't used in BrEng --> and the formation of the United States.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=92}} China remained the sole source of tea, but in 1826 the plant was found growing wild in the East India Company's newly-conquered territory of [[Colonial Assam|Assam]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=92}} In 1848 the East India Company sent botanist [[Robert Fortune]], disguised as a Chinese merchant, to visit China's tea-growing areas and steal seedlings of the highest quality tea plants;{{efn-ua|As a consequence of the trade deficit in silver, the East India Company began to pay for these goods with [[opium]] grown in its Indian territories, in violation of Chinese law.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} Chinese attempts to restrict the drug trade led to the [[First Opium War]] in which China was heavily defeated by the private army of the East India Company and the [[Royal Navy]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} The establishment of European-controlled [[treaty ports]] in the wake of China's defeat made it significantly easier for European merchants to visit China and for Europeans to smuggle items out of China.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=92}}}} these were shipped to India in [[Wardian case]]s and planted in Assam and other Company-controlled areas of the Himalayan foothills with a similar climate.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=92}} These high quality tea plants flourished in these territories, and tea became one of the most important exports of [[British India]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=93}}\n|-\n|110\n|''[[Aloe succotrina]]'', Fynbos aloe,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} is endemic to the [[Cape Province]] of [[South Africa]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=84}} Since the days of the Roman Empire medicines derived from ''[[Aloe perryi]]'' had been imported from [[Socotra]] off the coast of northeast Africa,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}} and when European botanists first reached the Cape they assumed the native aloes to be the same plant as that grown in Socotra and named it accordingly.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}}{{efn-ua|Medicines derived from ''Aloe perryi'' were invariably exported to Europe in processed form. Consequently the botanists who assumed the aloes of mainland Africa to be identical to the aloes of Socotra had never seen a complete specimen of ''Aloe perryi'' and were unaware that it was a different species.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=84}}}} At the time the museum was built, aloe-based medicines were in common use.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}}\n|-\n|111\n|''[[Citrus medica]]'', the citron.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} The first [[citrus fruit]] to be cultivated,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Ram\u00f3n-Laca |first=L. |title=The Introduction of Cultivated Citrus to Europe via Northern Africa and the Iberian Peninsula |journal=Economic Botany |date=Winter 2003 |volume=57 |issue=4 |pages=502\u2013514 |doi=10.1663/0013-0001(2003)057[0502:tiocct]2.0.co;2}}</ref> since antiquity citrons had been an important ingredient in many medications.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=65}}\n|-\n|112\n|''[[Punica granatum]]'', the pomegranate,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} did not grow in the British climate and was rarely used in British cuisine.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}} It is likely that it was included owing to its [[Pomegranate#Symbolism|religious significance]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}} Along with ''Magnolia auriculata'', this was one of the two sample images that persuaded Ayrton to authorise the painted ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}}\n|-\n|113\n|''[[Quassia amara]]'', Surinam quassia-wood,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} grew widely in the then-British territory of [[British Guiana]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}} A natural [[insecticide]], it was valuable to 19th-century medicine as a treatment against parasites and as a [[larvicide]] to prevent [[mosquito]]es from breeding.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}}\n|-\n|114\n|''[[Ackee|Akesia africana]]'', the ackee,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} is mislabelled on the ceiling; its scientific name was, and remains, ''Blighia sapida''.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=86}} (The scientific name ''Blighia sapida'' had been given to the ackee by staff at the British Museum, so the museum's staff would certainly have been aware of the correct name. Knapp & Press (2005) speculate that as the plant had been named by [[Charles Konig]],{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=163}} a mineralogist rather than a botanist, the museum's botanists may have been unhappy accepting the name.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=86}}) Ackee originated in West Africa, but was rarely cultivated there either by native inhabitants or by European settlers.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=86}} It was introduced to [[Jamaica]] in the 18th century as a cheap and nutritious food for the region's slaves;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=87}} it became widely popular there, and is now considered a symbol of Jamaica.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=86}}\n|-\n|115\n|''[[Diospyros embryopteris]]'', the guab tree or Malabar ebony, a traditional source of black dye.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}}\n|-\n|116\n|''[[Zea mays]]'', sweetcorn or maize,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}} was the staple food of much of the Americas before European colonisation. Able to grow in a wide variety of climates, by the time the museum was built it was cultivated worldwide.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=71}}\n|-\n|117\n|''[[Cassia fistula]]'', the golden shower tree, is an Indian plant.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}} A strong [[laxative]], in the 19th century it formed the basis of many European and traditional Indian medicines.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|118\n|''[[Calotropis procera]]'', the apple of Sodom,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}} was an inedible plant native to [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], and of little commercial use.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}} It is likely that Waterhouse and the devoutly religious Owen included this plant owing to its religious significance.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|119\n|''[[Cydonia oblonga|Pyrus cydonia]]'', the quince (now known as ''Cydonia oblonga''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}} was a commonly eaten food in 19th-century Europe, and was also often grown as an ornamental plant. Knapp & Press (2005) conjecture that the quince was included to allow visitors to compare a familiar plant with those more exotic species also depicted on the ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|120\n|''[[Garcinia indica]]'', the kokum, a commonly-used element in Indian cuisine.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}}\n|-\n|121\n|''[[Myristica fragrans]]'' is the source of [[nutmeg]],{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} for centuries one of the world's most valuable commodities.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=88}} Indigenous to the [[Maluku Islands]] (the Moluccas), it had historically been imported to Europe via land across Asia to the [[Ottoman Empire]] and onwards to Venice, and consequently was extremely scarce and expensive; it was the search for new routes to nutmeg markets that prompted the voyages of [[Vasco da Gama]] to India,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=88}} of [[Christopher Columbus]] to the Americas,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=88}} and of [[John Franklin]] to the [[Northwest Passage]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=90}} The Maluku Islands were controlled by the Dutch,{{efn-ua|Although the Maluku Islands were controlled by the Dutch, the tiny island of [[Run (island)|Run]] had been controlled by the English and was England's sole source of nutmeg. In the 1667 [[Treaty of Breda (1667)|Treaty of Breda]] England ceded Run to the Dutch in exchange for [[Manhattan]], giving the Netherlands a monopoly on the world's nutmeg trade.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=90}}}} but in 1810 during the [[Napoleonic Wars]] British troops briefly captured the [[Banda Islands]], seizing nutmeg trees which they subsequently planted in [[Ceylon]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=90}}\n|-\n|122\n|''[[Dillenia|Dillenia ornata]]'', now known as ''Dillenia aurea'',{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} is a flowering shrub native to present-day India, Myanmar and Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indiabiodiversity.org/species/show/225695|title=Dillenia aurea Smith|work=India Biodiversity Portal|publisher=Biodiversity India|accessdate=21 December 2018|location=Bangalore}}</ref> First described in Nathaniel Wallich's ''Plantae Asiaticae Rariores'', whose botanical illustrations inspired many of the ceiling's archaic panels, its bright yellow flowers and ability to grow in the British climate made it a popular [[ornamental plant]] in the 19th century.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=94}}\n|-\n|123\n|''[[Ilex aquifolium]]'', English holly,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} is one of the very few [[evergreen]] plants native to the British Isles.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}} A common motif in British folklore and in Christian and pre-Christian symbolism, it would have been immediately familiar to the museum's visitors; Knapp & Press (2005) speculate that Waterhouse intentionally included this highly recognisable plant to encourage viewers to examine the less-familiar species also pictured.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|124\n|''[[Ricinus communis]]'', the castor bean,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} was the source of [[castor oil]], one of Victorian Britain's most commonly used medications.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=84}} Castor oil was also a valuable [[lubricant]] in this period.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=84}} Although native to Africa, it had spread throughout tropical regions, and at the time was thought to originate in India.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=84}}\n|-\n|125\n|''[[Pyrus communis]]'', the European pear tree,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} was one of the most important native fruit trees in Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}} Its distinctive fruit would have been immediately recognisable to 19th-century viewers, serving to attract viewers to examine the ceiling more closely.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|126\n|''[[Prunus cerasus|Cerasus communis]]'', the sour cherry (now known as ''Prunus cerasus''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} was introduced to Britain by the [[Roman Empire]] and flourished in the climate. Frequently used in English cookery, particularly [[cherry pie]], its distinctive red fruit would have been easily recognised by 19th-century visitors; Knapp & Press (2005) conjecture that as with the quince, it was included to allow viewers to compare this relatively familiar plant to the less recognisable species also illustrated.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|127\u2013132\n|''[[Eucalyptus globulus]]'', the Tasmanian blue gum tree.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=141}} Although not native to Britain, in this period it was grown widely in Spain for the production of [[eucalyptus oil]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=38}} Knapp & Press (2005) contend that this tree, with which British visitors were unlikely to have been familiar, was intentionally included among more familiar plants as a device to attract the attention of viewers.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}}\n|-\n|133\u2013138\n|''[[Pinus sylvestris]]'', the Scots pine,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=140}} Great Britain's only native species of pine.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=33}} As much of England had been cleared of woodland by this time, the remnants of the pine [[Caledonian Forest]] formed some of the most significant woodland in Britain, and the Scots pine was a national symbol of Scotland.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=33}} \n|-\n|139\u2013144\n|''[[Citrus limon]]um'', the lemon tree.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=139}} As with the orange, lemons rarely grew in Britain, but were also popular in British cuisine.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=36}}\n|-\n|145\u2013150\n|''[[Ficus carica]]'', the fig tree,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=138}} was largely unknown in Britain. As with the olive, figs and fig-leaves would have been familiar to 19th-century British visitors from the Biblical narrative;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=38}} 19th-century visitors would likely have recognised the fig tree from its leaves rather than its fruit, owing to the use of fig-leaves in most depictions of [[Adam and Eve]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=41}}\n|-\n|151\u2013156\n|''[[Olea europea]]'', the olive tree,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=137}} was at the time almost unknown in Britain; they did not grow in the British climate, and both olives and olive oil were rarely used in British cookery. However, they would have been familiar to the museum's visitors, as olives were frequently mentioned in the Bible, and olive oil was often used as [[Chrism|holy oil]] by the Anglican Church.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=39}}\n|-\n|style=\"white-space: nowrap;\"|157\u2013162\n|''[[Pyrus malus]]'', the apple tree,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=136}} had for centuries been a staple fruit of the British diet.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=33}} As a cultivated fruit developed by agricultural selection, the apple also symbolised human dominance over nature.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=33}} At the time the ceilings were painted, botanists wrongly believed the apple tree to be descended from ''[[Malus sylvestris]]'', the crab apple, and consequently native to Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=35}}\n|}\n\n===North Hall panels===\n[[File:Ceiling of the North Hall, Natural History Museum, London.jpg|right|thumb|alt=North Hall ceiling|upright|Ceiling of the North Hall]]\nThere are two rows of nine panels apiece on each side of the apex.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}} The central (highest) rows on each side consist of plain green panels, each containing a heraldic rose, thistle or shamrock in representation of England, Scotland and Ireland, the three nations then constituting the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}} The nine lower panels on each side each illustrate a different plant found in Britain or Ireland.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}}\n[[File:Natural History Museum, London, North Hall ceiling layout.png|left|alt=|135px]]\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|1\n|''[[Lonicera periclymenum]]'', woodbine or common honeysuckle,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} is highly valued as an ornamental plant, and has one of the sweetest [[floral scent]]s of any native British plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.woodlandtrust.org.uk/visiting-woods/trees-woods-and-wildlife/plants-and-fungi/woodland-wildflowers/honeysuckle/|title=Honeysuckle (Lonicera periclymenum)|publisher=Woodland Trust|accessdate=6 April 2019|location=Grantham}}</ref>\n|-\n|2\n|''[[Malva sylvestris]]'', common mallow,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} is an [[archaeophyte]] (a species introduced to Britain before 1500).{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=106}} It grows on rough ground, particularly along roads, railways and the edges of fields.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=109}}\n|-\n|3\n|''[[Corylus avellana]]'', common hazel,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} is one of the most widely grown varieties used for commercial [[hazelnut]] production.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://homeguides.sfgate.com/hazelnut-plants-65404.html|title=Hazelnut Plants|language=en|access-date=6 April 2019}}</ref> \n|-\n|4\n|''[[Sonchus palustris]]'', marsh sowthistle.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}} Once a common species in Britain, its range was drastically reduced following the draining of [[the Fens]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}}\n|-\n|5\n|''[[Sambucus nigra]]'', elder,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}} was a common ornamental plant. At the time the museum was built it was also in common use as a [[herbal remedy]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=113}}\n|-\n|6\n|''[[Datura stramonium]]'', jimsonweed or thornapple,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=110}} is the only [[Neophyte (botany)|neophyte]] species (a species introduced after 1500 that now grows wild) represented on the North Hall ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=109}} A commonly found [[weed]], jimsonweed contains high levels of [[hyoscine]] (scopolamine), and at the time the museum was built was used as a herbal remedy for [[asthma]] and [[motion sickness]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=109}} Jimsonweed was also well known as a powerful [[hallucinogen]]; its name originates from an incident in 1676 in which troops stationed in [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]] during [[Bacon's Rebellion]] accidentally ate the plant and \"turn'd natural Fools\" for eleven days.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=110}}\n|-\n|7\n|''[[Bistorta officinalis|Polygonum bistorta]]'', common bistort (also known as ''Bistorta officinalis'' and ''Persicaria bistorta''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}} had been a common plant in the British Isles but its range was drastically reduced by cultivation.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}} It became popular as an ornamental plant, and spread from gardens to once more become a common species throughout the British Isles.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}}\n|-\n|8\n|[[Ranunculus|''Ranunculus lingua'']], greater spearwort,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}} is a close relative of the better-known [[buttercup]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=105}} It grows in the wild throughout the British Isles and Europe.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=105}}\n|-\n|9\n|''[[Helleborus niger]]'', Christmas rose,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}} is a shrub native to the [[Alps]]. Christmas rose was a popular ornamental plant but did not grow in the wild in the British Isles; Knapp & Press (2005) conjecture that Waterhouse included it to make the point that cultivated ornamental gardens also represented an important botanical habitat.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=112}}\n|-\n|10\n|''[[Chamaenerion angustifolium|Epilobium Angustifolium]]'', rosebay willowherb (also known as ''Chamaenerion angustifolium''){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} was at the time the museum was built a relatively uncommon plant, found primarily in rocky uplands.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}} As a species able to grow in rocky areas and to propagate quickly via [[rhizome]]s into areas cleared of other species by burning, during the Second World War it spread rapidly in [[Strategic bombing during World War II|urban areas destroyed by bombing]],{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}} gaining rosebay willowherb the nickname of \"fireweed\" by which it remains frequently known.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=112}}\n|-\n|11\n|''[[Onopordum acanthium]]'', Scotch thistle,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} is a national emblem of Scotland<!-- I'm aware some historians believe that the species depicted in Scottish heraldry is Cirsium vulgare rather than Scotch thistle, but as far as the Victorian artists were aware O. acanthium was the species in question -->.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=106}} At the time the museum was built it was believed to have originated in [[East Anglia]], but is now thought to be an [[Introduced species of the British Isles|introduced species]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=107}}\n|-\n|12\n|''[[Helleborus viridis]]'', green hellebore,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} is native to Wales and the south and west of England.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=112}} A popular ornamental plant, it has spread from gardens and grows wild throughout Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=112}}\n|-\n|13\n|''[[Inula helenium]]'', elecampane,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} was a significant source of [[inulin]], and as such had been valued as a medicinal plant since the Roman era.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=106}} Although an introduced species, it has grown wild throughout Britain for centuries.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=109}}\n|-\n|14\n|''[[Digitalis purpurea]]'', common foxglove,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} has been a medicinal plant for millennia.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=113}} One of its active ingredients, [[digitoxin]], was the most significant drug for cardiac conditions at the time the museum was built.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=115}} \n|-\n|15\n|''[[Rosa canina]]'', dog rose,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} was a common ornamental species. It would also have been familiar to the museum's visitors as a plant then in common medicinal use.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=113}}\n|-\n|16\n|''[[Glaucium flavum|Glaucium luteum]]'', yellow horned poppy (now known as ''Glaucium flavum'').{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} A source of [[glaucine]],<ref>{{cite journal |author1=G.B. Lapa |author2=O.P. Sheichenko |author3=A.G. Serezhechkin |author4=O.N. Tolkachev |date=August 2004 |title=HPLC Determination of Glaucine in Yellow Horn Poppy Grass (''Glaucium flavum Crantz'') |journal=Pharmaceutical Chemistry Journal |volume=38 |issue=1 |pages=441\u2013442 |issn=0091-150X |doi=10.1023/B:PHAC.0000048907.58847.c6 |quote=S-(+)-Glaucine (C<sub>21</sub>H<sub>25</sub>NO<sub>4</sub>) is the main alkaloid component in the grass of yellow horn poppy (''Glaucium luteum L.'', syn. ''Glaucium flavum Crantz'') of the family Papaveraceae}}</ref> it is used as a [[antitussive|cough suppressant]].<ref>R\u00fchle KH, Criscuolo D, Dieterich HA, K\u00f6hler D, Riedel G. Objective evaluation of dextromethorphan and glaucine as antitussive agents. ''British Journal of Clinical Pharmacology''. 1984 May;17(5):521-4. {{PMID|6375709}}</ref>\n|-\n|17\n|''[[Aconitum napellus]]'', monk's hood or wolfsbane.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} ''Aconitum napellus napellus'', the subspecies found in Britain, is one of the few plants [[endemic]] to Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=105}}\n|-\n|style=\"white-space: nowrap;\"|18{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}\n|''[[Daphne laureola]]'', spurge laurel.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} As a plant toxic to mammals but not to birds, it was widely cultivated on [[English country house|country estates]] to provide [[ground cover]] for the rearing of [[pheasants]] for [[pheasant shooting|shooting]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}}\n|}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist-ua|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book |title=Flowering Trees and Shrubs in India, Sixth Edition|last=Cowen|first=D. V.|year=1984|publisher=Thacker and Co|oclc=803751318|location=Bombay|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Draelos|first=Zoe Diana|title=Cosmetic Dermatology: Products and Procedures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D2a-CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA57|year=2015|publisher=Wiley|isbn=978-1-118-65546-7|location=Chichester, UK|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Girouard|first=Mark|authorlink=Mark Girouard|title=Alfred Waterhouse and the Natural History Museum|year=1981|edition=1999|publisher=Natural History Museum|location=London|isbn=978-0-565-09135-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Knapp|first1=Sandra|authorlink1=Sandra Knapp|last2=Press|first2=Bob|title=The Gilded Canopy|year=2005|publisher=Natural History Museum|location=London|isbn=978-0-565-09198-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ponting|first=Clive|authorlink=Clive Ponting|year=2000|title=World History: A New Perspective|location=London|publisher=Chatto & Windus|isbn=0-7011-6834-X|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stearn|first=William T.|authorlink=William T. Stearn|title=The Natural History Museum at South Kensington|year=1980|publisher=Natural History Museum|location=London|isbn=978-0-565-09030-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Thackray|first1=John|last2=Press|first2=Bob|title=Nature's Treasurehouse: A History of the Natural History Museum|edition=2013|year=2001|publisher=Natural History Museum|location=London|isbn=978-0-565-09318-1|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Natural History Museum, London, Central Hall ceiling|Hintze Hall ceiling}}\n*[https://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/beta/exhibit/ZgIC0U5-YXGjLg Interactive and zoomable ultra-high-definition images of the Hintze Hall ceiling] at the [[Google Cultural Institute]]\n\n{{Coord|51|29|46|N|00|10|35|W|region:GB|display=title}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n[[Category:Natural History Museum, London]]\n[[Category:Alfred Waterhouse buildings]]\n[[Category:Painted ceilings]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Decorated ceilings}}\n[[File:Ceiling of the Central at the Natural History Museum, London 2.JPG|right|thumb|upright=1.5|alt=Central Hall ceiling|Central Hall (now Hintze Hall) ceiling in 2013]]\nThe '''ceilings of the Natural History Museum''' are a pair of decorated ceilings in the main Central Hall (officially Hintze Hall since 2014) and smaller North Hall of the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in [[South Kensington]], London, unveiled at the building's opening in 1881. They were designed by the museum's architect [[Alfred Waterhouse]] and painted by the artist Charles James Lea. The ceiling of the Central Hall consists of 162 panels, 108 of which depict plants considered significant to the history of the museum, to the [[British Empire]] or the museum's visitors and the remainder are highly stylised decorative botanical paintings. The ceiling of the smaller North Hall consists of 36 panels, 18 of which depict plants growing in the [[British Isles]]. Painted directly onto the plaster of the ceilings, they also make use of [[gilding]] for visual effect.\n\nThe natural history collections had originally shared a building with their parent institution the [[British Museum]], but with the expansion of the British Empire there was a significant increase in both public and commercial interest in natural history, and in the number of specimens added to the museum's natural history collections. In 1860 it was agreed that a separate museum of natural history would be created in a large building, capable of displaying the largest specimens, such as whales. The superintendent of the natural history departments, [[Richard Owen]], envisaged that visitors would enter a large central hall containing what he termed an \"index collection\" of representative exhibits, from which other galleries would radiate, and a smaller hall to the north would display the natural history of the British Isles. Waterhouse's [[Romanesque Revival architecture in the United Kingdom|Romanesque]] design for the museum included decorative painted ceilings. [[Acton Smee Ayrton]], the [[First Commissioner of Works]], refused to permit the decoration of the ceilings on grounds of cost, but Waterhouse convinced him that provided the painting took place while the scaffolding from the museum's construction was still in place it would incur no extra cost; he further managed to convince Ayrton that the ceiling would be more appealing if elements of the paintings were gilded.\n\nThe ceiling of the Central Hall consists of six rows of painted panels, three on each side of the roof's apex. Above the landing at the southern end of the building, the ceiling is divided into nine-panel blocks. The uppermost three panels in each block consist of what Waterhouse termed \"archaic\" panels, depicting stylised plants on a green background. Each of the lower six panels in each block depicts a plant considered of particular significance to the British Empire, against a pale background. Above the remainder of the Central Hall the archaic panels remain in the same style, but each set of six lower panels depicts a single plant, spreading across the six panels and against the same pale background; these represent plants considered of particular significance either to visitors, or to the history of the museum. The ceiling of the smaller North Hall comprises just four rows of panels. The two uppermost rows are of a simple design of heraldic symbols of the then constituent countries of the United Kingdom; each panel in the lower two rows depicts a different plant found in Britain or Ireland, in keeping with the room's intended purpose as a display of British natural history.\n\nAs the ceilings were built cheaply, they are extremely fragile and require regular repair. They underwent significant conservation work in 1924, 1975 and 2016. The restoration in 2016 coincided with the removal of \"[[Dippy (London)|Dippy]]\", a cast of a ''[[Diplodocus]]'' skeleton which had previously stood in the Central Hall, and the installation of the skeleton of a [[blue whale]] suspended from the ceiling.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Hans Sloane by Stephen Slaughter, 1736, National Portrait Gallery, London.JPG|right|upright|thumb|alt=Hans Sloane|Hans Sloane]]\nIrish physician [[Hans Sloane]] was born in 1660, and since childhood had a fascination with natural history.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=11}} In 1687 Sloane was appointed personal doctor to [[Christopher Monck, 2nd Duke of Albemarle|Christopher Monck]], the newly appointed [[Lieutenant Governor of Jamaica]],{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=11}} and lived on that island until Monck died in October 1688.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=13}} During his free time in Jamaica Sloane indulged his passion for biology and botany, and on his return to London brought with him a collection of plants, animal and mineral specimens and numerous drawings and notes regarding the local wildlife, which eventually became the basis for his major ''A Voyage to the Islands {{not a typo|Madera}}, Barbados, Nieves, S. Christophers and Jamaica'' (1707\u20131725).{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=13}} He became one of England's leading doctors, credited with the invention of [[chocolate milk]] and with the popularisation of [[quinine]] as a medicine,{{efn-ua|Sloane's chocolate milk was intended for medicinal use, in particular as a believed cure for [[tuberculosis]] and [[Syncope (medicine)|fainting fits]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=43}}{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=14}}}} and in 1727 [[George II of Great Britain|King George&nbsp;II]] appointed him [[in ordinary|Physician in Ordinary]] (doctor to the Royal Household).{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=14}}\n\nBuilding on the collection he had brought from Jamaica, Sloane continued to collect throughout his life, using his new-found wealth to buy items from other collectors and to buy out the collections of existing museums.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=15}}{{efn-ua|Sloane's motivation for collecting is unknown. Towards his death he claimed that by studying as much of the world as possible he hoped to have a closer understanding of the will of God, but there is little evidence that he was particularly pious during most of the period in which he assembled his collections.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=17}}}} During Sloane's life there were few public museums in England, and by 1710 Sloane's collection filled 11 large rooms, which he allowed the public to visit.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=18}} Following his death on 11 January 1753, Sloane stipulated that his collection\u2014by this time filling two large houses{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=11}}\u2014was to be kept together for the public benefit if at all possible.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=18}} The collection was initially offered to King George II, who was reluctant to meet the \u00a320,000 (about \u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|20000|1753|r=-5}}|0}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} terms{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}) purchase cost stipulated in Sloane's will.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=20}}{{efn-ua|Hans Sloane's will was specific as to how the collection was to be disposed of. He named a committee of 63 trustees, a mixture of scientists, politicians, religious figures, other collectors, business leaders and Sloane family members. The trustees were instructed to offer the collection for \u00a320,000 to the King; if the King declined to purchase it they were to offer it to the [[Royal Society]], [[Oxford University]] and the [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh]], and if they declined it was to be offered to an assortment of foreign academic bodies. Only if none of the named institutions were willing to purchase the collection were the trustees to allow it to be broken up.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=18}}}} Parliament ultimately agreed to establish a national lottery to fund the purchase of Sloane's collection and the [[Harleian Library]] which was also currently for sale, and to unite them with the [[Cotton library]], which had been bequeathed to the nation in 1702, to create a national collection.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|pp=20\u201321}} On 7 June 1753 the [[British Museum Act 1753]] was passed, authorising the unification of the three collections as the [[British Museum]] and establishing the national lottery to fund the purchase of the collections and to provide funds for their maintenance.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=21}}\n\n[[File:Montagu House, drawing by Sutton Nichols (published 1754).JPG|right|thumb|alt=Montagu House|Montagu House at the time of its transfer to the newly-created British Museum]]\nThe trustees settled on [[Montagu House, Bloomsbury|Montagu House]] in [[Bloomsbury]] as a home for the new British Museum, opening it to the public for the first time on 15 January 1759.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|pp=25\u201326}}{{efn-ua|Although the collections were open to the public, the early British Museum was not easy to visit. Prospective visitors had to apply in writing to the porter and return the next day to find out whether they had been judged 'fit and proper persons', only after which would they be issued a ticket to attend at a specified time in future.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=27}} Visitors were not permitted to spend more than an hour in each of the three departments of Natural and Artificial Productions, Printed Books, and Manuscripts.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=25}}}} With the British Museum now established numerous other collectors began to donate and bequeath items to the museum's collections,{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=28}} which were further swelled by large quantities of exhibits brought to England in 1771 by the [[first voyage of James Cook]],{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=29}} by a large collection of Egyptian antiquities (including the [[Rosetta Stone]]) ceded by the French in the [[Capitulation of Alexandria (1801)|Capitulation of Alexandria]],{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=31}} by the 1816 purchase of the [[Elgin Marbles]] by the British government who in turn passed them to the museum,{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=31}} and by the 1820 bequest of the vast botanical collections of [[Joseph Banks]].{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=29}}{{efn-ua|Joseph Banks had accompanied Captain James Cook on his voyage to Australia. Banks persuaded Cook to call his landing site [[Botany Bay]], on account of the wide variety of specimens he collected there; Cook had intended to call the site Stingray Bay.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=45}} Banks went on to become one of the founders of [[Kew Gardens]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=47}}}} Other collectors continued to sell, donate or bequeath their collections to the museum, and by 1807 it was clear that Montagu House was unable to accommodate the museum's holdings. In 1808\u201309, in an effort to save space, the newly appointed keeper of the natural history department [[George Shaw]] felt obliged to destroy large numbers of the museum's specimens in a series of bonfires in the museum's gardens.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=31}} The 1821 bequest of the library of 60,000 books assembled by [[George III of the United Kingdom|George III]] forced the trustees to address the issue, as the bequest was on condition that the collection be displayed in a single room, and Montagu House had no such room available.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=41}} In 1823 [[Robert Smirke (architect)|Robert Smirke]] was hired to design a replacement building, the first parts of which opened in 1827 and which was completed in the 1840s.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=42}}\n\n===Plans for a Natural History building===\n[[image:Richard-owen2.jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=Richard Owen|Richard Owen, 1878]]\nWith more space for displays and able to accommodate large numbers of visitors, the new British Museum proved a success with the public, and the natural history department proved particularly popular.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=52}} Although the museum's management had traditionally been dominated by classicists and antiquarians,{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=49}} in 1856 the natural history department was split into separate departments of botany, zoology, mineralogy and geology, each with their own keeper and with botanist and palaeontologist [[Richard Owen]] as superintendent of the four departments.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=54}} By this time the expansion of the [[British Empire]] had led to an increased appreciation of the importance of natural history on the part of the authorities, as territorial expansion had given British companies access to unfamiliar species, the commercial possibilities of which needed to be investigated.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=65}}{{efn-ua|A similar approach to natural history had already been undertaken by Spain during its colonial expansion in the Americas; from 1712 onwards Spanish government and religious officials were obliged to record and report on any plants, animals or minerals they encountered with potential commercial uses.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=65}}}}\n\nBy the time of Owen's appointment, the collections of the natural history departments had increased tenfold in size in the preceding 20 years, and the museum was again suffering from a chronic lack of space.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=59}} There had also long been criticism that because of the varied nature of its displays the museum was confusing and lacked coherence; as early as 1824 [[Robert Peel|Sir Robert Peel]], the [[Home Secretary]], had commented that \"what with marbles, statues, butterflies, manuscripts, books and pictures, I think the museum is a farrago that distracts attention\".{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=8}} Owen proposed that the museum be split into separate buildings, with one building to house the works of Man<!-- \"works of Man is Owen's phrasing --> (art, antiquities, books and manuscripts) and one to house the works of God (the natural history departments);{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=60}} he argued that the expansion of the British Empire had led to an increased ability to procure specimens, and that increased space to store and display these specimens would both aid scholarship, and enhance Britain's prestige.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=63}}\n{{quote|text=The great instrument of zoological science, as Lord Bacon points out, is a Museum of Natural History. Every civilized state in Europe possesses such a Museum. That of England has been progressively developed to the extent which the restrictive circumstances under which it originated have allowed. The public is now fully aware, by the reports that have been published by Parliament, by representations to Government, and by articles in Reviews and other Periodicals, of the present condition of the National Museum of Natural History and of its most pressing requirements. Of them the most pressing, and the one essential to rendering the collections worthy of this great empire, is 'space'. Our colonies include parts of the earth where the forms of plants and animals are the most strange. No empire in the world had ever so wide a range for the collection of the various forms of animal life as Great Britain. Never was there so much energy and intelligence displayed in the capture and transmission of exotic animals by the enterprising traveller in unknown lands and by the hardy settler in remote colonies, as by those who start from their native shores of Britain. Foreign Naturalists consequently visit England anticipating to find in her capital and in her National Museum the richest and most varied materials for their comparisons and deductions. And they ought to be in a state pre-eminently \nconducive to the advancement of a philosophical zoology, and on a scale commensurate with the greatness of the nation and the peculiar national facilities for such perfection. But, in order to receive and to display zoological specimens, space must be had, and not merely space for display, but for orderly display: the galleries should bear relation in size and form with the nature of the classes respectively occupying them. They should be such as to enable the student or intelligent visitor to discern the extent of the class, and to trace the kind and order of the variations which have been superinduced upon its common or fundamental characters.|author=Richard Owen, President's Address to the [[British Association for the Advancement of Science]], 1858<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/cbarchive_108573_presdentsaddresstothebaas18581859/presdentsaddresstothebaas18581859_djvu.txt|title=President's Address to the BAAS, 1858|last=Owen|first=Richard|year=1858|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1858 a group of 120 leading scientists wrote to [[Benjamin Disraeli]], at the time the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], complaining about the inadequacy of the existing building for displaying and storing the natural history collections.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=8}}{{efn-ua|Owen was not a signatory to the letter, probably because he was an employee of the museum and was reluctant to criticise his employer in public. It is likely that he orchestrated its writing.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=8}}}} In January 1860, the trustees of the museum approved Owen's proposal.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=41}} (Only nine of the British Museum's fifty trustees supported Owen's scheme, but 33 trustees failed to turn up to the meeting. As a consequence, Owen's plan passed by nine votes to eight.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=60}}) Owen envisaged a huge new building of {{convert|500000|sqft|sqm}} for the natural history collections, capable of exhibiting the largest specimens.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=61}} Owen felt that exhibiting large animals would attract visitors to the new museum; in particular, he hoped to collect and display whole specimens of large whales while he still had the opportunity, as he felt that the larger species of whale were on the verge of extinction.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=61}} (It was reported that when the [[Royal Commission on Scientific Instruction]] asked Owen how much space would be needed, he replied \"I shall want space for seventy whales, to begin with\".<ref name=\"TimesOpening\">{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=This is a great day with the young people of the metropolis |author= |section=Opinion and Editorial |date=18 April 1881 |page_number=9 |issue=30171 |column=D}}</ref>) In October 1861 Owen gave [[William Ewart Gladstone]], the newly-appointed Chancellor of the Exchequer, a tour of the cramped natural history departments of the British Museum, to demonstrate how overcrowded and poorly lit the museum's galleries and storerooms were, and to impress on him the need for a much larger building.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=7}}\n\n[[image:Alfred Waterhouse, The Graphic, 4 May 1878.jpg|alt=Alfred Waterhouse|right|thumb|Alfred Waterhouse, 1878]]\nAfter much debate over a potential site, in 1864 the site formerly occupied by the [[1862 International Exhibition]] in [[South Kensington]] was chosen. [[Francis Fowke]], who had designed the buildings for the International Exhibition, was commissioned to build Owen's museum.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=66}} In December 1865 Fowke died, and the [[Office of Works]] commissioned little-known architect [[Alfred Waterhouse]], who had never previously worked on a building of this scale,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=15}} to complete Fowke's design. Dissatisfied with Fowke's scheme, in 1868 Waterhouse submitted his own revised design, which was endorsed by the trustees.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=66}}{{efn-ua|The delay between the selection of the site in 1864 and the acceptance of Waterhouse's design in 1868 was the result of repeated changes of government; the United Kingdom had five different prime ministers during this period, each of whom had a different opinion on the controversial scheme to build a major museum in what was then a distant and relatively inaccessible suburb.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|pp=20\u201321}}}}\n\nOwen, who considered animals more important than plants, was unhappy with the museum containing botanical specimens at all, and during the negotiations that led to the new building supported transferring the botanical collections to the new [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Royal Botanic Gardens]] at [[Kew]] to amalgamate the national collections of living and preserved plants.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=124}} However, he decided that it would diminish the significance of his new museum were it not to cover the whole of nature,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=125}} and when the Royal Commission on Scientific Instruction was convened in 1870 to review the national policy on scientific education Owen successfully lobbied for the museum to retain its botanical collections.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=126}} In 1873 construction finally began on the new museum building.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=7}}\n\n==Waterhouse's building==\n[[File:Waterhouse NHM painting.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.2|alt=Natural History Museum exterior|Painting by Waterhouse of the final design for the building, 1876. The arch between the central towers is the entrance to the Central Hall. The side facade at the extreme right of the painting, fronting onto what is now [[Exhibition Road]], was never built.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=40}}]]\nWaterhouse's design was a [[Romanesque Revival architecture in the United Kingdom|Romanesque]] scheme,{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=31}} loosely based on German religious architecture;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=16}} Owen was a leading [[creationism|creationist]], and felt that the museum served a religious purpose in displaying the works of God.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=27}} The design was centred around a very large rectangular central hall and a smaller hall to the north.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=17}} Visitors would enter from the street into the Central Hall,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=18}} which would hold what Owen termed an \"index collection\" of typical specimens, intended to serve as an introduction to the museum's collections for those unfamiliar with natural history.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=15}}{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=12}}{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=62}} Extended galleries were to radiate to the east and west from this central hall to form the south face of the museum, with further galleries to the east, west and north to be added when funds allowed to complete a rectangular shape.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=68}}{{efn-ua|A lack of funds meant that Waterhouse's planned east, west and north galleries were never built, and the central halls and south front were the only parts of his design to be completed.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=22}} Between 1911 and 1913 plans were drawn up to build extensions to the east and west in a similar style to Waterhouse's, but the First World War meant the plans were abandoned.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=64}} By the time funds became available for further expansion in the late 20th century, Waterhouse's style was out of fashion, and later additions to the museum are in a radically different architectural style.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=68}}}}\n\nUniquely for the time, Waterhouse's building was faced inside and out with [[terracotta]], the first building in England to be so designed;{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=53}} although expensive to build, this was resistant to the [[acid rain]] of heavily-polluted London, allowed the building to be washed clean,{{efn-ua|Waterhouse chose terracotta because it was washable, but for much of the museum's history the exterior was never cleaned, giving the building a reputation for ugliness. It was only in 1975 that the exterior was fully washed, restoring it to Waterhouse and Owen's intended appearance.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=57}}{{sfn|Stearn|1980|p=53}}}} and also allowed it to be decorated with intricate mouldings and sculptures.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=70}} A smaller North Hall, immediately north of the Central Hall, would be used for exhibits specifically relating to British natural history.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=99}}{{efn-ua|The use of the smaller North Hall for the exhibition of British natural history was controversial. [[Henry Woodward (geologist)|Henry Woodward]], the Keeper of the geological department, felt that this would be the topic of the most interest to visitors, and that as a consequence it should be in the more prominent Central Hall.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=100}}}} On 18 April 1881 the new British Museum (Natural History) opened to the public.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=23}}{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=76}} As relocating exhibits from Bloomsbury was a difficult and time-consuming process, much of the building remained empty at the time the museum opened.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=99}}\n\n==Central Hall==\n[[File:Central Hall, Natural History Museum, London 20181216 102906 (31397699157).jpg|right|thumb|alt=Central Hall|Being above the skylights meant that the ceiling was dimly lit. As it could be viewed from both the distant floor and the much higher balconies, the design needed to be aesthetically pleasing at both long and short distances.]]\nAs well as being large, the Central Hall was to be very high, rising the full {{convert|72|ft|m|adj=on}} height of the building to a plaster-lined [[mansard roof]],{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}}{{sfn|Stearn|1980|p=47}} with [[skylight]]s running the length of the hall at the junction between the roof and the wall.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}} A grand staircase at the northern end of the hall, flanked by archways leading to the smaller North Hall,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=99}} led to balconies running almost the full length of the hall to a staircase which in turn led to a large landing above the main entrance, such that a visitor entering the hall would walk the full length of the floor of the hall to reach the first staircase, and then the full length of the balcony to reach the second.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=66}} As a consequence, it posed a difficulty to Waterhouse's plans to decorate the building. As the skylights were lower than the ceiling the roof was in relative darkness compared to the rest of the room,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=18}} and owing to the routes to be taken by visitors, the design needed to be attractive when viewed both from the floor below, and from the raised balconies to the each side.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=66}} To address this, Waterhouse decided to decorate the {{convert|170|ft|m|adj=on}}{{sfn|Stearn|1980|p=47}} ceiling with painted botanical panels.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}}\n{{quote|text=The lower panels will have representations of foliage treated conventionally. The upper panels will be treated with more variety of colour and the designs will be of an archaic character. The chief idea to be represented is that of growth. The colours will be arranged so that the most brilliant will be near the apex of the roof.|author=Alfred Waterhouse, June 1876{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}}}}\n\n[[File:Central Hall, Natural History Museum, London 20181216 101359 (46336914261).jpg|right|thumb|upright|alt=Balcony|One of the identical twin balconies running the length of Central Hall, connecting the first and second staircases]]\n[[Acton Smee Ayrton]], the [[First Commissioner of Works]], was hostile to the museum project, and sought to cut costs wherever possible;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=20}} he disliked art, and felt that it was his responsibility to restrain the excesses of artists and architects.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=22}} Having already insisted that Waterhouse's original design for wooden ceilings and a lead roof be replaced with cheaper plaster and slate,{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=22}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}} Ayrton vetoed Waterhouse's plan to decorate the ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}} Waterhouse eventually persuaded Ayrton that provided the ceiling were decorated while the scaffolding from its construction remained in place, a decorated ceiling would be no more expensive than a plain white one. He prepared two sample paintings of the [[pomegranate]] and [[magnolia]] for Ayrton, who approved \u00a31435 (about \u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|1435|1868|r=-4}}|0}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} terms{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}) to decorate the ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}} Having obtained approval for the paintings, Waterhouse managed to convince Ayrton that the paintings' appeal would be enhanced if certain elements were [[gilding|gilded]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}}\n\nRecords do not survive of how the plants to be represented were chosen and who created the initial designs.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}} Knapp & Press (2005) believe that it was almost certainly Waterhouse himself, likely working from specimens in the museum's botanical collections,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=19}} while [[William T. Stearn]], writing in 1980, believes that the illustrations were chosen by botanist [[William Carruthers (botanist)|William Carruthers]], who at the time was the museum's Keeper of Botany.{{sfn|Stearn|1980|p=52}} To create the painted panels from the initial [[modello|cartoons]], Waterhouse commissioned Manchester artist [[Charles James Lea]] of Best & Lea, with whom he had already worked on [[Rockliffe Park (Hurworth)|Pilmore Hall]]<!-- This isn't an incorrect link, Pilmore Hall changed its name --> in [[Hurworth-on-Tees]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=20}} Waterhouse provided Lea with a selection of botanical drawings, and requested that Lea \"select and prepare drawings of fruits and flowers most suitable and gild same in the upper panels of the roof\";{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=20}} it is not recorded who drew the cartoons for the paintings, or how the species were chosen.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=123}} Best & Lea agreed a fee of \u00a31975 (about \u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|1975|1868|r=-4}}|0}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} terms{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}) for the work.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=23}} How the panels were painted is not recorded, but it is likely Lea painted directly onto the ceiling from the scaffolding.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=123}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=23}}\n\n===Main ceiling===\n[[File:Hintze Hall ceiling (part).jpg|right|thumb|alt=Central hall ceiling and girders|Three long rows of panels on each side rise from the skylights to meet at the roof's apex. The supporting girders are themselves decorated with gilded leaves.]]\nWaterhouse and Lea's design for the ceiling is based on a theme of growth and power. From the skylights on each side, three rows of panels run the length of the main hall, with the third, uppermost rows on each side meeting at the apex of the roof.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=25}} The two lower rows are divided into blocks of six panels apiece, each block depicting a different plant species.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=38}} Plants spread their branches upwards towards the apex, representing the theme of growth.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=25}} The supporting girders of the ceiling are spaced at every third column of panels, dividing the panels into square blocks of nine;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=28}} the girders are an integral part of the design, designed to be barely visible from the ground but highly visible from the upper galleries, representing industry working with nature.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=29}}\n\n[[File:Banksia speciosa painting on the ceiling of the Natural History Museum, London.jpg|right|thumb|alt=Painting of Banksia speciosa|The six panels depicting ''Banksia speciosa'']]\nThe girders themselves are based on 12th-century German architecture. Each comprises a round arch, braced with repeating triangles to create a zig-zag pattern. Within each upward-facing triangle is a highly stylised gilded leaf; the six different leaf designs repeat across the length of the hall.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=29}} Running perpendicular to the girders\u2014i.e., along the length of the hall\u2014are seven iron support beams. The topmost of these forms the apex of the roof, and the next beam down on each side, separating the topmost from the middle row of panels, is painted with a geometric design of cream and green rectangles.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=30}} The next beam down on each side, separating the middle from the lowest row of panels, is decorated in the same shades of cream and green, but this time with a design of green triangles pointing upwards.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=30}} The lowest of the beams, separating the panels from the skylights, is painted deep burgundy and is labelled with the scientific name of the plant depicted in the panels above; the names are flanked with a motif of gilt dots and highly stylised roses.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=30}} At Owen's request, the plants were labelled with their [[binomial name]]s rather than their English names, as he felt this would serve an educational purpose to visitors.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}}\n\nOther than on the outermost edges of the panels at the two ends of the hall,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=129}} each set of nine panels is flanked alongside the girders by an almost abstract design of leaves; these decorations continue along the space between the skylights and the girders to reach the terracotta walls below, providing a visible connection between the walls and the ceiling designs.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}}\n\nBetween the main entrance and the landing of the main staircase,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=48}} the lower two rows of panels all have a pale cream background, intended to draw the viewer's attention to the plant being illustrated; each plant chosen was considered significant either to visitors, or to the museum itself.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}} Each block of three columns depicts a different species, but all have a broadly similar design.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}} The central column in the lowest row depicts the trunk or stalk of the plant in question, while the panels on either side and the three panels of the row above depict the branches of the plant spreading from the lower central panel.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}} The design was intended to draw the viewer's eye upwards, and to give the impression that the plants are growing.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=32}}\n[[File:Ceiling of the Central at the Natural History Museum, London.JPG|center|620px|thumb|alt=Central Hall ceiling|Layout of the skylights and panels]]\n\n====Archaic panels====\n{{multiple image|align= right|direction= horizontal|total_width= 400|caption_align= left|image1= Ottelia cordata painting on the ceiling of the Natural History Museum, London.jpg|alt1=Ottelia|caption1= Archaic panel depicting ''[[Ottelia]]'' and a stylised bird|image2= Nathaniel Wallich05.jpg|alt2=Curcuma|caption2= ''[[Curcuma]]'', Nathaniel Wallich (1832)}}\nAbove the six-panel sets and adjacent to the apex of the roof lie the top rows of panels. These panels, called the \"archaic\" panels by Waterhouse, are of a radically different design to those below. Each panel is surrounded by gilded strips and set against a dark green background, rather than the pale cream of the six-panel sets; the archaic panels also continue beyond the six panel sets and over the landing of the main staircase, to run the full length of the Central Hall.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=48}}\n\nThe archaic panels depict flattened, stylised plants in pale colours with gilt highlighting, sometimes accompanied by birds, butterflies and insects.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=58}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=51}} Unlike the six-panel sets the archaic panels are not labelled, and while some plants on the archaic panels are recognisable others are stylised beyond recognition.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=51}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=122}}\n\nNo records survive of how Waterhouse and Lea selected the designs for the archaic panels,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=52}} or on from which images they were derived.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=129}} Owing to the flattened nature of the designs, it is possible that they were based on [[pressed flowers]] in the museum's [[herbarium]], or on illustrations in the British Museum's collection of books on botany.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=52}} Some of the archaic panels appear to be simplified versions of the illustrations in [[Nathaniel Wallich]]'s book ''[[Plantae Asiaticae Rariores]]''.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=54}}\n\n===Balconies===\n{{multiple image|align= right|direction= horizontal|total_width= 400|caption_align= left|image1= Central Hall, Natural History Museum, London 20181216 101316 (45613574294).jpg|alt1=Balcony ceiling panels|caption1= Panels from the balcony ceiling, with a lizard, snail, bird and crab|image2= Central Hall, Natural History Museum, London 20181216 100923 (45613575774).jpg|alt2=Lobby ceiling panel|caption2= A northern lobby ceiling depicting birds, insects, butterflies and paterae}}\nThe ceiling of the balconies flanking the Central Hall are also decorated, albeit to a far more simple design. The ceilings are painted with a stencilled motif of square panels, each containing a small illustration of a different plant or animal. All the birds and insects from the archaic panels are included; the panels also feature cacti, cockatoos, crabs, daisies, fish, hawks, lizards, octopuses, pinecones, pomegranates, snails and snakes.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=61}} The ceilings of the lobbies at the northern end of each balcony\u2014originally the entrances to the museum's refreshment room\u2014are each decorated with a single large panel of stencilled birds, insects, butterflies and [[patera]]e.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=61}}\n\n===South landing===\n{{multiple image|align= right|direction= horizontal|total_width= 400|caption_align= left|image1= Natural History Museum Main Hall, London, UK - Diliff.jpg|alt1=Central Hall from the landing|caption1= Unlike the intentionally exposed girders of the main hall, the supporting arches above the landing are enclosed within terracotta facing.|image2= Central Hall, Natural History Museum, London 20181216 101528 (46286407432).jpg|alt2=Nine botanical panels|caption2= A nine-panel set from above the landing. The archaic panels' style remains the same, but each lower panel depicts a separate species.}}\nUnlike the cavernous, intentionally cathedral-like feel of the main space of the Central Hall,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=25}}<!-- this is the cite for \"intentionally cathedral-like --> the ceiling of the landing above the main entrance, connecting the balconies to the upper level, has a different design.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=66}} Instead of the exposed and decorated iron girders of the main space, the structural girders of this end of the building are faced in the same terracotta style as the building's walls.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=66}} As the structure of the landing and staircases meant that the ceiling at this end of the room was not clearly visible from the ground floor, there was less of a need to make the designs appear attractive from far below; instead, the design of this stretch of the ceiling was intended to be viewed from a relatively close distance.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=67}}\n\nAs with the rest of the Hall, the ceiling is still divided into blocks of nine panels.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=67}} The archaic panels still run the full length, providing a thematic and visual connection with the rest of the ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=51}} The six lower panels of each set do not depict a single plant spreading across each set of panels; instead, each of the 36 panels in the lower two rows depicts a different plant.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=67}} These each represent a plant considered of particular significance to the British Empire.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=123}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=67}}\n\n==North Hall==\nArchways flanking the northern staircase to the balcony level lead to the North Hall, intended by Owen for a display of the natural history of the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=100}} Waterhouse designed a ceiling for the North Hall representing this theme.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}} As with the Central Hall, this ceiling comprises rows of panels above a long skylight along each side of the room; there are two rows per side rather than three, and nine panels on each row.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}} Unlike the archaic panels in the top row of the Central Hall, the upper rows on each side consist of plain green panels, each containing a heraldic rose, thistle or shamrock in representation of England, Scotland and Ireland, the three nations then constituting the constituent parts of the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}} (Wales was not represented, as in this period it was considered a part of England.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}})\n\n[[File:Ceiling of the North Hall (now the canteen), Natural History Museum, London.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.5|alt=North Hall ceiling|The ceiling of the smaller North Hall depicts native British plants against a green background.]]\nIn keeping with Owen's intent that the room be used for a display on the topic of the British Isles,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=103}} the nine lower panels on each side each illustrate a different plant found in Britain or Ireland.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}}{{efn-ua|It is now known that five of the 18 plants depicted in the North Hall are not native to the British Isles but were introduced by humans.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=103}}}} The plants depicted were chosen to illustrate the variety of plant habitats in the British Isles.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=103}}{{efn-ua|The only significant habitat type found in the British Isles not represented on the North Hall ceiling is [[moorland]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=103}}}} Uniquely in the building, the ceiling panels of the North Hall make use of [[Silver leaf (art)|silver leaf]] as well as gilt.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}} (During conservation work in 2016 it was found that initially some panels in the Central Hall had also made use of silver leaf, but the silver sections had subsequently been overpainted with [[ochre]].<ref name=\"HiddenTreasures\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/discover/hidden-treasures-above-heads.html|title=Hidden treasures above our heads|last=Pavid|first=Katie|date=24 April 2016|publisher=[[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]]|accessdate=8 April 2019|location=London}}</ref>) The style of illustration is similar to that of those over the south landing,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}} but instead of the pale backgrounds of the main ceiling and the panels above the landing, the illustrations in the North Hall are set against a dark green background; Waterhouse's intent was that the darker colour scheme would create an intimate feel by making the ceiling appear lower.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=103}}\n\nOne of the last parts of the initial museum to be completed, the display of British natural history in the North Hall was somewhat arbitrary, and did not reflect Owen's original intentions.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}} Stuffed native animals such as birds and rats were exhibited, alongside prize-winning racehorses, common domesticated animals such as cows and ducks, and an exhibit on commonly grown crops and garden vegetables and on the control of insects.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}} The display was unsuccessful, and was later removed,{{efn-ua|The museum eventually opened a more coherent display on the natural history of Britain in a second floor gallery.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}}}} with the North Hall used as a space for temporary exhibitions before eventually becoming the museum's cafeteria.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}}{{efn-ua|The original refreshment room had been on the balcony level between the Central and North Halls.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=61}} It was illuminated by large stained glass windows overlooking both Halls.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=100}}}}\n\n==After completion==\n{{quote|text=The walls and the ceilings are decorated, as befits a Palace of Nature, with all the varieties of animal and vegetable life, and the more striking fossil remains&nbsp;... Not the least admirable part of the plan is the great central hall, to be furnished and ornamented as an index to the contents of the museum. Though its proportions are magnificent, it will only be an epitome of the whole collection. The idea seems to have been suggested by the Reference Library of 60,000 volumes in the Reading Room of the British Museum, which this hall will almost equal in size, though of a very different form. We are sure that Londoners will be very glad to hear that they have now the opportunity of pursuing the most delightful of all studies in a true Temple of Nature, showing, as it should, the Beauty of Holiness.|author=''The Times'' on the opening of the Natural History Museum, 18 April 1881<ref name=\"TimesOpening\" />}}\n\n[[File:Terracotta monkey in the Natural History Museum Central Hall.jpg|right|upright|thumb|alt=Terracotta monkey|A terracotta monkey on a supporting column in the Central Hall]]\nAlthough the terracotta decorations of the museum do contain some botanical motifs, most of the decor of the building with the exception of the ceiling depicts animals,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=123}} with extinct species depicted on the east wing and extant species on the west.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=71}}{{efn-ua|The sculptures on the interior and exterior of the building reflect the original layout of its displays. Those parts of the building east of the Central Hall were intended by Owen and Waterhouse to be used for geological specimens, and are decorated with sculptures of extinct species known only from fossils; those parts to the west were to be used for the display of extant species, and are decorated with sculptures of living plants and animals.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=71}} The division is not absolute; bats are depicted on the east wing among extinct species, while [[ammonite]]s are depicted among the living species on the west wing.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=71}}}} A statue of [[Adam]] originally stood between the two wings over the main entrance, celebrating humanity as the peak of creation, but was dislodged during the Second World War and not replaced.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=58}}{{efn-ua|In Waterhouse's initial design the main entrance was topped with statues of both Adam and Eve, but after his original plan for a level [[parapet]] was replaced by a [[gable]], mounting two statues became impractical and only Adam was included.{{sfn|Girouard|1981|p=57}}}} Much was written at the time of the museum's opening about the terracotta decorations of the museum, but very little was written about how the ceiling was received.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=27}} Knapp & Press (2005) speculate that the apparent lack of public interest in the design of the ceiling could be owing to the prevalence of [[William Morris]]'s ornate floral wallpaper and fabric designs rendering the decorations of the ceiling less unusual to Victorian audiences than might be expected.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=28}}\n\n===Deterioration, restoration and conservation===\nDuring the construction of the building Waterhouse had been under intense pressure from the trustees to cut costs, and consequently was forced to abandon his proposed wooden ceiling.{{sfn|Thackray|Press|2001|p=69}} Instead, beneath a [[slate roof]], the ceilings were constructed of [[lath]] and plaster. The ribs that frame the panels were reinforced with animal hair, but the panels themselves were not reinforced.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=117}} As a consequence, the ceiling panels are unusually susceptible to vibration and to expansion and contraction caused by temperature variations.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=117}}\n\nThe elaborate nature of the building's design means that its roof slopes at multiple angles, with numerous gutters and gullies, all of which are easily blocked by leaves and wind-blown detritus.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=118}} As such, during periods of heavy rainfall water often penetrates the slate roof and reaches the fragile plaster ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=118}} In 1924 and 1975, the museum has been obliged to repair and restore the ceilings owing to water damage.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=118}} The height of the Central Hall ceiling made this a complicated and expensive process, requiring floor-to-ceiling scaffolding across the length and width of the Central Hall.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=118}} The need to avoid damage to the fragile mosaic flooring and the terracotta tiling on the walls caused further difficulty in erecting the scaffolding.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=120}} The exact nature and the cost of the repairs conducted in 1924 and 1975 is unknown, as is the identity of the restorers, as the relevant records have been lost, although it is known that cracks in the ceiling were filled with plaster and the paintwork and gilding retouched;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|pp=120\u2013121}} it is possible that some of the panels were replaced entirely.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=121}}\n\nDuring the Second World War, South Kensington was heavily bombed. The north, east, south and west of the building sustained direct bomb hits; the east wing in particular suffered severe damage and its upper floor was left a burned-out shell. The bombs missed the centre of the museum, leaving the fragile ceilings of the Central and North Halls undamaged.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=117}}\n\n[[File:Whale skeleton (39940686951).jpg|right|thumb|alt=Whale skeleton hanging from ceiling|In 2017 a blue whale skeleton was suspended from the ceiling of the recently renamed Hintze Hall, replacing the \"Dippy\" ''Diplodocus'' cast which had stood there for many years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/discover/news/2018/september/secret-history-of-hope-the-blue-whale-finally-revealed.html|title=The secret history of Hope the blue whale has finally been revealed|last=Davis|first=Josh|date=21 September 2018|publisher=[[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]]|accessdate=8 April 2019|location=London}}</ref>]]\nSince the 1975 restoration the ceiling once more began to deteriorate, individual sections of plaster becoming unkeyed (detached from their underlying laths),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=122}} paintwork peeling from some panels,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=121}} and the delicate plasterwork cracking.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|pp=121\u2013122}} The ends of the Central Hall suffered the worst deterioration, with some cracks above the landing and the northern end of the hall becoming large enough to be visible to the naked eye, while the gilding in the North Hall became gradually tarnished.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=122}}\n\nIn 2001 a systematic programme for the conservation of the ceilings was instituted.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=121}} A specialised [[hoist (device)|hoist]] is regularly used to allow a surveyor to take high [[image resolution|resolution]] photographs of each panel from a close distance, and the images of each panel used to create a [[time series]] for each panel.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=121}} This permits staff to monitor the condition of each panel for deterioration.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=121}}\n\nIn 2014, following a \u00a35,000,000 donation from businessman [[Michael Hintze]], Central Hall was formally renamed Hintze Hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-27319973|title=Natural History Museum receives \u00a35m donation|date=8 May 2014|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=8 April 2019|location=London}}</ref> In 2016, in conjunction with works to replace the \"[[Dippy (London)|Dippy]]\" cast of a ''[[Diplodocus]]'' skeleton which had previously been the Central Hall's centrepiece with the skeleton of a [[blue whale]] suspended from the ceiling, further conservation work took place. The cracks in the plasterwork were filled, and flaked or peeling paintwork was repaired with [[Japanese tissue]].<ref name=\"HiddenTreasures\" />\n\n==Layout of the ceiling panels==\n===Central Hall panels===\n[[image:Hintze Hall ceiling\u2014Nicotiana tabacum.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Tobacco plant|''[[Nicotiana tabacum]]'' as pictured on the ceiling]]\nThe panels are arranged in blocks of nine. The two central, uppermost rows (55\u2013108) constitute the archaic panels. Of the outer two rows, in the six blocks at the southern end of the hall above the landing and the main entrance (1\u201318 and 109\u2013126) each panel depicts a different plant considered of particular significance to the British Empire,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=67}} while the twelve six-panel blocks above the main hall (19\u201354 and 127\u2013162) each depict a single plant considered of particular importance to visitors or to the history of the museum, spreading across six panels.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}} \n[[File:Natural History Museum, London, Central Hall ceiling layout.png|left|alt=|800px]]\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|1\n|''[[Garcinia hanburyi]]'', a variety of gamboge tree (misspelled on the ceiling as ''Garcinia hanburyii'').{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}} Gamboge trees were the traditional source of [[gamboge]], the dark yellow pigment of the clothing worn by [[Bhikkhu|Buddhist monks]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=10IMFSavIMsC&pg=PA1352&lpg=PA1352&dq|title=Mansfeld's Encyclopedia of Agricultural and Horticultural Crops: (Except Ornamentals)|last=Hanelt|first=Peter|date=11 May 2001|publisher=Springer|accessdate=8 August 2011|isbn=9783540410171}}</ref>\n|-\n|2\n|''[[Docynia|Pyrus indica]]'' (now ''Docynia indica''), the Indian pear.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}} Native to South and Southeast Asia, the fruit is used to produce juice, wine and related products.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Ha Van Tiep, Pham Huu Thuong, La Nguyen, Hoang Thi Lua, Vu Van Thuan, Lo Thi Kieu, Sammy Carsan, Ann Degrande, Delia Catacutan, Chris Harwood|year=2018|title=Domestication of ''Docynia indica'' in Vietnam|journal=Forests, Trees and Livelihoods|publisher=Taylor & Francis|location=Abingdon|volume=27|issue=4|pages=230\u2013242|doi=10.1080/14728028.2018.1511480}}</ref>\n|-\n|3\n|''[[Cornus capitata]]'', the evergreen dogwood, was a popular ornamental plant.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}}\n|-\n|4\n|''[[Coffea arabica]]'', the Arabian coffee plant,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}} was the main cultivar of [[coffee]]. Coffee had been one of Britain's most popular drinks since being introduced to Britain from the Middle East by [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]] traders in the early 17th century.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|pp=82\u201383}}{{efn-ua|As early as 1675, London contained over 3000 coffee-houses.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=81}}}} At the time the museum was built the coffee trade was dominated by the [[Dutch East Indies]], but British colonists were planting huge coffee plantations in [[British East Africa]] (now Kenya).{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}}\n|-\n|5\n|''[[Nicotiana tabacum]]'', the tobacco plant.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}} Tobacco from ''[[Nicotiana rustica]]'' (Aztec tobacco) had been introduced to England from the failed [[Roanoke Colony]], the first British attempt at permanent settlement in North America, but the taste proved unpopular in European markets.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=68}} In an effort to make the [[Colony of Virginia]] economically self-sufficient, settler [[John Rolfe]] began to plant seeds of the milder and better-tasting ''Nicotiana tabacum'' imported from Spanish colonies to the south.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=69}} The climate and soil of Virginia proved ideal for the cultivation of tobacco, which soon became the principal export of the colony.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=69}} The economic benefits of tobacco farming led to the colony prospering and to British expansion along the coast of North America, while the labour-intensive processes involved in tobacco production led to Britain entering the [[Atlantic slave trade]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=71}}\n|-\n|6\n|''[[Gossypium barbadense]]'', extra-long staple cotton (also known as sea cotton).{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=151}} Cotton imported from the Mediterranean had been in limited use in Britain since the 16th century, but expansion in India led to [[muslin]] and [[calico]]\u2014both made from ''[[Gossypium arboreum]]'' (tree cotton)\u2014being imported to Britain in large quantities.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=73}} Cotton-based fabrics were highly prized in Africa; as a consequence, Indian-made fabrics were traded by the British to African rulers in exchange for slaves, who in turn were shipped to North America to work in the tobacco industry.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=73}} In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, as the [[Industrial Revolution]] began, raw cotton began to be shipped to Britain to be woven into fabrics in the newly built [[cotton mill]]s.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=74}} To supply these mills, ''Gossypium barbadense'' was planted across the southern states of the newly independent United States, largely staffed with cheap slave labour; as it had longer fibres than the tree cotton of India, it was more suitable for weaving in the new industrial mills.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=74}} The plant was fundamental to both the British and the American economies; at the time the museum opened cotton accounted for more than half the value of exports from the US to Britain,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=74}} and approximately one in 10 jobs in Britain were connected to the cotton industry.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=77}}{{efn-ua|Alfred Waterhouse was a [[Quaker]] and an active [[abolitionist]], and would have been well aware of the significance of ''Gossypium barbadense''.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=77}}}}\n|-\n|7\n|''[[Prunus amygdalus]]'', the almond,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} was religiously significant in Christianity, being described in the Bible as among \"the best fruits in the land\".<ref>{{Bibleverse|Genesis|43:11|KJV}}</ref>\n|-\n|8\n|''[[Myroxylon balsamum|Myroxylon pereira]]'' (now ''Myroxylon balsamum''), was the source of [[Balsam of Peru]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} Balsam of Peru was a significant ingredient in perfumes and was also a commonly used food flavouring and traditional medication.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/balsam-of-peru|title=Balsam of Peru|work=ScienceDirect|publisher=Elsevier|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|9\n|''[[Butea frondosa]]'', flame-of-the-forest or dhaak,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} an Indian plant whose sap was an important source of [[tannin]].{{sfn|Cowen|1984|p=3}}\n|-\n|10\n|''[[Quercus tinctoria]]'', the black oak (now called ''Quercus velutina''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} is a North American species that was endemic in most of the former British American colonies.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=79}} It was valuable as a source of timber,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=79}} and also as the source of [[quercitron]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=77}} Before the invention of synthetic pigments in the 19th century quercitron was one of the most commonly used dyes in Europe, and was primarily imported through [[Glasgow]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=80}}\n|-\n|11\n|''[[Magnolia fraseri|Magnolia auriculata]]'', the big-leaf magnolia (now called ''Magnolia fraseri''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} was native to the [[Blue Ridge Mountains]] in the Appalachians. Imported to Europe in large quantities, it became a hugely popular ornamental plant.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|pp=80\u201381}} This design was one of the two sample images that persuaded Acton Smee Ayrton to authorise the decoration of the ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}}\n|-\n|12\n|''[[Citrus bergamia]]'', the bergamot orange.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=152}} Bergamot is commonly used in perfume,{{sfn|Draelos|2015|p=57}} and also gives [[Earl Grey tea]] its distinctive flavour and scent.<ref name=GRIN>{{GRIN|''Citrus bergamia''}}</ref>\n|-\n|13\n|''[[Aesculus hippocastanum]]'', the horse chestnut,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} was native to the Balkans but had been cultivated throughout Europe. A popular ornamental plant, its hard seeds (known as [[conkers]]) were thought to be of medicinal benefit to horses.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Lack, H. Walter | title = The Discovery and Rediscovery of the Horse Chestnut | journal = Arnoldia | volume = 61 | issue = 4 | url = http://arnoldia.arboretum.harvard.edu/pdf/articles/628.pdf|page=15}}</ref>\n|-\n|14\n|''[[Strychnos nux-vomica]]'', the strychnine tree, is native to India.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} In 19th-century Britain [[strychnine]], produced from the tree's fruit, was one of the most commonly used poisons, and of high commercial significance as a [[rodenticide]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|15\n|''[[Gluta usitata|Melanorrh\u0153a usitata]]'', Burmese lacquer (now known as ''Gluta usitata''), was traditionally used as a source of varnish in [[Burma]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} As an Asian plant that would grow in the British climate, it was a popular ornamental plant in the 19th century.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=94}}\n|-\n|16\n|''[[Rhododendron maddenii|Rhododendron formosum]]'', a subspecies of ''Rhododendron maddenii'',{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} represents the many species of [[rhododendron]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=95}} Rhododendrons were widely found in [[Nepal]] and the Himalayan foothills, a region with a similar climate to the British Isles, and as a consequence these plants flourished in the cool damp British climate.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=94}} Rhododendrons and the closely related [[azalea]]s became hugely popular as ornamental plants in the 19th century, and a mainstay of 19th-century gardening.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=80}} Several rhododendron and azalea cultivars have subsequently spread throughout Britain and other territories previously controlled or influenced by Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=95}}\n|-\n|17\n|''[[Saccharum officinarum]]'', the most common species of [[sugarcane]], at the time the primary source of [[sugar]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} Although historically sugar was rarely used in Britain, it became hugely popular in the 18th century; in 1750 sugar constituted around one fifth of all European imports, and the overwhelming majority of these imports came from British and French [[slave plantation]]s in the Caribbean.{{sfn|Ponting|2000|p=510}} In the 19th century the popularity of sugar continued to rise; over the fifty years from 1800 to 1850 the ''per capita'' British consumption of sugar doubled.{{sfn|Ponting|2000|p=698}}\n|-\n|18\n|''[[Prunus domestica]]'', the most common species of [[plum]] tree.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=153}} Believed to be one of the first fruit trees to be domesticated,<ref>{{cite book|title=Horticultural Reviews (Volume 23)|editor=Jules Janick|year=1998|isbn=978-0471254454|publisher=Wiley}}</ref> plums\u2014particularly the [[Damson]]\u2014were an important component of English cuisine.\n|-\n|19\u201324\n|''[[Banksia speciosa]]'', the showy banksia,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=130}} was an Australian plant that was rarely grown in Britain, and was unlikely to be familiar to British audiences. It is probable that it was included as a tribute to Joseph Banks, naturalist on [[HMS Endeavour|HMS ''Endeavour'']], {{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=41}} after whom the [[genus]] was named,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=44}} and whose 1820 bequest of his collections formed much of the core of the British Museum's botanical displays.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=41}} Although named for Banks, ''Banksia speciosa'' was not one of the species collected by him on the ''Endeavour'' voyage, but was first described by [[Robert Brown (botanist, born 1773)|Robert Brown]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=47}}\n|-\n|25\u201330\n|''[[Amygdalus persica]]'', the peach tree.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=131}} Although peaches do not grow well in Britain, they were nonetheless a popular fruit at the time.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=33}} At the time the museum was built, peach trees were grown extensively in Britain in [[greenhouse|hothouses]] and against south-facing walls which were warmed by the sun, and peaches were considered a luxury item.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=36}}\n|-\n|31\u201336\n|''[[Theobroma cacao]]'', the cacao tree,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=132}} did not grow in Britain, but chocolate was highly popular in Britain at the time. It is possible that it was included as a tribute to Hans Sloane.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=44}}\n|-\n|37\u201342\n|''[[Quercus robur]]'', the English oak,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=133}} was considered a national symbol of England.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=32}} Oaks were long-lived, hardy and strong, all qualities the English associated with themselves; they were also a key element in English culture, having been used as a building material in much of England's most celebrated architecture, and as the traditional English building material for warships.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=32}}\n|-\n|43\u201348\n|''[[Vitis vinefera]]'', the grape vine.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=134}} Although not native to Britain, visitors would have been familiar with grapes from the manufacture of wine, at the time considered a luxury.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=39}}\n|-\n|49\u201354\n|''[[Citrus aurantium]]'', the Seville orange,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=135}} did not generally grow in Britain, but was a staple of British culture as a key ingredient in [[marmalade]] and perfume.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=38}}\n|-\n|55\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Butea frondosa]]'' (dhaak or flame-of-the-forest){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|56\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Arisaema]]'' (cobra lily){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|57\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Dillenia]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|58\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Piper (plant)|Piper]]'' (pepper), possibly ''[[Piper ribesioides]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|59\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Curcuma]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|60\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[orchid]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|61\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Aloe]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|62\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[orchid]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|63\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[Citrus \u00d7 sinensis|orange tree]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|64\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[orchid]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|65\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Ottelia]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|66\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Blighia sapida]]'' (ackee){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|67\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[dahlia]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|68\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Quassia amara]]'' (Surinam quassia-wood){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|69\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[rose]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|70\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Phytelephas]]'' (ivory palm){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|71\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Arbutus unedo]]'' (strawberry<!-- Don't link this to [[strawberry]], despite the name the plants are unrelated --> tree){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|72\n|Archaic panel depicting an unidentifiable stylised plant{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|73\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Aesculus hippocastanum]]'' (horse chestnut){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|74\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Markhamia stipulata]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|75\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Bletilla]]'' (urn orchid){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|76\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Papaver somniferum]]'' (opium poppy){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|77\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Matonia]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|78\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Momordica charantia]]'' (bitter melon or bitter apple){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|79\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Psidium guajava]]'' (common guava){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|80\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Helianthus annuus]]'' (common sunflower){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|81\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Punica granatum]]'' (pomegranate){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|82\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[orchid]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|83\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Pothos (plant)|Pothos]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|84\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Gladiolus]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=148}}\n|-\n|85\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[hellebore]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|86\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Tradescantia]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|87\n|Archaic panel depicting an unidentifiable stylised plant{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=149}}\n|-\n|88\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Inula helenium]]'' (elecampane){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|89\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Marantaceae]]'' (arrowroot){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|90\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Vanilla planifolia]]'' (vanilla orchid){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=150}}\n|-\n|91\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Asclepiadoideae]]'' (milkweed){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|92\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Aristolochiaceae]]'' (birthwort){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|93\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Passiflora]]'' (passion flower){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=142}}\n|-\n|94\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Digitalis purpurea]]'' (common foxglove){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|95\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Viburnum]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|96\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[iris (plant)|iris]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=143}}\n|-\n|97\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Rhododendron arboreum]]'' (tree rhododendron){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|98\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Alcea rosea]]'' (common hollyhock){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|99\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Ananas comosus]]'' (pineapple){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=144}}\n|-\n|100\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised [[lily]]{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|101\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Hedychium]]'' (ginger lily){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|102\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Gossypium]]'' (cotton){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=145}}\n|-\n|103\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Bertholletia excelsa]]'' (Brazil nut){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|104\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Magnolia fraseri]]'' (big-leaf magnolia){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|105\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Zantedeschia aethiopica]]'' (arum lily){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=146}}\n|-\n|106\n|Archaic panel depicting an unidentifiable stylised ''[[Asteraceae]]'' (daisy), thought to be ''[[Arctotis]]'' or ''[[Chrysanthemum]]''{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|107\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Lagerstroemia speciosa]]'' (crepe-myrtle){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|108\n|Archaic panel depicting a stylised ''[[Passiflora caerulea]]'' (common passion flower){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=147}}\n|-\n|109\n|''[[Camellia sinensis|Camellia thea]]'', the tea plant (now known as ''Camellia sinensis''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} is native to China, and [[tea]] made from its leaves has been drunk in China for millennia.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} Since the early 17th century limited quantities of tea were imported into Europe from China, but the drink remained expensive and was initially little known in Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} From the early 18th century onwards tea became popular and the British-owned [[East India Company]] began to import tea in large quantities from China.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} Chinese insistence on being paid in silver for tea, and for other exports such as porcelain, silk and spices, led to a trade deficits and to shortages of silver in Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} In 1773, in an effort to assist the East India Company and to reduce smuggling into its American colonies, Great Britain enacted the [[Tea Act]], allowing the Company to ship tea duty-free to [[British North America]], provoking the [[Boston Tea Party]] and subsequently the [[American War of Independence]]<!-- This is an article on a British topic in British English, don't change this to \"American Revolution\" or \"Revolutionary War\" as the terms aren't used in BrEng --> and the formation of the United States.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=92}} China remained the sole source of tea, but in 1826 the plant was found growing wild in the East India Company's newly-conquered territory of [[Colonial Assam|Assam]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=92}} In 1848 the East India Company sent botanist [[Robert Fortune]], disguised as a Chinese merchant, to visit China's tea-growing areas and steal seedlings of the highest quality tea plants;{{efn-ua|As a consequence of the trade deficit in silver, the East India Company began to pay for these goods with [[opium]] grown in its Indian territories, in violation of Chinese law.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} Chinese attempts to restrict the drug trade led to the [[First Opium War]] in which China was heavily defeated by the private army of the East India Company and the [[Royal Navy]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=91}} The establishment of European-controlled [[treaty ports]] in the wake of China's defeat made it significantly easier for European merchants to visit China and for Europeans to smuggle items out of China.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=92}}}} these were shipped to India in [[Wardian case]]s and planted in Assam and other Company-controlled areas of the Himalayan foothills with a similar climate.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=92}} These high quality tea plants flourished in these territories, and tea became one of the most important exports of [[British India]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=93}}\n|-\n|110\n|''[[Aloe succotrina]]'', Fynbos aloe,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} is endemic to the [[Cape Province]] of [[South Africa]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=84}} Since the days of the Roman Empire medicines derived from ''[[Aloe perryi]]'' had been imported from [[Socotra]] off the coast of north-east Africa,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}} and when European botanists first reached the Cape they assumed the native aloes to be the same plant as that grown in Socotra and named it accordingly.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}}{{efn-ua|Medicines derived from ''Aloe perryi'' were invariably exported to Europe in processed form. Consequently the botanists who assumed the aloes of mainland Africa to be identical to the aloes of Socotra had never seen a complete specimen of ''Aloe perryi'' and were unaware that it was a different species.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=84}}}} At the time the museum was built, aloe-based medicines were in common use.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}}\n|-\n|111\n|''[[Citrus medica]]'', the citron.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} The first [[citrus fruit]] to be cultivated,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Ram\u00f3n-Laca |first=L. |title=The Introduction of Cultivated Citrus to Europe via Northern Africa and the Iberian Peninsula |journal=Economic Botany |date=Winter 2003 |volume=57 |issue=4 |pages=502\u2013514 |doi=10.1663/0013-0001(2003)057[0502:tiocct]2.0.co;2}}</ref> since antiquity citrons had been an important ingredient in many medications.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=65}}\n|-\n|112\n|''[[Punica granatum]]'', the pomegranate,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} did not grow in the British climate and was rarely used in British cuisine.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}} It is likely that it was included owing to its [[Pomegranate#Symbolism|religious significance]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}} Along with ''Magnolia auriculata'', this was one of the two sample images that persuaded Ayrton to authorise the painted ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=21}}\n|-\n|113\n|''[[Quassia amara]]'', Surinam quassia-wood,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} grew widely in the then-British territory of [[British Guiana]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}} A natural [[insecticide]], it was valuable to 19th-century medicine as a treatment against parasites and as a [[larvicide]] to prevent [[mosquito]]es from breeding.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=83}}\n|-\n|114\n|''[[Ackee|Akesia africana]]'', the ackee,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=156}} is mislabelled on the ceiling; its scientific name was, and remains, ''Blighia sapida''.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=86}} (The scientific name ''Blighia sapida'' had been given to the ackee by staff at the British Museum, so the museum's staff would certainly have been aware of the correct name. Knapp & Press (2005) speculate that as the plant had been named by [[Charles Konig]],{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=163}} a mineralogist rather than a botanist, the museum's botanists may have been unhappy accepting the name.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=86}}) Ackee originated in West Africa, but was rarely cultivated there either by native inhabitants or by European settlers.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=86}} It was introduced to [[Jamaica]] in the 18th century as a cheap and nutritious food for the region's slaves;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=87}} it became widely popular there, and is now considered a symbol of Jamaica.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=86}}\n|-\n|115\n|''[[Diospyros embryopteris]]'', the guab tree or Malabar ebony, a traditional source of black dye.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}}\n|-\n|116\n|''[[Zea mays]]'', sweetcorn or maize,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}} was the staple food of much of the Americas before European colonisation. Able to grow in a wide variety of climates, by the time the museum was built it was cultivated worldwide.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=71}}\n|-\n|117\n|''[[Cassia fistula]]'', the golden shower tree, is an Indian plant.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}} A strong [[laxative]], in the 19th century it formed the basis of many European and traditional Indian medicines.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|118\n|''[[Calotropis procera]]'', the apple of Sodom,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}} was an inedible plant native to [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], and of little commercial use.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}} It is likely that Waterhouse and the devoutly religious Owen included this plant owing to its religious significance.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|119\n|''[[Cydonia oblonga|Pyrus cydonia]]'', the quince (now known as ''Cydonia oblonga''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}} was a commonly eaten food in 19th-century Europe, and was also often grown as an ornamental plant. Knapp & Press (2005) conjecture that the quince was included to allow visitors to compare a familiar plant with those more exotic species also depicted on the ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|120\n|''[[Garcinia indica]]'', the kokum, a commonly-used element in Indian cuisine.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=155}}\n|-\n|121\n|''[[Myristica fragrans]]'' is the source of [[nutmeg]],{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} for centuries one of the world's most valuable commodities.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=88}} Indigenous to the [[Maluku Islands]] (the Moluccas), it had historically been imported to Europe via land across Asia to the [[Ottoman Empire]] and onwards to Venice, and consequently was extremely scarce and expensive; it was the search for new routes to nutmeg markets that prompted the voyages of [[Vasco da Gama]] to India,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=88}} of [[Christopher Columbus]] to the Americas,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=88}} and of [[John Franklin]] to the [[Northwest Passage]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=90}} The Maluku Islands were controlled by the Dutch,{{efn-ua|Although the Maluku Islands were controlled by the Dutch, the tiny island of [[Run (island)|Run]] had been controlled by the English and was England's sole source of nutmeg. In the 1667 [[Treaty of Breda (1667)|Treaty of Breda]] England ceded Run to the Dutch in exchange for [[Manhattan]], giving the Netherlands a monopoly on the world's nutmeg trade.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=90}}}} but in 1810 during the [[Napoleonic Wars]] British troops briefly captured the [[Banda Islands]], seizing nutmeg trees which they subsequently planted in [[Ceylon]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=90}}\n|-\n|122\n|''[[Dillenia|Dillenia ornata]]'', now known as ''Dillenia aurea'',{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} is a flowering shrub native to present-day India, Myanmar and Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indiabiodiversity.org/species/show/225695|title=Dillenia aurea Smith|work=India Biodiversity Portal|publisher=Biodiversity India|accessdate=21 December 2018|location=Bangalore}}</ref> First described in Nathaniel Wallich's ''Plantae Asiaticae Rariores'', whose botanical illustrations inspired many of the ceiling's archaic panels, its bright yellow flowers and ability to grow in the British climate made it a popular [[ornamental plant]] in the 19th century.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=94}}\n|-\n|123\n|''[[Ilex aquifolium]]'', English holly,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} is one of the very few [[evergreen]] plants native to the British Isles.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}} A common motif in British folklore and in Christian and pre-Christian symbolism, it would have been immediately familiar to the museum's visitors; Knapp & Press (2005) speculate that Waterhouse intentionally included this highly recognisable plant to encourage viewers to examine the less-familiar species also pictured.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|124\n|''[[Ricinus communis]]'', the castor bean,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} was the source of [[castor oil]], one of Victorian Britain's most commonly used medications.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=84}} Castor oil was also a valuable [[lubricant]] in this period.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=84}} Although native to Africa, it had spread throughout tropical regions, and at the time was thought to originate in India.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=84}}\n|-\n|125\n|''[[Pyrus communis]]'', the European pear tree,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} was one of the most important native fruit trees in Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}} Its distinctive fruit would have been immediately recognisable to 19th-century viewers, serving to attract viewers to examine the ceiling more closely.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|126\n|''[[Prunus cerasus|Cerasus communis]]'', the sour cherry (now known as ''Prunus cerasus''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=154}} was introduced to Britain by the [[Roman Empire]] and flourished in the climate. Frequently used in English cookery, particularly [[cherry pie]], its distinctive red fruit would have been easily recognised by 19th-century visitors; Knapp & Press (2005) conjecture that as with the quince, it was included to allow viewers to compare this relatively familiar plant to the less recognisable species also illustrated.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=96}}\n|-\n|127\u2013132\n|''[[Eucalyptus globulus]]'', the Tasmanian blue gum tree.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=141}} Although not native to Britain, in this period it was grown widely in Spain for the production of [[eucalyptus oil]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=38}} Knapp & Press (2005) contend that this tree, with which British visitors were unlikely to have been familiar, was intentionally included among more familiar plants as a device to attract the attention of viewers.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=31}}\n|-\n|133\u2013138\n|''[[Pinus sylvestris]]'', the Scots pine,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=140}} Great Britain's only native species of pine.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=33}} As much of England had been cleared of woodland by this time, the remnants of the pine [[Caledonian Forest]] formed some of the most significant woodland in Britain, and the Scots pine was a national symbol of Scotland.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=33}} \n|-\n|139\u2013144\n|''[[Citrus limon]]um'', the lemon tree.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=139}} As with the orange, lemons rarely grew in Britain, but were also popular in British cuisine.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=36}}\n|-\n|145\u2013150\n|''[[Ficus carica]]'', the fig tree,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=138}} was largely unknown in Britain. As with the olive, figs and fig-leaves would have been familiar to 19th-century British visitors from the Biblical narrative;{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=38}} 19th-century visitors would likely have recognised the fig tree from its leaves rather than its fruit, owing to the use of fig-leaves in most depictions of [[Adam and Eve]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=41}}\n|-\n|151\u2013156\n|''[[Olea europea]]'', the olive tree,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=137}} was at the time almost unknown in Britain; they did not grow in the British climate, and both olives and olive oil were rarely used in British cookery. However, they would have been familiar to the museum's visitors, as olives were frequently mentioned in the Bible, and olive oil was often used as [[Chrism|holy oil]] by the Anglican Church.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=39}}\n|-\n|style=\"white-space: nowrap;\"|157\u2013162\n|''[[Pyrus malus]]'', the apple tree,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=136}} had for centuries been a staple fruit of the British diet.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=33}} As a cultivated fruit developed by agricultural selection, the apple also symbolised human dominance over nature.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=33}} At the time the ceilings were painted, botanists wrongly believed the apple tree to be descended from ''[[Malus sylvestris]]'', the crab apple, and consequently native to Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=35}}\n|}\n\n===North Hall panels===\n[[File:Ceiling of the North Hall, Natural History Museum, London.jpg|right|thumb|alt=North Hall ceiling|upright|Ceiling of the North Hall]]\nThere are two rows of nine panels apiece on each side of the apex.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=101}} The central (highest) rows on each side consist of plain green panels, each containing a heraldic rose, thistle or shamrock in representation of England, Scotland and Ireland, the three nations then constituting the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}} The nine lower panels on each side each illustrate a different plant found in Britain or Ireland.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=102}}\n[[File:Natural History Museum, London, North Hall ceiling layout.png|left|alt=|135px]]\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|1\n|''[[Lonicera periclymenum]]'', woodbine or common honeysuckle,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} is highly valued as an ornamental plant, and has one of the sweetest [[floral scent]]s of any native British plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.woodlandtrust.org.uk/visiting-woods/trees-woods-and-wildlife/plants-and-fungi/woodland-wildflowers/honeysuckle/|title=Honeysuckle (Lonicera periclymenum)|publisher=Woodland Trust|accessdate=6 April 2019|location=Grantham}}</ref>\n|-\n|2\n|''[[Malva sylvestris]]'', common mallow,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} is an [[archaeophyte]] (a species introduced to Britain before 1500).{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=106}} It grows on rough ground, particularly along roads, railways and the edges of fields.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=109}}\n|-\n|3\n|''[[Corylus avellana]]'', common hazel,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} is one of the most widely grown varieties used for commercial [[hazelnut]] production.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://homeguides.sfgate.com/hazelnut-plants-65404.html|title=Hazelnut Plants|language=en|access-date=6 April 2019}}</ref> \n|-\n|4\n|''[[Sonchus palustris]]'', marsh sowthistle.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}} Once a common species in Britain, its range was drastically reduced following the draining of [[the Fens]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}}\n|-\n|5\n|''[[Sambucus nigra]]'', elder,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}} was a common ornamental plant. At the time the museum was built it was also in common use as a [[herbal remedy]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=113}}\n|-\n|6\n|''[[Datura stramonium]]'', jimsonweed or thornapple,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}}{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=110}} is the only [[Neophyte (botany)|neophyte]] species (a species introduced after 1500 that now grows wild) represented on the North Hall ceiling.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=109}} A commonly found [[weed]], jimsonweed contains high levels of [[hyoscine]] (scopolamine), and at the time the museum was built was used as a herbal remedy for [[asthma]] and [[motion sickness]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=109}} Jimsonweed was also well known as a powerful [[hallucinogen]]; its name originates from an incident in 1676 in which troops stationed in [[Jamestown, Virginia|Jamestown]] during [[Bacon's Rebellion]] accidentally ate the plant and \"turn'd natural Fools\" for eleven days.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=110}}\n|-\n|7\n|''[[Bistorta officinalis|Polygonum bistorta]]'', common bistort (also known as ''Bistorta officinalis'' and ''Persicaria bistorta''),{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}} had been a common plant in the British Isles but its range was drastically reduced by cultivation.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}} It became popular as an ornamental plant, and spread from gardens to once more become a common species throughout the British Isles.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}}\n|-\n|8\n|[[Ranunculus|''Ranunculus lingua'']], greater spearwort,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}} is a close relative of the better-known [[buttercup]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=105}} It grows in the wild throughout the British Isles and Europe.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=105}}\n|-\n|9\n|''[[Helleborus niger]]'', Christmas rose,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=159}} is a shrub native to the [[Alps]]. Christmas rose was a popular ornamental plant but did not grow in the wild in the British Isles; Knapp & Press (2005) conjecture that Waterhouse included it to make the point that cultivated ornamental gardens also represented an important botanical habitat.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=112}}\n|-\n|10\n|''[[Chamaenerion angustifolium|Epilobium Angustifolium]]'', rosebay willowherb (also known as ''Chamaenerion angustifolium''){{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} was at the time the museum was built a relatively uncommon plant, found primarily in rocky uplands.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}} As a species able to grow in rocky areas and to propagate quickly via [[rhizome]]s into areas cleared of other species by burning, during the Second World War it spread rapidly in [[Strategic bombing during World War II|urban areas destroyed by bombing]],{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}} gaining rosebay willowherb the nickname of \"fireweed\" by which it remains frequently known.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=112}}\n|-\n|11\n|''[[Onopordum acanthium]]'', Scotch thistle,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} is a national emblem of Scotland<!-- I'm aware some historians believe that the species depicted in Scottish heraldry is Cirsium vulgare rather than Scotch thistle, but as far as the Victorian artists were aware O. acanthium was the species in question -->.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=106}} At the time the museum was built it was believed to have originated in [[East Anglia]], but is now thought to be an [[Introduced species of the British Isles|introduced species]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=107}}\n|-\n|12\n|''[[Helleborus viridis]]'', green hellebore,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} is native to Wales and the south and west of England.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=112}} A popular ornamental plant, it has spread from gardens and grows wild throughout Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=112}}\n|-\n|13\n|''[[Inula helenium]]'', elecampane,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} was a significant source of [[inulin]], and as such had been valued as a medicinal plant since the Roman era.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=106}} Although an introduced species, it has grown wild throughout Britain for centuries.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=109}}\n|-\n|14\n|''[[Digitalis purpurea]]'', common foxglove,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} has been a medicinal plant for millennia.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=113}} One of its active ingredients, [[digitoxin]], was the most significant drug for cardiac conditions at the time the museum was built.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=115}} \n|-\n|15\n|''[[Rosa canina]]'', dog rose,{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=157}} was a common ornamental species. It would also have been familiar to the museum's visitors as a plant then in common medicinal use.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=113}}\n|-\n|16\n|''[[Glaucium flavum|Glaucium luteum]]'', yellow horned poppy (now known as ''Glaucium flavum'').{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} A source of [[glaucine]],<ref>{{cite journal |author1=G.B. Lapa |author2=O.P. Sheichenko |author3=A.G. Serezhechkin |author4=O.N. Tolkachev |date=August 2004 |title=HPLC Determination of Glaucine in Yellow Horn Poppy Grass (''Glaucium flavum Crantz'') |journal=Pharmaceutical Chemistry Journal |volume=38 |issue=1 |pages=441\u2013442 |issn=0091-150X |doi=10.1023/B:PHAC.0000048907.58847.c6 |quote=S-(+)-Glaucine (C<sub>21</sub>H<sub>25</sub>NO<sub>4</sub>) is the main alkaloid component in the grass of yellow horn poppy (''Glaucium luteum L.'', syn. ''Glaucium flavum Crantz'') of the ''Papaveraceae'' family}}</ref> it is used as a [[antitussive|cough suppressant]].<ref>R\u00fchle KH, Criscuolo D, Dieterich HA, K\u00f6hler D, Riedel G. Objective evaluation of dextromethorphan and glaucine as antitussive agents. ''British Journal of Clinical Pharmacology''. 1984 May;17(5):521-4. {{PMID|6375709}}</ref>\n|-\n|17\n|''[[Aconitum napellus]]'', monk's hood or wolfsbane.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} ''Aconitum napellus napellus'', the subspecies found in Britain, is one of the few plants [[endemic]] to Britain.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=105}}\n|-\n|style=\"white-space: nowrap;\"|18{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}{{nbsp}}\n|''[[Daphne laureola]]'', spurge laurel.{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=158}} As a plant toxic to mammals but not to birds, it was widely cultivated on [[English country house|country estates]] to provide [[ground cover]] for the rearing of [[pheasants]] for [[pheasant shooting|shooting]].{{sfn|Knapp|Press|2005|p=111}}\n|}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist-ua|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=25em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book |title=Flowering Trees and Shrubs in India, Sixth Edition|last=Cowen|first=D. V.|year=1984|publisher=Thacker and Co|oclc=803751318|location=Bombay|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Draelos|first=Zoe Diana|title=Cosmetic Dermatology: Products and Procedures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D2a-CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA57|year=2015|publisher=Wiley|isbn=978-1-118-65546-7|location=Chichester, UK|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Girouard|first=Mark|authorlink=Mark Girouard|title=Alfred Waterhouse and the Natural History Museum|year=1981|edition=1999|publisher=Natural History Museum|location=London|isbn=978-0-565-09135-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Knapp|first1=Sandra|authorlink1=Sandra Knapp|last2=Press|first2=Bob|title=The Gilded Canopy|year=2005|publisher=Natural History Museum|location=London|isbn=978-0-565-09198-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ponting|first=Clive|authorlink=Clive Ponting|year=2000|title=World History: A New Perspective|location=London|publisher=Chatto & Windus|isbn=0-7011-6834-X|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stearn|first=William T.|authorlink=William T. Stearn|title=The Natural History Museum at South Kensington|year=1980|publisher=Natural History Museum|location=London|isbn=978-0-565-09030-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Thackray|first1=John|last2=Press|first2=Bob|title=Nature's Treasurehouse: A History of the Natural History Museum|edition=2013|year=2001|publisher=Natural History Museum|location=London|isbn=978-0-565-09318-1|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Natural History Museum, London, Central Hall ceiling|Hintze Hall ceiling}}\n*[https://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/beta/exhibit/ZgIC0U5-YXGjLg Interactive and zoomable ultra-high-definition images of the Hintze Hall ceiling] at the [[Google Cultural Institute]]\n\n{{Coord|51|29|46|N|00|10|35|W|region:GB|display=title}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n[[Category:Natural History Museum, London]]\n[[Category:Alfred Waterhouse buildings]]\n[[Category:Painted ceilings]]\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ceilings_of_the_Natural_History_Museum,_London"}
{"title_page": "Li Fengbao", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder<!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Li Fengbao\n| native_name = \n| alias       = \n| birth_name  =  \n| image       = File:Qing dynasty diplomat Li Fengbao.jpg|thumb|\n| imagesize   =\n| caption     = Li in [[Vienna]]\n| birth_date  = 1834\n| birth_place = [[Chongming District|Chongming]], [[Jiangsu Province]], [[Qing Empire]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1887|08|06|1834|df=y}}\n| death_place =  [[Chongming District|Chongming]], [[Jiangsu Province]], [[Qing Empire]]\n| occupation  = [[Diplomat]], politician, government official\n| nationality = [[Qing]] [[China|Chinese]]\n| education =  \n|office1       = [[Chinese Ambassador to France]]\n|term_start1   = 1884\n|term_end1     = 1884\n|predecessor1  = [[Xu Jingcheng]] (didn't take office)\n|successor1    = [[Xu Jingcheng]]\n}}\n'''Li Fengbao'''(1834-1887,<ref name=\":1\" /> {{Lang-zh|c=|s=\u674e\u51e4\u82de|t=\u674e\u9cf3\u82de}}), [[courtesy name]] '''Haike'''(\u6d77\u5ba2), [[Art name]] '''Dan'ya'''(\u4e39\u6daf) was a late [[Qing dynasty]] Chinese diplomat. He was the imperial commissioner(ambassador) of China to [[German Empire|Germany]] between 1878 and 1884. During this time, Li also held the concurrent posts of the ambassador to [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungary]], [[Netherlands]](1881-1884)<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The Early Dutch Sinologists (1854-1900) (2 vols): Training in Holland and China, Functions in the Netherlands Indies|last=Kuiper|first=Koos|publisher=BRILL|year=2017|isbn=9789004339637|location=|pages=}}</ref> and [[Italia|Italy]].\n\n== Life ==\nLi was born in [[Chongming Island|Chongming]], then a part of [[Jiangsu|Jiangsu province]]. In his early years, he was especially fond of the study of [[astronomy]] as well as mapping, military strategy and phonology.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u660e\u6e05\u65f6\u671f\u4e0a\u6d77\u5730\u533a\u7684\u8457\u59d3\u671b\u65cf|last=Wu|first=Ren'an|publisher=\u4e0a\u6d77\u4eba\u6c11\u51fa\u7248\u793e|year=1997|isbn=9787208024762|location=Shanghai|page=304}}</ref> His talents were appreciated by [[Ding Richang]], governor of Jiangsu. Ding recommended him to [[Li Hongzhang]]. Under Li Hongzhang, Li Fengbao worked at [[Jiangnan Shipyard]] and [[Wusong Battery]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Krupp und die Modernisierung Chinas|last=Qiao|first=Wei|publisher=\u5929\u6d25\u53e4\u7c4d\u51fa\u7248\u793e|year=2001|isbn=9787805047850|location=|pages=74\u201376}}</ref>\n\nIn 1875, as a secretary of Li Hongzhang, he participated Hongzhang's meeting with British officer [[Thomas Francis Wade]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u6dee\u7cfb\u4eba\u7269\u5217\u4f20/\u6587\u804c\u00b7\u5317\u6d0b\u6d77\u519b\u00b7\u6d0b\u5458/\u6dee\u7cfb\u96c6\u56e2\u4e0e\u8fd1\u4ee3\u4e2d\u56fd|last=Ma|first=Changhua|publisher=Huangshan Shushe|year=1995|isbn=9787806300121|location=|page=145}}</ref> In 1877, he was appointed the supervisor of oversea Chinese student in [[British Empire|Britain]]. These students were sent by the Qing government with the purpose of learning advanced naval technologies. Along with Li was the French naval officer [[Prosper Giquel]] who was another supervisor of the students.\n\nIn August 1878, he was appointed the commissioner of China to Germany and later Austria-Hungary, Netherlands and Italy after his predecessor [[Liu Xihong]] was recalled to the imperial court.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Renditions|last=|first=|publisher=Research Centre for Translation, Chinese University of Hong Kong|year=2000|isbn=|location=|page=112}}</ref> Diplomatic affairs between France and China also concerned Li, according to historical records. During [[Sino-French War]], Li actively involved in the delivery of the battleship [[Chinese ironclad Dingyuan|Chinese ironclad ''Dingyuan'']] from Germany to China.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u6e05\u53f2\u8bba\u4e1b|last=|first=|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company|year=2002|isbn=9787504339348|location=|pages=156\u2013158}}</ref> In 1881, Li visited [[Leiden University]], Netherlands and met  with German scholar [[Johann Joseph Hoffmann]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAlthough being an experienced officer and diplomat, Li was not trusted by the conservative power-blocs in Qing's court. When [[Chinese cruiser Jiyuan|Chinese cruiser ''Jiyuan'']]'s construction was completed, rumors in Beijing spread and Li was accused of embezzlement of government funds. He was impeached by imperial censors and was dismissed once and for all from the court. Despite the fact that the cruiser Jiyuan functioned well after arriving in China, Li's dismissal was not reversed. In August 6, 1887, Li died in his hometown Chongming after suffering from depression for several years, aged 53.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u79cb\u98a8\u5bf6\u528d\u5b64\u81e3\u6dda\uff1a\u665a\u6e05\u7684\u653f\u5c40\u548c\u4eba\u7269\u7e8c\u7de8|last=Jiang|first=Ming|publisher=\u9999\u6e2f\u4e2d\u548c\u51fa\u7248\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|year=2016|isbn=9789888369195|location=Hongkong|pages=242\u2013252}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\nLi Fengbao contributed to the early advancement of modern Chinese artillery. He was among the first ones to translate technical documents of Western artillery. When the Qing dynasty government purchased cannons from [[Krupp]], his translations no doubt were the key to the understanding of the cannons' way of functioning.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn addition, Li Fengbao translated the German infantry drill codes from German to Chinese. This code in turn was adopted by the [[new armies]], modernized infantry troops of Qing dynasty.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Body and Military Masculinity in Late Qing and Early Republican China: The Art of Governing Soldiers|last=Schillinger|first=Nicolas|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2016|isbn=9781498531696|location=|page=74}}</ref>\n\nLi also left his \"Diary of the ministerial trip to Germany\"(\u4f7f\u5fb7\u65e5\u8a18). The diary is one of the few Qing dynasty historical documents that contains a detailed description of the Western society during the late 19th century.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u9ec4\u9075\u61b2\u5e2b\u53cb\u8a18|last=Jiang|first=Yinghao|publisher=Chinese University Press|year=2002|isbn=9789622018396|location=|page=173}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n\n[[Category:Qing dynasty diplomats]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of China to France]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of China to Italy]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of China to Austria]]\n[[Category:Chongming District]]\n[[Category:1834 births]]\n[[Category:1887 deaths]]\n[[Category:Chinese shipbuilders]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of embezzlement]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder<!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Li Fengbao\n| native_name = \n| alias       = \n| birth_name  =  \n| image       = File:Qing dynasty diplomat Li Fengbao.jpg|thumb|\n| imagesize   =\n| caption     = Li in [[Vienna]]\n| birth_date  = 1834\n| birth_place = [[Chongming]], [[Jiangsu Province]], [[Qing Empire]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1887|08|06|1834|df=y}}\n| death_place =  [[Chongming]], [[Jiangsu Province]], [[Qing Empire]]\n| occupation  = [[Diplomat]], politician, government official\n| nationality = [[Qing]] [[China|Chinese]]\n| education =  \n|office1       = [[Chinese Ambassador to France]]\n|term_start1   = 1884\n|term_end1     = 1884\n|predecessor1  = [[Xu Jingcheng]] (didn't take office)\n|successor1    = [[Xu Jingcheng]]\n}}\n'''Li Fengbao'''(1834-1887,<ref name=\":1\" /> {{Lang-zh|c=|s=\u674e\u51e4\u82de|t=\u674e\u9cf3\u82de}}), [[courtesy name]] '''Haike'''(\u6d77\u5ba2), [[Art name]] '''Dan'ya'''(\u4e39\u6daf) was a late [[Qing dynasty]] Chinese diplomat. He was the imperial commissioner(ambassador) of China to [[German Empire|Germany]] between 1878 and 1884. During this time, Li also held the concurrent posts of the ambassador to [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungary]], [[Netherlands]](1881-1884)<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The Early Dutch Sinologists (1854-1900) (2 vols): Training in Holland and China, Functions in the Netherlands Indies|last=Kuiper|first=Koos|publisher=BRILL|year=2017|isbn=9789004339637|location=|pages=}}</ref> and [[Italia|Italy]].\n\n== Life ==\nLi was born in [[Chongming Island|Chongming]], then a part of [[Jiangsu|Jiangsu province]]. In his early years, he was especially fond of the study of [[astronomy]] as well as mapping, military strategy and phonology.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u660e\u6e05\u65f6\u671f\u4e0a\u6d77\u5730\u533a\u7684\u8457\u59d3\u671b\u65cf|last=Wu|first=Ren'an|publisher=\u4e0a\u6d77\u4eba\u6c11\u51fa\u7248\u793e|year=1997|isbn=9787208024762|location=Shanghai|pages=304}}</ref> His talents were appreciated by [[Ding Richang]], governor of Jiangsu. Ding recommended him to [[Li Hongzhang]]. Under Li Hongzhang, Li Fengbao worked at [[Jiangnan Shipyard]] and [[Wusong Battery]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Krupp und die Modernisierung Chinas|last=Qiao|first=Wei|publisher=\u5929\u6d25\u53e4\u7c4d\u51fa\u7248\u793e|year=2001|isbn=9787805047850|location=|pages=74\u201376}}</ref>\n\nIn 1875, as a secretary of Li Hongzhang, he participated Hongzhang's meeting with British officer [[Thomas Francis Wade]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u6dee\u7cfb\u4eba\u7269\u5217\u4f20/\u6587\u804c\u00b7\u5317\u6d0b\u6d77\u519b\u00b7\u6d0b\u5458/\u6dee\u7cfb\u96c6\u56e2\u4e0e\u8fd1\u4ee3\u4e2d\u56fd|last=Ma|first=Changhua|publisher=Huangshan Shushe|year=1995|isbn=9787806300121|location=|pages=145}}</ref> In 1877, he was appointed the supervisor of oversea Chinese student in [[British Empire|Britain]]. These students were sent by the Qing government with the purpose of learning advanced naval technologies. Along with Li was the French naval officer [[Prosper Giquel]] who was another supervisor of the students.\n\nIn August 1878, he was appointed the commissioner of China to Germany and later Austria-Hungary, Netherlands and Italy after his predecessor [[Liu Xihong]] was recalled to the imperial court.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Renditions|last=|first=|publisher=Research Centre for Translation, Chinese University of Hong Kong|year=2000|isbn=|location=|pages=112}}</ref> Diplomatic affairs between France and China also concerned Li, according to historical records. During [[Sino-French War]], Li actively involved in the delivery of the battleship [[Chinese ironclad Dingyuan|Chinese ironclad ''Dingyuan'']] from Germany to China.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u6e05\u53f2\u8bba\u4e1b|last=|first=|publisher=Zhonghua Book Company|year=2002|isbn=9787504339348|location=|pages=156\u2013158}}</ref> In 1881, Li visited [[Leiden University]], Netherlands and met  with German scholar [[Johann Joseph Hoffmann]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAlthough being an experienced officer and diplomat, Li was not trusted by the conservative power-blocs in Qing's court. When [[Chinese cruiser Jiyuan|Chinese cruiser ''Jiyuan'']]'s construction was completed, rumors in Beijing spread and Li was accused of embezzlement of government funds. He was impeached by imperial censors and was dismissed once and for all from the court. Despite the fact that the cruiser Jiyuan functioned well after arriving in China, Li's dismissal was not reversed. In August 6, 1887, Li died in his hometown Chongming after suffering from depression for several years, aged 53.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u79cb\u98a8\u5bf6\u528d\u5b64\u81e3\u6dda\uff1a\u665a\u6e05\u7684\u653f\u5c40\u548c\u4eba\u7269\u7e8c\u7de8|last=Jiang|first=Ming|publisher=\u9999\u6e2f\u4e2d\u548c\u51fa\u7248\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|year=2016|isbn=9789888369195|location=Hongkong|pages=242\u2013252}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\nLi Fengbao contributed to the early advancement of modern Chinese artillery. He was among the first ones to translate technical documents of Western artillery. When the Qing dynasty government purchased cannons from [[Krupp]], his translations no doubt were the key to the understanding of the cannons' way of functioning.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn addition, Li Fengbao translated the German infantry drill codes from German to Chinese. This code in turn was adopted by the [[new armies]], modernized infantry troops of Qing dynasty.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Body and Military Masculinity in Late Qing and Early Republican China: The Art of Governing Soldiers|last=Schillinger|first=Nicolas|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2016|isbn=9781498531696|location=|pages=74}}</ref>\n\nLi also left his \"Diary of the ministerial trip to Germany\"(\u4f7f\u5fb7\u65e5\u8a18). The diary is one of the few Qing dynasty historical documents that contains a detailed description of the Western society during the late 19th century.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u9ec4\u9075\u61b2\u5e2b\u53cb\u8a18|last=Jiang|first=Yinghao|publisher=Chinese University Press|year=2002|isbn=9789622018396|location=|pages=173}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n\n[[Category:Qing dynasty diplomats]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of China to France]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of China to Italy]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of China to Austria]]\n[[Category:Chongming District]]\n[[Category:1834 births]]\n[[Category:1887 deaths]]\n[[Category:Chinese shipbuilders]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of embezzlement]]\n", "name_user": "Prisencolin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Chongming\u2192Chongming District(2) usingDab solver", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Li_Fengbao"}
{"title_page": "Post-postmodernism", "text_new": "{{Postmodernism}}\n{{short description|Artistic and philosophical movement}}\n'''Post-postmodernism''' is a wide-ranging set of developments in [[critical theory]], [[philosophy]], [[architecture]], [[art]], [[literature]], and [[culture]] which are emerging from and reacting to [[postmodernism]]. Another similar recent term is [[metamodernism]].\n\n==Periodization==\nMost scholars would agree that [[modernism]] began around 1900 and continued on as the dominant cultural force in the intellectual circles of Western culture well into the mid-twentieth century.<ref>Compare, for example:<br />{{cite book|last=Childs|first=Peter|title=Modernism|publisher=[[Routledge]]|location=New York|year=2008|isbn=978-0-415-41544-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-v8SXB4l7kcC|page=18}}: \"[modernism] is [...] primarily located in the years 1890-1930 [...]\"<br />{{cite book|last=Armstrong|first=Tim|title=Modernism: A Cultural History|publisher=[[Polity Press]]|location=Cambridge|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7456-2983-4|url=https://archive.org/details/modernismcultura0000arms|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/modernismcultura0000arms/page/24 24]|quote=[modernism] can be defined as a series of international artistic movements in the period 1900-40 [...].}}</ref> Like all eras, modernism encompasses many competing individual directions and is impossible to define as a discrete unity or totality. However, its chief general characteristics are often thought to include an emphasis on \"radical aesthetics, technical experimentation, spatial or rhythmic, rather than chronological form, [and] self-conscious reflexiveness\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Childs|first=Peter|title=Modernism|publisher=[[Routledge]]|location=New York|year=2008|isbn=978-0-415-41544-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-v8SXB4l7kcC|page=18}}</ref> as well as the search for authenticity in human relations, abstraction in art, and utopian striving. These characteristics are normally lacking in postmodernism or are treated as objects of irony.\n\n[[Postmodernism]] arose after World War II as a reaction to the perceived failings of modernism, whose radical artistic projects had come to be associated with [[totalitarianism]]<ref>Cf. Groys, Boris: ''The Total Art of Stalinism'', Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1992.</ref> or had been assimilated into mainstream culture. The basic features of what we now call postmodernism can be found as early as the 1940s, most notably in the work of [[Jorge Luis Borges]].<ref>See Barth, John: \u201c[[The Literature of Exhaustion]].\u201d ''The Atlantic Monthly'', August 1967, pp. 29-34.</ref> However, most scholars today would agree that postmodernism began to compete with modernism in the late 1950s and gained ascendancy over it in the 1960s.<ref>Cf., for example, Huyssen, Andreas: ''After the Great Divide. Modernism, Mass Culture, Postmodernism''. Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 1986, p. 188.</ref> Since then, postmodernism has been a dominant, though not undisputed, force in art, literature, film, music, drama, architecture, history, and continental philosophy. Salient features of postmodernism are normally thought to include the ironic play with styles, citations and narrative levels,<ref>See Hutcheon, Linda: ''A Poetics of Postmodernism. History, Theory, Fiction''. New York: Routledge, 1988, pp. 3-21; McHale, Brian: ''Postmodern Fiction'', London: Methuen, 1987.</ref> a metaphysical skepticism or [[nihilism]] towards a \"[[grand narrative]]\" of  Western culture,<ref>See Lyotard, Jean-Fran\u00e7ois, ''The Postmodern Condition: A Report on Knowledge'', Minneapolis: University of Minneapolis Press 1984</ref> a preference for the virtual at the expense of the real (or more accurately, a fundamental questioning of what 'the real' constitutes)<ref>See Baudrillard, Jean: \u201c[[Simulacra and Simulation]]s.\u201d In: ''Jean Baudrillard. Selected Writings''. Stanford: Stanford University Press 1988, pp. 166-184.</ref> and a \"waning of affect\"<ref>Jameson, Fredric: ''Postmodernism or, The Cultural Logic of Late Capitalism''. Durham: Duke University Press 1991, p. 16</ref> on the part of the subject, who is caught up in the free interplay of virtual, endlessly reproducible signs inducing a state of consciousness similar to schizophrenia.<ref>Jameson, Fredric: ''Postmodernism or, The Cultural Logic of Late Capitalism''. Durham: Duke University Press 1991, pp. 26-27.</ref>\n\nSince the late 1990s there has been a small but growing feeling both in popular culture and in academia that postmodernism \"has gone out of fashion.\"<ref>Potter, Garry and Lopez, Jose (eds.): ''After Postmodernism: An Introduction to Critical Realism''. London: The Athlone Press 2001, p. 4.</ref> However, there have been few formal attempts to define and name the era succeeding postmodernism, and none of the proposed designations has yet become part of mainstream usage.\n\nHowever, post-postmodernism in literature began with the publication of [[Bangladeshi]] poet [[Md. Ziaul Haque]]'s book of 'poetenry' (poems of ten lines) titled, ''Give Me a Sky to Fly'' in 2014.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Kabir Chowdhury | first = Fahmida | authorlink = Fahmida Kabir Chowdhury | title = Md. Ziaul Haque's ''Give Me a Sky to Fly'': The Beginning of Post-postmodernism in Literature | journal = International Journal of Humanities and Social Science Invention | volume = 3 | date = February 2014 | url = http://www.ijhssi.org/papers/v3(2)/Version-3/A032301011.pdf | accessdate = {{date|2020-04-16|mdy}}}}</ref>\n\n==Definitions==\nConsensus on what constitutes an era can not be easily achieved while that era is still in its early stages. However, a common theme of current attempts to define post-postmodernism is emerging as one where faith, trust, dialogue, performance, and sincerity can work to transcend postmodern [[irony]]. The following definitions, which vary widely in depth, focus, and scope, are listed in the chronological order of their appearance.\n\n===Turner's ''post-postmodernism''===\nIn 1995, the landscape architect and urban planner [[Tom Turner]] issued a book-length call for a post-postmodern turn in urban planning.<ref>''City as Landscape: A Post Post-modern View of Design and Planning'', (Taylor & Francis: London 1995).</ref> Turner criticizes the postmodern credo of \"anything goes\" and suggests that \u201cthe built environment professions are witnessing the gradual dawn of a post-Postmodernism that seeks to temper reason with faith.\u201d<ref>''City as Landscape: A Post Post-modern View of Design and Planning'', (Taylor & Francis: London 1995), p. 9.</ref> In particular, Turner argues for the use of timeless organic and geometrical patterns in urban planning. As sources of such patterns he cites, among others, the Taoist-influenced work of the American architect [[Christopher Alexander]], [[gestalt psychology]]  and the [[Psychoanalysis|psychoanalyst]] [[Carl Jung]]'s concept of [[Jungian archetypes|archetypes]]. Regarding terminology, Turner urges us to \"embrace post-Postmodernism \u2013 and pray for a better name.\"<ref>''City as Landscape: A Post Post-modern View of Design and Planning'', (Taylor & Francis: London 1995), p. 10; see also a summary of the book at [http://www.gardenvisit.com/history_theory/library_online_ebooks/architecture_city_as_landscape]</ref>\n\n===Epstein's ''trans-postmodernism''===\nIn his 1999 book on [[Russian postmodernism]] the Russian-American Slavist [[Mikhail Epstein]] suggested that postmodernism  \"is ... part of a much larger historical formation,\" which he calls \"[[postmodernity]]\".<ref>Epstein, Mikhail; Genis, Alexander; Vladiv-Glover, Slobodanka. ''Russian Postmodernism. New Perspectives on Post-Soviet Culture''. Berghahn Books: New York, 1999, p. 467.</ref> Epstein believes that postmodernist aesthetics will eventually become entirely conventional and provide the foundation for a new, non-ironic kind of poetry, which he describes using the prefix \"[[:wikt:trans-|trans-]]\":\n{{quote|In considering the names that might possibly be used to designate the new era following \"postmodernism,\" one finds that the prefix \"trans\" stands out in a special way. The last third of the 20th century developed under the sign of \"post,\" which signalled the demise of such concepts of modernity as \"truth\" and \"objectivity,\" \"soul\" and \"subjectivity,\" \"utopia\" and \"ideality,\" \"primary origin\" and \"originality,\" \"sincerity\" and \"sentimentality.\" All of these concepts are now being reborn in the form of \"trans-subjectivity,\" \"trans-idealism,\" \"trans-utopianism,\" \"trans-originality,\" \"trans-lyricism,\" \"trans-sentimentality\" etc.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.focusing.org/apm_papers/epstein.html | title=Epstein (specific) - the Place of Postmodernism in Postmodernity}}</ref>}} As an example Epstein cites the work of the contemporary Russian poet [[Timur Kibirov]].<ref>Epstein, Mikhail; Genis, Alexander; Vladiv-Glover, Slobodanka. ''Russian Postmodernism. New Perspectives on Post-Soviet Culture''. Berghahn Books: New York, 1999, pp. 457-460</ref>\n\n===Gans' ''post-millennialism''===\nThe term ''post-millennialism'' was introduced in 2000 by the American cultural theorist [[Eric Gans]]<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Gans | first = Eric | authorlink = Eric Gans | title = The Post-Millennial Age | journal = Anthropoetics | volume = 209 | date = June 3, 2000 | url = http://www.anthropoetics.ucla.edu/views/vw209/ | accessdate = {{date|2011-06-17|mdy}}}}</ref> to describe the era after postmodernism in ethical and socio-political terms. Gans associates postmodernism closely with \"victimary thinking,\" which he defines as being based on a non-negotiable ethical opposition between perpetrators and victims arising out of the experience of [[Auschwitz]] and [[Hiroshima]]. In Gans's view, the ethics of postmodernism is derived from identifying with the peripheral victim and disdaining the utopian center occupied by the perpetrator. Postmodernism in this sense is marked by a victimary politics that is productive in its opposition to modernist utopianism and totalitarianism but unproductive in its resentment of capitalism and liberal democracy, which he sees as the long-term agents of global reconciliation. In contrast to postmodernism, post-millennialism is distinguished by the rejection of victimary thinking and a turn to \"non-victimary dialogue\"<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Gans | first = Eric | authorlink = Eric Gans | title = Victimary Thinking Forever? | journal = Anthropoetics | volume = 230 | date = March 31, 2001 | url = http://www.anthropoetics.ucla.edu/views/vw230.htm | accessdate = {{date|2011-06-17|mdy}}}}</ref> that will \"diminish ... the amount of resentment in the world.\"<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Gans | first = Eric | authorlink = Eric Gans | title = Moral Heroism | journal = Anthropoetics | volume = 237 | date = June 9, 2001 | url = http://www.anthropoetics.ucla.edu/views/vw237.htm | accessdate = {{date|2011-06-17|mdy}}}}</ref> Gans has developed the notion of post-millennialism further in many of his internet ''Chronicles of Love and Resentment''<ref>{{Cite web | last = Gans | first = Eric | authorlink = Eric Gans | title = Chronicles of Love and Resentment | work = Anthropoetics | publisher = [[University of California, Los Angeles]] | date =  | url = http://www.anthropoetics.ucla.edu/views/Chronicles_home.cfm | accessdate = {{date|2011-06-17|mdy}} }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and the term is allied closely with his theory of [[generative anthropology]] and his scenic concept of history.<ref>For more on both see Gans, Eric: ''Originary Thinking: Elements of Generative Anthropology''. Stanford, California: Stanford University Press 1993.</ref>\n\n===Kirby's ''pseudo-modernism'' or ''digimodernism''===\nIn his 2006 paper ''[[The Death of Postmodernism and Beyond]]'', the British scholar Alan Kirby formulated a socio-cultural assessment of post-postmodernism that he calls \"pseudo-modernism\".<ref name=\"philosophynow\">{{Cite journal | last = Kirby | first = Alan | authorlink = Alan Kirby (writer)| title = The Death of Postmodernism And Beyond | journal = Philosophy Now | volume = | issue = 58 | date = November\u2013December 2006 | language =  | url = http://www.philosophynow.org/issue58/58kirby.htm | accessdate = {{date|2011-06-17|mdy}}}}</ref> Kirby associates pseudo-modernism with the triteness and shallowness resulting from the instantaneous, direct, and superficial participation in culture made possible by the internet, mobile phones, interactive television and similar means: \"In pseudo-modernism one phones, clicks, presses, surfs, chooses, moves, downloads.\"<ref name=\"philosophynow\" />\n\nPseudo-modernism's \"typical intellectual states\" are furthermore described as being \"ignorance, fanaticism and anxiety\" and it is said to produce a \"trance-like state\" in those participating in it. The net result of this media-induced shallowness and instantaneous participation in trivial events is a \"silent autism\" superseding \"the neurosis of modernism and the narcissism of postmodernism.\" Kirby sees no aesthetically valuable works coming out of \"pseudo-modernism\". As examples of its triteness he cites reality TV, interactive news programs, \"the drivel found ... on some [[Wikipedia]] pages\", docu-soaps, and the essayistic cinema of [[Michael Moore]] or [[Morgan Spurlock]].<ref name=\"philosophynow\"/> In a book published in September 2009 titled ''Digimodernism: How New Technologies Dismantle the Postmodern and Reconfigure our Culture'', Kirby developed further and nuanced his views on culture and textuality in the aftermath of [[postmodernism]].\n\n===Vermeulen and van den Akker's ''metamodernism''===\nIn 2010 the cultural theorists [[Timotheus Vermeulen]] and [[Robin van den Akker]] introduced the term [[metamodernism]] <ref name=\"journalofaestheticsandculture\">Vermeulen, Timotheus and Robin van den Akker. \"[http://aestheticsandculture.net/index.php/jac/article/view/5677/6304 Notes on metamodernism]\", ''Journal of Aesthetics and Culture'' 2010.</ref> as an intervention in the post-postmodernism debate. In their article \"Notes on Metamodernism\" they assert that the 2000s are characterized by the emergence of a sensibility that oscillates between, and must be situated beyond, modern positions and postmodern strategies. As examples of the metamodern sensibility Vermeulen and van den Akker cite the \"informed naivety\", \"pragmatic idealism\" and \"moderate fanaticism\" of the various cultural responses to, among others, climate change, the financial crisis, and (geo)political instability.\n\nThe prefix 'meta' here refers not to some reflective stance or repeated rumination, but to [[Plato]]'s ''[[metaxy]]'', which intends a movement between opposite poles as well as beyond.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metamodernism.com/2010/10/14/what-meta-means-and-does-not-mean/ | title=What meta means and does not mean}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Altermodern]]\n* [[Dogme 95]]\n* [[Excessivism]]\n* [[Integral theory (Ken Wilber)]]\n* [[Kitsch movement]]\n* [[Maximalism]]\n* [[Metamodernism]]\n* [[Neo-minimalism]]\n* [[New Puritans]]\n* [[New Sincerity]]\n* [[New Urbanism]]\n* [[Post-irony]]\n* [[Post-truth]]\n* [[Pseudorealism]]\n* [[Radical Orthodoxy]]\n* [[Remodernism]]\n* [[Stuckism]]\n* [[Transmodernism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|26em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://en.m.wiktionary.org/wiki/authenticism# Post-post-modernism known as Authenticism]\n*[http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=411731 Essay by Alan Kirby on theories of post-postmodernism]\n*[http://www.focusing.org/apm_papers/epstein.html Essay by Mikhail Epstein on The Place of Postmodernism in Postmodernity]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130810001724/http://alanfkirby.com/Introduction.pdf Introduction to \"Digimodernism: How New Technologies Dismantle the Postmodern and Reconfigure Our Culture\" by Alan Kirby]\n*[http://www.prlog.org/10814800-patrick-jf-queres-new-novel-grognard-now-available-at-major-booksellers.html Post-postmodern novel by Patrick J. F. Quere]\n*[http://aestheticsandculture.net/index.php/jac/article/viewArticle/5677 notes on metamodernism]\n*[http://www.performatism.de Performatism.de (Resource site for performatism and theories of post-postmodernism)]\n\n{{Criticism of postmodernism}}\n\n[[Category:Metamodernism|*]]\n[[Category:Theories of aesthetics]]\n[[Category:Architectural theory]]\n[[Category:Visual arts genres]]\n[[Category:Contemporary art]]\n[[Category:Contemporary philosophy]]\n[[Category:Critical theory]]\n[[Category:Criticism of postmodernism]]\n[[Category:Modernism]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture]]\n[[Category:New Urbanism]]\n[[Category:Postmodernism]]\n[[Category:Postmodern architecture]]\n[[Category:21st century in the arts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Postmodernism}}\n{{short description|Artistic and philosophical movement}}\n'''Post-postmodernism''' is a wide-ranging set of developments in [[critical theory]], [[philosophy]], [[architecture]], [[art]], [[literature]], and [[culture]] which are emerging from and reacting to [[postmodernism]]. Another similar recent term is [[metamodernism]].\n\n==Periodization==\nMost scholars would agree that [[modernism]] began around 1900 and continued on as the dominant cultural force in the intellectual circles of Western culture well into the mid-twentieth century.<ref>Compare, for example:<br />{{cite book|last=Childs|first=Peter|title=Modernism|publisher=[[Routledge]]|location=New York|year=2008|isbn=978-0-415-41544-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-v8SXB4l7kcC|page=18}}: \"[modernism] is [...] primarily located in the years 1890-1930 [...]\"<br />{{cite book|last=Armstrong|first=Tim|title=Modernism: A Cultural History|publisher=[[Polity Press]]|location=Cambridge|year=2005|isbn=978-0-7456-2983-4|url=https://archive.org/details/modernismcultura0000arms|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/modernismcultura0000arms/page/24 24]|quote=[modernism] can be defined as a series of international artistic movements in the period 1900-40 [...].}}</ref> Like all eras, modernism encompasses many competing individual directions and is impossible to define as a discrete unity or totality. However, its chief general characteristics are often thought to include an emphasis on \"radical aesthetics, technical experimentation, spatial or rhythmic, rather than chronological form, [and] self-conscious reflexiveness\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Childs|first=Peter|title=Modernism|publisher=[[Routledge]]|location=New York|year=2008|isbn=978-0-415-41544-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-v8SXB4l7kcC|page=18}}</ref> as well as the search for authenticity in human relations, abstraction in art, and utopian striving. These characteristics are normally lacking in postmodernism or are treated as objects of irony.\n\n[[Postmodernism]] arose after World War II as a reaction to the perceived failings of modernism, whose radical artistic projects had come to be associated with [[totalitarianism]]<ref>Cf. Groys, Boris: ''The Total Art of Stalinism'', Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1992.</ref> or had been assimilated into mainstream culture. The basic features of what we now call postmodernism can be found as early as the 1940s, most notably in the work of [[Jorge Luis Borges]].<ref>See Barth, John: \u201c[[The Literature of Exhaustion]].\u201d ''The Atlantic Monthly'', August 1967, pp. 29-34.</ref> However, most scholars today would agree that postmodernism began to compete with modernism in the late 1950s and gained ascendancy over it in the 1960s.<ref>Cf., for example, Huyssen, Andreas: ''After the Great Divide. Modernism, Mass Culture, Postmodernism''. Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 1986, p. 188.</ref> Since then, postmodernism has been a dominant, though not undisputed, force in art, literature, film, music, drama, architecture, history, and continental philosophy. Salient features of postmodernism are normally thought to include the ironic play with styles, citations and narrative levels,<ref>See Hutcheon, Linda: ''A Poetics of Postmodernism. History, Theory, Fiction''. New York: Routledge, 1988, pp. 3-21; McHale, Brian: ''Postmodern Fiction'', London: Methuen, 1987.</ref> a metaphysical skepticism or [[nihilism]] towards a \"[[grand narrative]]\" of  Western culture,<ref>See Lyotard, Jean-Fran\u00e7ois, ''The Postmodern Condition: A Report on Knowledge'', Minneapolis: University of Minneapolis Press 1984</ref> a preference for the virtual at the expense of the real (or more accurately, a fundamental questioning of what 'the real' constitutes)<ref>See Baudrillard, Jean: \u201c[[Simulacra and Simulation]]s.\u201d In: ''Jean Baudrillard. Selected Writings''. Stanford: Stanford University Press 1988, pp. 166-184.</ref> and a \"waning of affect\"<ref>Jameson, Fredric: ''Postmodernism or, The Cultural Logic of Late Capitalism''. Durham: Duke University Press 1991, p. 16</ref> on the part of the subject, who is caught up in the free interplay of virtual, endlessly reproducible signs inducing a state of consciousness similar to schizophrenia.<ref>Jameson, Fredric: ''Postmodernism or, The Cultural Logic of Late Capitalism''. Durham: Duke University Press 1991, pp. 26-27.</ref>\n\nSince the late 1990s there has been a small but growing feeling both in popular culture and in academia that postmodernism \"has gone out of fashion.\"<ref>Potter, Garry and Lopez, Jose (eds.): ''After Postmodernism: An Introduction to Critical Realism''. London: The Athlone Press 2001, p. 4.</ref> However, there have been few formal attempts to define and name the era succeeding postmodernism, and none of the proposed designations has yet become part of mainstream usage.\n\nHowever, post-postmodernism in literature began with the publication of [[Bangladeshi]] poet [[Md. Ziaul Haque]]'s book of 'poetenry' (poems of ten lines) titled, ''Give Me a Sky to Fly'' in 2014.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Kabir Chowdhury | first = Fahmida | authorlink = Fahmida Kabir Chowdhury | title = Md. Ziaul Haque's ''Give Me a Sky to Fly'': The Beginning of Post-postmodernism in Literature | journal = International Journal of Humanities and Social Science Invention | volume = 3 | date = February, 2014 | url = http://www.ijhssi.org/papers/v3(2)/Version-3/A032301011.pdf | accessdate = {{date|2020-04-16|mdy}}}}</ref>\n\n==Definitions==\nConsensus on what constitutes an era can not be easily achieved while that era is still in its early stages. However, a common theme of current attempts to define post-postmodernism is emerging as one where faith, trust, dialogue, performance, and sincerity can work to transcend postmodern [[irony]]. The following definitions, which vary widely in depth, focus, and scope, are listed in the chronological order of their appearance.\n\n===Turner's ''post-postmodernism''===\nIn 1995, the landscape architect and urban planner [[Tom Turner]] issued a book-length call for a post-postmodern turn in urban planning.<ref>''City as Landscape: A Post Post-modern View of Design and Planning'', (Taylor & Francis: London 1995).</ref> Turner criticizes the postmodern credo of \"anything goes\" and suggests that \u201cthe built environment professions are witnessing the gradual dawn of a post-Postmodernism that seeks to temper reason with faith.\u201d<ref>''City as Landscape: A Post Post-modern View of Design and Planning'', (Taylor & Francis: London 1995), p. 9.</ref> In particular, Turner argues for the use of timeless organic and geometrical patterns in urban planning. As sources of such patterns he cites, among others, the Taoist-influenced work of the American architect [[Christopher Alexander]], [[gestalt psychology]]  and the [[Psychoanalysis|psychoanalyst]] [[Carl Jung]]'s concept of [[Jungian archetypes|archetypes]]. Regarding terminology, Turner urges us to \"embrace post-Postmodernism \u2013 and pray for a better name.\"<ref>''City as Landscape: A Post Post-modern View of Design and Planning'', (Taylor & Francis: London 1995), p. 10; see also a summary of the book at [http://www.gardenvisit.com/history_theory/library_online_ebooks/architecture_city_as_landscape]</ref>\n\n===Epstein's ''trans-postmodernism''===\nIn his 1999 book on [[Russian postmodernism]] the Russian-American Slavist [[Mikhail Epstein]] suggested that postmodernism  \"is ... part of a much larger historical formation,\" which he calls \"[[postmodernity]]\".<ref>Epstein, Mikhail; Genis, Alexander; Vladiv-Glover, Slobodanka. ''Russian Postmodernism. New Perspectives on Post-Soviet Culture''. Berghahn Books: New York, 1999, p. 467.</ref> Epstein believes that postmodernist aesthetics will eventually become entirely conventional and provide the foundation for a new, non-ironic kind of poetry, which he describes using the prefix \"[[:wikt:trans-|trans-]]\":\n{{quote|In considering the names that might possibly be used to designate the new era following \"postmodernism,\" one finds that the prefix \"trans\" stands out in a special way. The last third of the 20th century developed under the sign of \"post,\" which signalled the demise of such concepts of modernity as \"truth\" and \"objectivity,\" \"soul\" and \"subjectivity,\" \"utopia\" and \"ideality,\" \"primary origin\" and \"originality,\" \"sincerity\" and \"sentimentality.\" All of these concepts are now being reborn in the form of \"trans-subjectivity,\" \"trans-idealism,\" \"trans-utopianism,\" \"trans-originality,\" \"trans-lyricism,\" \"trans-sentimentality\" etc.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.focusing.org/apm_papers/epstein.html | title=Epstein (specific) - the Place of Postmodernism in Postmodernity}}</ref>}} As an example Epstein cites the work of the contemporary Russian poet [[Timur Kibirov]].<ref>Epstein, Mikhail; Genis, Alexander; Vladiv-Glover, Slobodanka. ''Russian Postmodernism. New Perspectives on Post-Soviet Culture''. Berghahn Books: New York, 1999, pp. 457-460</ref>\n\n===Gans' ''post-millennialism''===\nThe term ''post-millennialism'' was introduced in 2000 by the American cultural theorist [[Eric Gans]]<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Gans | first = Eric | authorlink = Eric Gans | title = The Post-Millennial Age | journal = Anthropoetics | volume = 209 | date = June 3, 2000 | url = http://www.anthropoetics.ucla.edu/views/vw209/ | accessdate = {{date|2011-06-17|mdy}}}}</ref> to describe the era after postmodernism in ethical and socio-political terms. Gans associates postmodernism closely with \"victimary thinking,\" which he defines as being based on a non-negotiable ethical opposition between perpetrators and victims arising out of the experience of [[Auschwitz]] and [[Hiroshima]]. In Gans's view, the ethics of postmodernism is derived from identifying with the peripheral victim and disdaining the utopian center occupied by the perpetrator. Postmodernism in this sense is marked by a victimary politics that is productive in its opposition to modernist utopianism and totalitarianism but unproductive in its resentment of capitalism and liberal democracy, which he sees as the long-term agents of global reconciliation. In contrast to postmodernism, post-millennialism is distinguished by the rejection of victimary thinking and a turn to \"non-victimary dialogue\"<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Gans | first = Eric | authorlink = Eric Gans | title = Victimary Thinking Forever? | journal = Anthropoetics | volume = 230 | date = March 31, 2001 | url = http://www.anthropoetics.ucla.edu/views/vw230.htm | accessdate = {{date|2011-06-17|mdy}}}}</ref> that will \"diminish ... the amount of resentment in the world.\"<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Gans | first = Eric | authorlink = Eric Gans | title = Moral Heroism | journal = Anthropoetics | volume = 237 | date = June 9, 2001 | url = http://www.anthropoetics.ucla.edu/views/vw237.htm | accessdate = {{date|2011-06-17|mdy}}}}</ref> Gans has developed the notion of post-millennialism further in many of his internet ''Chronicles of Love and Resentment''<ref>{{Cite web | last = Gans | first = Eric | authorlink = Eric Gans | title = Chronicles of Love and Resentment | work = Anthropoetics | publisher = [[University of California, Los Angeles]] | date =  | url = http://www.anthropoetics.ucla.edu/views/Chronicles_home.cfm | accessdate = {{date|2011-06-17|mdy}} }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and the term is allied closely with his theory of [[generative anthropology]] and his scenic concept of history.<ref>For more on both see Gans, Eric: ''Originary Thinking: Elements of Generative Anthropology''. Stanford, California: Stanford University Press 1993.</ref>\n\n===Kirby's ''pseudo-modernism'' or ''digimodernism''===\nIn his 2006 paper ''[[The Death of Postmodernism and Beyond]]'', the British scholar Alan Kirby formulated a socio-cultural assessment of post-postmodernism that he calls \"pseudo-modernism\".<ref name=\"philosophynow\">{{Cite journal | last = Kirby | first = Alan | authorlink = Alan Kirby (writer)| title = The Death of Postmodernism And Beyond | journal = Philosophy Now | volume = | issue = 58 | date = November\u2013December 2006 | language =  | url = http://www.philosophynow.org/issue58/58kirby.htm | accessdate = {{date|2011-06-17|mdy}}}}</ref> Kirby associates pseudo-modernism with the triteness and shallowness resulting from the instantaneous, direct, and superficial participation in culture made possible by the internet, mobile phones, interactive television and similar means: \"In pseudo-modernism one phones, clicks, presses, surfs, chooses, moves, downloads.\"<ref name=\"philosophynow\" />\n\nPseudo-modernism's \"typical intellectual states\" are furthermore described as being \"ignorance, fanaticism and anxiety\" and it is said to produce a \"trance-like state\" in those participating in it. The net result of this media-induced shallowness and instantaneous participation in trivial events is a \"silent autism\" superseding \"the neurosis of modernism and the narcissism of postmodernism.\" Kirby sees no aesthetically valuable works coming out of \"pseudo-modernism\". As examples of its triteness he cites reality TV, interactive news programs, \"the drivel found ... on some [[Wikipedia]] pages\", docu-soaps, and the essayistic cinema of [[Michael Moore]] or [[Morgan Spurlock]].<ref name=\"philosophynow\"/> In a book published in September 2009 titled ''Digimodernism: How New Technologies Dismantle the Postmodern and Reconfigure our Culture'', Kirby developed further and nuanced his views on culture and textuality in the aftermath of [[postmodernism]].\n\n===Vermeulen and van den Akker's ''metamodernism''===\nIn 2010 the cultural theorists [[Timotheus Vermeulen]] and [[Robin van den Akker]] introduced the term [[metamodernism]] <ref name=\"journalofaestheticsandculture\">Vermeulen, Timotheus and Robin van den Akker. \"[http://aestheticsandculture.net/index.php/jac/article/view/5677/6304 Notes on metamodernism]\", ''Journal of Aesthetics and Culture'' 2010.</ref> as an intervention in the post-postmodernism debate. In their article \"Notes on Metamodernism\" they assert that the 2000s are characterized by the emergence of a sensibility that oscillates between, and must be situated beyond, modern positions and postmodern strategies. As examples of the metamodern sensibility Vermeulen and van den Akker cite the \"informed naivety\", \"pragmatic idealism\" and \"moderate fanaticism\" of the various cultural responses to, among others, climate change, the financial crisis, and (geo)political instability.\n\nThe prefix 'meta' here refers not to some reflective stance or repeated rumination, but to [[Plato]]'s ''[[metaxy]]'', which intends a movement between opposite poles as well as beyond.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metamodernism.com/2010/10/14/what-meta-means-and-does-not-mean/ | title=What meta means and does not mean}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Altermodern]]\n* [[Dogme 95]]\n* [[Excessivism]]\n* [[Integral theory (Ken Wilber)]]\n* [[Kitsch movement]]\n* [[Maximalism]]\n* [[Metamodernism]]\n* [[Neo-minimalism]]\n* [[New Puritans]]\n* [[New Sincerity]]\n* [[New Urbanism]]\n* [[Post-irony]]\n* [[Post-truth]]\n* [[Pseudorealism]]\n* [[Radical Orthodoxy]]\n* [[Remodernism]]\n* [[Stuckism]]\n* [[Transmodernism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|26em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://en.m.wiktionary.org/wiki/authenticism# Post-post-modernism known as Authenticism]\n*[http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=411731 Essay by Alan Kirby on theories of post-postmodernism]\n*[http://www.focusing.org/apm_papers/epstein.html Essay by Mikhail Epstein on The Place of Postmodernism in Postmodernity]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130810001724/http://alanfkirby.com/Introduction.pdf Introduction to \"Digimodernism: How New Technologies Dismantle the Postmodern and Reconfigure Our Culture\" by Alan Kirby]\n*[http://www.prlog.org/10814800-patrick-jf-queres-new-novel-grognard-now-available-at-major-booksellers.html Post-postmodern novel by Patrick J. F. Quere]\n*[http://aestheticsandculture.net/index.php/jac/article/viewArticle/5677 notes on metamodernism]\n*[http://www.performatism.de Performatism.de (Resource site for performatism and theories of post-postmodernism)]\n\n{{Criticism of postmodernism}}\n\n[[Category:Metamodernism|*]]\n[[Category:Theories of aesthetics]]\n[[Category:Architectural theory]]\n[[Category:Visual arts genres]]\n[[Category:Contemporary art]]\n[[Category:Contemporary philosophy]]\n[[Category:Critical theory]]\n[[Category:Criticism of postmodernism]]\n[[Category:Modernism]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture]]\n[[Category:New Urbanism]]\n[[Category:Postmodernism]]\n[[Category:Postmodern architecture]]\n[[Category:21st century in the arts]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Remove comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Post-postmodernism"}
